WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.600
[Amit Varma]: What were our maharajas like?

00:00:06.600 --> 00:00:08.840
[Amit Varma]: That's actually a silly question to ask.

00:00:08.840 --> 00:00:10.760
[Amit Varma]: Because maharajas were people too.

00:00:10.760 --> 00:00:12.760
[Amit Varma]: And people contain multitudes.

00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:16.840
[Amit Varma]: Back in the days of our military states, we had maharajas who were Sanskrit scholars.

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:19.520
[Amit Varma]: We had maharajas who were drunk in the salute all the time.

00:00:19.520 --> 00:00:23.380
[Amit Varma]: We had maharajas who were great sportsmen and also shitty sportsmen.

00:00:23.380 --> 00:00:25.760
[Amit Varma]: Some maharajas were doctors in practice medicine.

00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:30.040
[Amit Varma]: And there was even one who allegedly liked to fornicate with his elephant.

00:00:30.040 --> 00:00:31.640
[Amit Varma]: Jumbo my darling.

00:00:31.640 --> 00:00:36.160
[Amit Varma]: And yet, where there are multitudes, there must also be simplistic narratives.

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:40.520
[Amit Varma]: And interestingly, the most common simplistic narrative about the maharajas was one propagated

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:44.760
[Amit Varma]: by both the British Empire and their enemies, the Freedom Fighters of India, led by the

00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:45.760
[Amit Varma]: Congress.

00:00:45.760 --> 00:00:50.920
[Amit Varma]: For the British, the maharajas were a bunch of ridiculous feudal autocrats incapable of

00:00:50.920 --> 00:00:52.460
[Amit Varma]: governing wisely.

00:00:52.460 --> 00:00:54.320
[Amit Varma]: So the British had to do it for them.

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:59.160
[Amit Varma]: For the Freedom Fighters, the maharajas were, well, a bunch of ridiculous feudal autocrats

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:01.220
[Amit Varma]: incapable of governing wisely.

00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:04.720
[Amit Varma]: And so independent India had to be constructed without them.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:07.360
[Amit Varma]: This narrative suited both parties.

00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:10.280
[Amit Varma]: This narrative is false.

00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:17.880
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:17.880 --> 00:01:18.880
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:24.960
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:24.960 --> 00:01:26.320
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:30.880
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is a brilliant young historian, Manu Pillay, who has been on my show three

00:01:30.880 --> 00:01:32.160
[Amit Varma]: times before.

00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:35.960
[Amit Varma]: Each of those episodes were wildly popular, just like his books, and I'll link them from

00:01:35.960 --> 00:01:36.960
[Amit Varma]: the show notes.

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:42.440
[Amit Varma]: His latest book is called False Allies, India's Maharajas in the Age of Ravi Verma, and focuses

00:01:42.440 --> 00:01:48.400
[Amit Varma]: on busting simple stereotypes around our maharajas with powerful storytelling centered around

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:53.440
[Amit Varma]: the princely states of Travancore, Pudukottai, Baroda, Mysore, and Mewar.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:57.560
[Amit Varma]: Indeed, Manu's books should be a model for how to write history because of the way they

00:01:57.560 --> 00:02:00.480
[Amit Varma]: combine gripping storytelling with rigorous research.

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:04.440
[Amit Varma]: When I first recorded with him for The Seen and The Unseen, I compared his book Rebel

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:07.040
[Amit Varma]: Sultans to The Game of Thrones.

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:08.880
[Amit Varma]: That's how much fun he is to read.

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:11.680
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, that's how much bloodshed there is in the book as well.

00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:17.240
[Amit Varma]: And 30% of each book of his consists of extensive footnotes and endnotes, which speaks to the

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:22.040
[Amit Varma]: depth of his research and offers us so many rabbit holes to explore.

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:23.920
[Amit Varma]: So let's move on to this conversation now.

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:27.480
[Amit Varma]: But before we begin, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:27.480 --> 00:02:30.720
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer but never quite gotten down to it?

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:32.200
[Amit Varma]: Well, I'd love to help you.

00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:36.300
[Amit Varma]: Over the last year, I've enjoyed teaching my online course, The Art of Clear Writing,

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:39.720
[Amit Varma]: and an online community has now sprung up of all my past students.

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:43.800
[Amit Varma]: We have workshops, a newsletter to showcase the work of students, and vibrant community

00:02:43.800 --> 00:02:46.560
[Amit Varma]: interaction with much stimulation.

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:51.200
[Amit Varma]: In the course itself, through four webinars spread over four weekends, I share all I know

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:53.840
[Amit Varma]: about the craft and practice of clear writing.

00:02:53.840 --> 00:02:58.440
[Amit Varma]: There are many exercises, much interaction, and a lovely and lively community at the end

00:02:58.440 --> 00:02:59.440
[Amit Varma]: of it.

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:03.240
[Amit Varma]: The course costs rupees 10,000 plus GST, or about $150.

00:03:03.240 --> 00:03:06.840
[Amit Varma]: And the October classes begin on the 9th of October.

00:03:06.840 --> 00:03:12.200
[Amit Varma]: So if you're interested, head on over to register at indiancut.com slash clear writing.

00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:14.800
[Amit Varma]: That's indiancut.com slash clear writing.

00:03:14.800 --> 00:03:19.680
[Amit Varma]: Being a good writer does not require God-given talent, just the willingness to work hard

00:03:19.680 --> 00:03:23.920
[Amit Varma]: and a clear idea of what you need to do to refine your skills.

00:03:23.920 --> 00:03:25.920
[Amit Varma]: I can help you.

00:03:25.920 --> 00:03:28.560
[Amit Varma]: Manu, welcome back to The Scene and The Unseen.

00:03:28.560 --> 00:03:30.720
[Amit Varma]: Pleasure being here, I think the fourth time.

00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:34.440
[Amit Varma]: It is indeed the fourth time and you said something delightful as you stepped into my

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:35.440
[Amit Varma]: house.

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:39.200
[Amit Varma]: In fact, this is the first episode we're recording in my little makeshift home studio, which

00:03:39.200 --> 00:03:43.080
[Amit Varma]: I intend to get properly sound treated, but listeners do give feedback on what you feel

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:47.320
[Amit Varma]: about the sound of this because remote recording sounds aren't always the best.

00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:51.640
[Amit Varma]: So I just thought rather than try to kind of book a studio every time, it's convenient

00:03:51.640 --> 00:03:53.280
[Amit Varma]: to have a studio at home.

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:57.720
[Amit Varma]: But as Manu entered my home, he said that he has a distinction of doing the first longest

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:02.360
[Amit Varma]: episode with me, which basically meant that one of the episodes we did, and I forget which

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:06.000
[Amit Varma]: one, and they were all wildly popular, was the longest at the time.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:11.120
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of my readers, I think it was a good Sudhir Sarnobat, did this interactive

00:04:11.120 --> 00:04:12.120
[Amit Varma]: chart on Twitter.

00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:17.320
[Amit Varma]: Do you see that now where essentially it was a map of all my episodes and how the length

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:18.320
[Amit Varma]: went up.

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:19.320
[Amit Varma]: I see.

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:20.480
[Amit Varma]: So it just kept on going up.

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:24.560
[Amit Varma]: And of course, I reached four hours, 59 minutes in episode 200.

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:30.080
[Amit Varma]: But that's kind of cheating because I was a guest there with people like you kindly

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:31.080
[Amit Varma]: asking questions.

00:04:31.080 --> 00:04:35.640
[Amit Varma]: But apart from that one special episode, I've hit four hours a couple of times, I think

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:36.640
[Amit Varma]: so.

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:40.080
[Amit Varma]: But the thing that we haven't really done in the three episodes that we've done, which

00:04:40.080 --> 00:04:45.840
[Amit Varma]: we haven't really covered, is something that I try to do now in all the episodes I do,

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:49.600
[Amit Varma]: which is talk about your kind of personal life and get to know you a little better by

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:50.600
[Amit Varma]: personal life.

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:51.600
[Amit Varma]: I don't mean personal life.

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:52.680
[Amit Varma]: I mean, your history kind of.

00:04:52.680 --> 00:04:57.280
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about, you know, where you grew up, what kind of kid you were, and

00:04:57.280 --> 00:04:58.280
[Amit Varma]: so on.

00:04:58.280 --> 00:04:59.280
[Guest]: We can start there.

00:04:59.280 --> 00:05:00.280
[Guest]: I grew up in Pune.

00:05:00.280 --> 00:05:02.640
[Guest]: I was born in Kerala, but I grew up in Pune.

00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:07.240
[Guest]: I was the kind of kid who got into, I mean, it's not something that comes across to people

00:05:07.240 --> 00:05:12.000
[Guest]: anymore because now I look very dignified and proper, but in those days I was up to

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:13.440
[Guest]: very strange things.

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:17.480
[Guest]: I used to throw myself down staircases, try and jump out of the balcony.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:19.440
[Guest]: I set my house on fire once.

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:23.200
[Guest]: I used to have these hot wheel cars, which I used to drench in deodorant and set them

00:05:23.200 --> 00:05:27.000
[Guest]: on fire and then watch them zoom around while they were lit.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:32.560
[Guest]: So it was not a very ordinary childhood in terms of my personal leanings and inclinations.

00:05:32.560 --> 00:05:33.560
[Guest]: It was a lot of fun.

00:05:33.560 --> 00:05:37.560
[Guest]: I was a social child, very happy, running around, you know, plenty of friends and things

00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:39.240
[Guest]: like that.

00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:41.400
[Guest]: Reading happened when I was about 11 or 12.

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:44.960
[Guest]: That's when my sister, basically to calm me down, thrust a book into my hand and said

00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:45.960
[Guest]: read.

00:05:45.960 --> 00:05:49.400
[Guest]: And it started with the comics and then slowly graduated to other books.

00:05:49.400 --> 00:05:51.960
[Guest]: I remember writing an essay for my school newspaper.

00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:56.240
[Guest]: I don't think it got published, about when I read David Copperfield for the first time.

00:05:56.240 --> 00:06:00.520
[Guest]: It was my first long book, 600 pages, I think, the unabridged version.

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:03.280
[Guest]: And it felt like an achievement because I was 12 or 13.

00:06:03.280 --> 00:06:06.920
[Guest]: And then from there, you know, I took an interest in reading, took an interest in history and

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:09.200
[Guest]: you know, eventually ended up writing.

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:12.720
[Guest]: The writing initially used to be, you know, funny little skits for school.

00:06:12.720 --> 00:06:16.640
[Guest]: I remember writing a funny poem about my bench partner in school.

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:17.640
[Guest]: It wasn't rude.

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:21.720
[Guest]: It was sort of a comical account describing her and she obviously didn't like it.

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:22.720
[Guest]: She tore it.

00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:26.760
[Guest]: But yeah, I was, you know, I had a good childhood in that sense.

00:06:26.760 --> 00:06:27.760
[Amit Varma]: Nothing to complain about.

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:28.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:06:28.760 --> 00:06:32.160
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I remember an anecdote you told me about your childhood, but it was I think not

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:33.160
[Amit Varma]: on the record.

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:37.240
[Amit Varma]: It was off the record, where when you were 16, you took a rat or something and you held

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:39.240
[Amit Varma]: it in a bucket to see if it would drown.

00:06:39.240 --> 00:06:40.240
[Amit Varma]: And it did.

00:06:40.240 --> 00:06:41.240
[Guest]: Is that true?

00:06:41.240 --> 00:06:42.240
[Guest]: Yes, that was.

00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:43.240
[Guest]: It wasn't when I was 16.

00:06:43.240 --> 00:06:44.240
[Guest]: I was a little younger than that.

00:06:44.240 --> 00:06:45.240
[Guest]: Maybe 13, 14.

00:06:45.240 --> 00:06:46.720
[Guest]: And you know, my grandfather caught the rat.

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:50.880
[Guest]: This was in his house in Kerala, old houses, they've got plenty of mice and things running

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:51.880
[Guest]: around.

00:06:51.880 --> 00:06:54.120
[Guest]: And he caught it in a little, almost like a cage.

00:06:54.120 --> 00:06:55.120
[Guest]: The trap was like a cage.

00:06:55.120 --> 00:06:57.760
[Guest]: And he said, go release it outside.

00:06:57.760 --> 00:07:00.680
[Guest]: But then somewhere I had heard something about a bucket and something.

00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:04.840
[Guest]: So I decided to try and see if I could, you know, conduct this experiment where I sort

00:07:04.840 --> 00:07:06.480
[Guest]: of drowned the rat.

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:09.520
[Guest]: And it was not very pleasant afterwards.

00:07:09.520 --> 00:07:10.520
[Guest]: It did die.

00:07:10.520 --> 00:07:14.200
[Guest]: And you know, it felt, it's very strange at the age of 13, that kind of power over another

00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:15.200
[Guest]: creature.

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:19.120
[Guest]: It's a, I wouldn't say it's intoxicating, but it was different.

00:07:19.120 --> 00:07:20.760
[Guest]: You could feel that power.

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:22.280
[Guest]: And I felt very bad afterwards.

00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:25.120
[Guest]: The instant it died, I felt so guilty.

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:28.120
[Guest]: And then I turned vegetarian for seven years, because I thought that was the only way I

00:07:28.120 --> 00:07:30.480
[Guest]: could expiate my sin.

00:07:30.480 --> 00:07:34.280
[Guest]: But yeah, eventually, at the age of 21, I again started eating eggs and then slowly

00:07:34.280 --> 00:07:40.160
[Guest]: graduated to chicken occasionally and gave up my guilt about killing the poor animal.

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:44.040
[Guest]: But yeah, that was my homicidal thing at that time.

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:48.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I think Amitav Kumar wrote an essay once or a book about how in Bihar, a particular

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:51.160
[Amit Varma]: place to eat rats, to catch rats and eat them.

00:07:51.160 --> 00:07:55.120
[Amit Varma]: So when you said intoxicating, I thought it will set you down a very interesting path,

00:07:55.120 --> 00:07:56.120
[Amit Varma]: but it clearly...

00:07:56.120 --> 00:08:01.200
[Guest]: Well, one day, if I become a dictator, well, probably very dangerous thing, because clearly,

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:06.040
[Guest]: you know, imagine 13 year old and just having that kind of control over another living being,

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:07.040
[Guest]: it was scary.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:09.440
[Guest]: You know, now that I think of it, what was I thinking?

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:11.560
[Guest]: Was I some kind of crazy child?

00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:15.800
[Guest]: Anyway, the fact that I felt guilt immediately after, I think, can give me some relief that

00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:21.440
[Guest]: I wasn't completely out of that moral limit that we place on ourselves, which is, yeah,

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:24.000
[Guest]: which is, it's good to know that I have that moral limit.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, just just thinking of that impulse reminds me of this beautiful book by Ryu Murakami,

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.680
[Amit Varma]: the other Murakami, as it were, a book called Piercing, where the book begins with this

00:08:31.680 --> 00:08:35.600
[Amit Varma]: guy sleeping in a room with his wife and the babies in the crib.

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:41.880
[Amit Varma]: And he gets up and he has this uncontrollable desire to stab the baby.

00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:45.440
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, he doesn't actually want to do it because it's his baby, but he has this

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:47.080
[Amit Varma]: uncontrollable desire.

00:08:47.080 --> 00:08:50.920
[Amit Varma]: So and he knows that the only way to quench this, the only way he can save his baby is

00:08:50.920 --> 00:08:53.040
[Amit Varma]: by going out and killing someone else.

00:08:53.040 --> 00:08:54.200
[Amit Varma]: And that's the rest of the book.

00:08:54.200 --> 00:08:57.720
[Amit Varma]: So it's a it's a fabulous book and one of those things where you don't kind of need

00:08:57.720 --> 00:09:01.240
[Amit Varma]: to explain something, the impulse is just there and the way it unfolds so naturally

00:09:01.240 --> 00:09:03.520
[Amit Varma]: you feel, yeah, I mean, this is what could happen.

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:04.520
[Guest]: Human beings are weird.

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:09.320
[Guest]: We're such complicated, strange creatures, there's really no predicting how a human being

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:10.320
[Guest]: can behave.

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:12.840
[Guest]: There's, you know, only so much conditioning you can do.

00:09:12.840 --> 00:09:17.440
[Guest]: At the end of it, I think every human being is capable of sort of, you know, breaking

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:19.920
[Guest]: out of that and becoming something completely different.

00:09:19.920 --> 00:09:24.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, people often ask with astonishment that how come in Hitler's time so many ordinary

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:27.040
[Amit Varma]: Germans were kind of privy to that thing.

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:29.800
[Amit Varma]: Hannah Arendt used the phrase the banality of evil.

00:09:29.800 --> 00:09:34.920
[Amit Varma]: And without getting too much into current politics, I think we see that, you know, it's

00:09:34.920 --> 00:09:37.200
[Amit Varma]: not that unusual shit can happen.

00:09:37.200 --> 00:09:42.640
[Amit Varma]: So how did you then move towards like, did you have a fascination with history, particularly

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:43.640
[Amit Varma]: as a genre?

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:47.240
[Amit Varma]: Or was it just storytelling and history kind of fit into that?

00:09:47.240 --> 00:09:50.160
[Amit Varma]: Like was there a time when you started reading history, and after that, was there a time

00:09:50.160 --> 00:09:52.000
[Amit Varma]: when you said that I want to write history?

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.240
[Guest]: Well, it began, frankly, with just stories about my ancestors, I would hear from my grandmother.

00:09:56.240 --> 00:10:00.120
[Guest]: And it wasn't like these people, these were famous people or anything, it was just that

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:06.120
[Guest]: the way she related the doings of her uncles, her great uncles, her father, her mother,

00:10:06.120 --> 00:10:10.360
[Guest]: they didn't feel like great grandmother, great grandfather, they just felt like really funny,

00:10:10.360 --> 00:10:15.160
[Guest]: interesting people, you know, so to begin with just seeing older people in your family,

00:10:15.160 --> 00:10:21.080
[Guest]: not as relatives, not as these esteemed sort of, you know, older figures, but as individuals,

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:25.200
[Guest]: that was very special, and I started getting interested in the stories of people.

00:10:25.200 --> 00:10:28.680
[Guest]: So I would read a lot of biographies, I would read, and then that obviously is linked to

00:10:28.680 --> 00:10:32.120
[Guest]: history, because if you're reading about people long dead and gone, naturally, you know, you're

00:10:32.120 --> 00:10:34.160
[Guest]: going to pick up history books.

00:10:34.160 --> 00:10:35.360
[Guest]: From there, it sort of picked up.

00:10:35.360 --> 00:10:39.680
[Guest]: And then, you know, as we did that podcast on the ivory throne, I found that story at

00:10:39.680 --> 00:10:45.440
[Guest]: the age of 18, the story of this Queen, female Maharaja of Travancore, who sort of ends up

00:10:45.440 --> 00:10:49.920
[Guest]: lapsing into oblivion and dying as a nobody after having much power and money and all

00:10:49.920 --> 00:10:50.920
[Guest]: of that.

00:10:50.920 --> 00:10:54.220
[Guest]: And I thought, here's an interesting story, and I want to sort of peel back the layers.

00:10:54.220 --> 00:10:58.000
[Guest]: So it was part interest in the biography, but also in the history.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.280
[Guest]: And since then, history sort of, you know, become the main thing, but I still try and

00:11:01.280 --> 00:11:06.680
[Guest]: connect it often to the people who populate history, not in the sense necessarily of great

00:11:06.680 --> 00:11:12.280
[Guest]: men and great women, but trying to just understand history by looking at it through their eyes,

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:17.320
[Guest]: as opposed to in the abstract or in the context of economic trends and things like that.

00:11:17.320 --> 00:11:19.800
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, it was a it was a process.

00:11:19.800 --> 00:11:22.880
[Amit Varma]: And where did the bit about learning how to do history come from?

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:26.200
[Amit Varma]: Because it's one thing to have an interest in history to read a lot of history books

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:27.520
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth.

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:29.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, how do you get that discipline?

00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:32.680
[Amit Varma]: And you became a historian in a sense when you were very young, right?

00:11:32.680 --> 00:11:37.840
[Amit Varma]: The Throne was written when you were what, 11, 12, finished when I was 25, yes, when

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:38.960
[Amit Varma]: you were 25.

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:43.080
[Amit Varma]: So what's that kind of daunting or did it help that you were too young to know better?

00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:44.640
[Amit Varma]: And you just kind of dived into it?

00:11:44.640 --> 00:11:47.000
[Amit Varma]: How did you learn that bit of doing history?

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:50.960
[Guest]: I think, you know, nobody was there to guide me at that time, I was doing it entirely privately,

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:53.240
[Guest]: I was managing jobs, etc.

00:11:53.240 --> 00:11:56.360
[Guest]: But the thing is, I took to the archives like a duck to water.

00:11:56.360 --> 00:12:00.560
[Guest]: For some reason, it I love the space, I love the silence, I love touching files that were

00:12:00.560 --> 00:12:03.480
[Guest]: so old, that nobody had touched before.

00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:07.160
[Guest]: And then I think I just formed an aptitude and, you know, managing that kind of primary

00:12:07.160 --> 00:12:11.960
[Guest]: material, interpreting it, reading academic material that helps you interpret it.

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:15.560
[Guest]: And then you pick up the skills and then you slowly realize that yeah, this is what historians

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:16.600
[Guest]: do as well.

00:12:16.600 --> 00:12:19.520
[Guest]: Which is why, you know, Shashi Tharoor once told me that when he read my book, he said

00:12:19.520 --> 00:12:20.840
[Guest]: this could have been your PhD thesis.

00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:24.280
[Guest]: And I said, yes, this always happens, I write a book and then realize that I could have

00:12:24.280 --> 00:12:27.480
[Guest]: just done this as a PhD thesis instead of a private book.

00:12:27.480 --> 00:12:32.240
[Guest]: Now I'm doing a PhD separately, which is nothing connected to any of these books I've written.

00:12:32.240 --> 00:12:35.360
[Guest]: But you know, it's just, it's a habit I picked up.

00:12:35.360 --> 00:12:39.140
[Guest]: And since then, once I decided consciously that I wanted to stick to this, then obviously

00:12:39.140 --> 00:12:43.480
[Guest]: you start figuring out the methods properly, the rigor, the approaches you're supposed

00:12:43.480 --> 00:12:44.480
[Guest]: to take.

00:12:44.480 --> 00:12:47.640
[Guest]: And you consciously read up on the latest academic research just to make sure that you're

00:12:47.640 --> 00:12:51.400
[Guest]: on top of what is happening in the field more broadly.

00:12:51.400 --> 00:12:56.360
[Guest]: But yeah, the beginnings were almost by accident, you know, I had decided I wanted to do this

00:12:56.360 --> 00:12:58.680
[Guest]: book that became the ivory throne eventually.

00:12:58.680 --> 00:13:02.560
[Guest]: I decided I wanted to be in London and decided to go there for a master's so I could access

00:13:02.560 --> 00:13:03.640
[Guest]: the archives.

00:13:03.640 --> 00:13:05.760
[Guest]: And from there, it just took a life of its own.

00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:10.560
[Guest]: And habit just turned into, I mean, luckily, for all you know, you know, you often do find

00:13:10.560 --> 00:13:16.680
[Guest]: people who do history books without necessarily doing all the hard work that they should.

00:13:16.680 --> 00:13:19.600
[Guest]: So luckily for me, I would like to believe that that didn't happen.

00:13:19.600 --> 00:13:22.560
[Guest]: The six years that I took to write the book, I wasn't in a hurry.

00:13:22.560 --> 00:13:26.880
[Guest]: I ended up taking the time and I think giving myself that kind of time also meant that I

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:30.600
[Guest]: was growing up in the process, which meant I was also getting more mature about how I

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:34.200
[Guest]: was reading the same subject, reading the same materials and files again.

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:37.440
[Guest]: So you know, the drafts that were written when I was 22, very different from the drafts

00:13:37.440 --> 00:13:42.160
[Guest]: that were published at the age of 25, because much changed in that time.

00:13:42.160 --> 00:13:47.120
[Guest]: But I began not because of any academic guidance or a degree or any kind of official training.

00:13:47.120 --> 00:13:52.480
[Guest]: The training came after I'd already picked up a lot of the skills just in terms of streamlining

00:13:52.480 --> 00:13:54.160
[Amit Varma]: what I had.

00:13:54.160 --> 00:13:58.400
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you mentioned sort of doing a PhD, which, you know, you're doing one now

00:13:58.400 --> 00:13:59.840
[Amit Varma]: and I asked why.

00:13:59.840 --> 00:14:05.960
[Amit Varma]: And that leads me to sort of another question about, say, academic historians, and people

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:07.720
[Amit Varma]: who are not academic historians.

00:14:07.720 --> 00:14:12.040
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, you know, there is a certain amount of resentment among academic historians

00:14:12.040 --> 00:14:15.800
[Amit Varma]: of popular historians who haven't paid the dues, so to say, and I'm just going out there

00:14:15.800 --> 00:14:16.800
[Amit Varma]: and doing that.

00:14:16.800 --> 00:14:20.960
[Amit Varma]: But my question is not just about that, but something larger, which is about the relevance

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:23.760
[Amit Varma]: of a lot of academic paths that people take.

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:28.960
[Amit Varma]: Like what, for example, I can't fathom is that when you have written these acclaimed

00:14:28.960 --> 00:14:31.560
[Amit Varma]: books of history, why would you want to do a PhD?

00:14:31.560 --> 00:14:32.560
[Amit Varma]: What is the relevance?

00:14:32.560 --> 00:14:37.280
[Amit Varma]: I mean, okay, you know, within certain circles, it can still be considered, you know, a mark

00:14:37.280 --> 00:14:38.720
[Amit Varma]: of respect and all of that.

00:14:38.720 --> 00:14:43.000
[Amit Varma]: But you are a historian, you are a, you know, respected historian, no one criticizes your

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.880
[Amit Varma]: methods or anything like that, then why the PhD?

00:14:45.880 --> 00:14:51.800
[Amit Varma]: And also, what are the kind of trade offs, like what role does the whole academic discipline?

00:14:51.800 --> 00:14:55.520
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I know what role it has played for the decades, because you need history and

00:14:55.520 --> 00:14:56.960
[Amit Varma]: you need historians.

00:14:56.960 --> 00:15:03.240
[Amit Varma]: But going forward, where you don't have to depend on gatekeepers or degrees or whatever,

00:15:03.240 --> 00:15:07.280
[Amit Varma]: anyone can just get in there and do history if they are passionate about much like you

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:12.360
[Amit Varma]: did, you know, will the relevance or the role of academic historians change?

00:15:12.360 --> 00:15:18.520
[Amit Varma]: And I sort of ask this, because I think about this in other fields, for example, where academics

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:23.920
[Amit Varma]: is elapsing more and more into irrelevance, you know, many fields whenever relevant anyway,

00:15:23.920 --> 00:15:26.040
[Amit Varma]: history is very relevant and very important.

00:15:26.040 --> 00:15:28.240
[Amit Varma]: So what's your sort of thinking on this?

00:15:28.240 --> 00:15:29.240
[Amit Varma]: And why are you doing a PhD?

00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:33.360
[Guest]: Well, the you know, the whole question of resentment on the part of certain academic

00:15:33.360 --> 00:15:37.600
[Guest]: historians for popular historians, you know, that I don't think that exists that much in

00:15:37.600 --> 00:15:41.600
[Guest]: the West, because a lot of academic historians do write for popular presses and trade presses

00:15:41.600 --> 00:15:42.600
[Guest]: as well.

00:15:42.600 --> 00:15:46.640
[Guest]: The my favorite example I give in many places is Mary Beard, you know, she's a proper scholar,

00:15:46.640 --> 00:15:50.560
[Guest]: she's a very senior scholar, but she also wrote a book like SPQR, which is for a lay

00:15:50.560 --> 00:15:53.680
[Guest]: audience and they don't see it very much as an ego issue.

00:15:53.680 --> 00:15:56.920
[Guest]: Whereas I think in India, there's still some of that ego thing, which is that if you're

00:15:56.920 --> 00:16:01.520
[Guest]: an academic historian, you don't write in a way that can even remotely be called storytelling.

00:16:01.520 --> 00:16:06.080
[Guest]: You know, storytelling is a bad word, you're meant to use the jargon, etc.

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:07.080
[Guest]: And I have an allergy for that.

00:16:07.080 --> 00:16:08.080
[Guest]: I don't like jargon.

00:16:08.080 --> 00:16:11.040
[Guest]: I don't like words like epistemic, whatever that is.

00:16:11.040 --> 00:16:13.000
[Guest]: I can't even pronounce it properly.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:17.560
[Guest]: It's just not, it doesn't come to me naturally, because history to me feels like something

00:16:17.560 --> 00:16:19.360
[Guest]: you should take out into the world.

00:16:19.360 --> 00:16:24.600
[Guest]: You know, on the one hand, we complain that people are perverting history, misusing history.

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:28.580
[Guest]: But then if you're not going to make an effort to actually communicate good history in an

00:16:28.580 --> 00:16:33.280
[Guest]: accessible way to large numbers of people, you sort of lose the right to complain about

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:34.920
[Guest]: these other things that are happening.

00:16:34.920 --> 00:16:38.680
[Guest]: You can fill a gap with fake news because a gap exists, you know, whereas if you try

00:16:38.680 --> 00:16:43.940
[Guest]: and bridge the gap properly, then you know, it becomes a very different kind of game altogether.

00:16:43.940 --> 00:16:46.120
[Guest]: And you can be in a position of strength.

00:16:46.120 --> 00:16:50.520
[Guest]: So yeah, I mean, and I have no reason to complain, of course, the only resentment I've got from

00:16:50.520 --> 00:16:54.560
[Guest]: academic historians are from my contemporaries, not from senior historians.

00:16:54.560 --> 00:17:00.480
[Guest]: I've got glowing reviews in peer reviewed journals, I've got awards and things like

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:01.480
[Guest]: that.

00:17:01.480 --> 00:17:05.340
[Guest]: I've been invited to give lectures in fairly academic sort of settings.

00:17:05.340 --> 00:17:07.800
[Guest]: So none of that really worries me.

00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:11.680
[Guest]: But you know, PhD still, if you want to teach, for example, tomorrow, then it's useful to

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:12.740
[Guest]: have a PhD.

00:17:12.740 --> 00:17:16.320
[Guest]: Some pressure I will admit comes from my mother because my father never finished his PhD.

00:17:16.320 --> 00:17:20.560
[Guest]: So she's been quite determined that I should at least finish my PhD.

00:17:20.560 --> 00:17:24.860
[Guest]: So you know, some of it is also that, but it's just a thing you do.

00:17:24.860 --> 00:17:28.560
[Guest]: It's not my main thing, you know, I'm currently doing a PhD.

00:17:28.560 --> 00:17:30.800
[Guest]: But in the process, I've written two other books.

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:34.880
[Guest]: And as I said earlier, I could have easily made those my thesis if I wanted a shortcut

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:35.880
[Guest]: out.

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:39.880
[Guest]: But I didn't think of it that way, I didn't think of it strategically.

00:17:39.880 --> 00:17:41.520
[Guest]: This is just something I'm doing.

00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:46.120
[Guest]: And I think in some ways, you know, it does, I think having that kind of footing in academia

00:17:46.120 --> 00:17:49.240
[Guest]: does give you one strength, which is that you learn to theorize better.

00:17:49.240 --> 00:17:53.520
[Guest]: When I'm doing, for example, a narrative history, I'm not really contributing in terms of theory.

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:58.640
[Guest]: Whereas being in academia, you also have a certain pressure to come up not just with

00:17:58.640 --> 00:18:02.360
[Guest]: original research, but also theorize about a larger point, you know.

00:18:02.360 --> 00:18:06.760
[Guest]: So if it's Travancore, for example, it's not just about that incident, say theorize about

00:18:06.760 --> 00:18:11.000
[Guest]: kingship and the place of kingship, not just in Indian history, but also in contemporary

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:12.000
[Guest]: politics.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.480
[Guest]: So that kind of theorizing is something that you pick up in academia, and you don't feel

00:18:16.480 --> 00:18:21.060
[Guest]: any such need to do that for a regular audience, which I think is a useful skill, because it

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:26.440
[Guest]: gives you some kind of capacity to look at the bigger picture, you know, build a conceptual

00:18:26.440 --> 00:18:31.480
[Guest]: base that other people can then develop or argue with or sort of have a debate about,

00:18:31.480 --> 00:18:33.520
[Guest]: which is an interesting challenge in its own right.

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:37.800
[Guest]: That happens in a much smaller circle, it's not really for a large audience.

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:39.180
[Guest]: But you know, challenges are interesting.

00:18:39.180 --> 00:18:44.620
[Guest]: So I thought, let me just take this off the box, take it as it comes, enjoy the process

00:18:44.620 --> 00:18:46.960
[Guest]: while I'm also doing what I really want to do.

00:18:46.960 --> 00:18:51.120
[Guest]: And I'm one thing is sure that even if I do a thesis, I'm never going to publish it as

00:18:51.120 --> 00:18:52.280
[Guest]: an academic text.

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:53.280
[Guest]: That's not my thing.

00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:55.960
[Guest]: I never see myself doing that.

00:18:55.960 --> 00:18:58.560
[Amit Varma]: Do you think that that's a trap that academic historians can fall into?

00:18:58.560 --> 00:19:02.720
[Amit Varma]: Like you read a work of history then and, and notice it, notice that it's happening

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:06.360
[Amit Varma]: that there's a narrative that they've chosen or a particular ideological viewpoint that

00:19:06.360 --> 00:19:07.500
[Amit Varma]: they have to take.

00:19:07.500 --> 00:19:11.560
[Amit Varma]: And they've obviously got their own incentives at play within academia.

00:19:11.560 --> 00:19:16.440
[Amit Varma]: And they want to fit in there with their peers and, you know, often toe the party line, as

00:19:16.440 --> 00:19:17.440
[Amit Varma]: it were.

00:19:17.440 --> 00:19:20.640
[Amit Varma]: So do you feel that that affects the doing of history?

00:19:20.640 --> 00:19:26.960
[Amit Varma]: And that in some ways, is something that has kind of changed in modern times, where because

00:19:26.960 --> 00:19:31.320
[Amit Varma]: of technology, because of perhaps easier access, which I'll ask you about next, there are more

00:19:31.320 --> 00:19:34.680
[Amit Varma]: people just liberated to kind of do history.

00:19:34.680 --> 00:19:39.760
[Amit Varma]: So is there a problem like that with academic history and why is so much of academic history

00:19:39.760 --> 00:19:40.760
[Amit Varma]: kind of unreadable?

00:19:40.760 --> 00:19:44.740
[Guest]: Yeah, that's the thing, you know, two parts, I'll give the answer in two parts.

00:19:44.740 --> 00:19:48.280
[Guest]: The one thing is academics have their own politics, they have their own ego clashes,

00:19:48.280 --> 00:19:52.240
[Guest]: they have their own disputes and very human petty issues with each other.

00:19:52.240 --> 00:19:55.640
[Guest]: You know, sometimes it's masked behind a lot of jargon, but in reality, it can come down

00:19:55.640 --> 00:20:00.120
[Guest]: to very basic human resentments, it has nothing, like in any other profession, some people

00:20:00.120 --> 00:20:03.360
[Guest]: don't get along with each other, some people are resentful of somebody else's success in

00:20:03.360 --> 00:20:06.180
[Guest]: some seminar circuit, all of that exists.

00:20:06.180 --> 00:20:10.480
[Guest]: And yes, there is a pressure sometimes, for example, to come up with new original terms,

00:20:10.480 --> 00:20:14.640
[Guest]: you know, like a new original concept, like something that is pathbreaking, and everyone's

00:20:14.640 --> 00:20:18.680
[Guest]: trying to be pathbreaking, which is, demeans the whole point of being pathbreaking, if

00:20:18.680 --> 00:20:22.560
[Guest]: everyone's trying to do that everyone's trying to invent a new concept and a new definition

00:20:22.560 --> 00:20:27.200
[Guest]: and a new term, you know, contribute to the jargon rather than contribute to the subject

00:20:27.200 --> 00:20:28.760
[Guest]: that has its problems.

00:20:28.760 --> 00:20:34.440
[Guest]: So there is that in academia, I do agree, there is a certain amount of ideological hesitation

00:20:34.440 --> 00:20:40.120
[Guest]: in India sometimes, you know, I wrote an article on the Mapla rebellion for the Hindu, many

00:20:40.120 --> 00:20:44.640
[Guest]: people liked it, but many people said no, no, you can't highlight the religious element

00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:49.080
[Guest]: of that rebellion in 1921, because it will be used to victimize present day Muslims.

00:20:49.080 --> 00:20:53.600
[Guest]: Now, the thing is, I understand, and obviously, one doesn't like to contribute to that kind

00:20:53.600 --> 00:20:55.000
[Guest]: of victimization.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:59.200
[Guest]: But all the same, in the longer term, if you don't talk about it, you're again creating

00:20:59.200 --> 00:21:01.680
[Guest]: room for somebody else to misinterpret it.

00:21:01.680 --> 00:21:05.640
[Guest]: So a lot of historians will focus just on the economic aspect, they will focus just

00:21:05.640 --> 00:21:10.920
[Guest]: on the social aspect, they'll focus on landlordism, feudalism, but they will do everything possible

00:21:10.920 --> 00:21:12.640
[Guest]: to studiously avoid religion.

00:21:12.640 --> 00:21:17.020
[Guest]: I mean, don't avoid it, acknowledge that it's at least in the room, because there's plenty

00:21:17.020 --> 00:21:19.160
[Guest]: of evidence that that is the case.

00:21:19.160 --> 00:21:22.100
[Guest]: So the Mapla rebellion is the big event in 1921.

00:21:22.100 --> 00:21:26.200
[Guest]: But there were a series of smaller outrages through the 19th century.

00:21:26.200 --> 00:21:29.600
[Guest]: And you see that religion does play a role, because all of these people, when they go

00:21:29.600 --> 00:21:33.840
[Guest]: out and start the rebellion, there's a whole ritual, they dress in white, they go and take

00:21:33.840 --> 00:21:36.280
[Guest]: the blessings of a Muslim cleric.

00:21:36.280 --> 00:21:37.280
[Guest]: All of that happens.

00:21:37.280 --> 00:21:41.400
[Guest]: When they attack temples, for example, they festoon it and this is a quote, they festoon

00:21:41.400 --> 00:21:44.120
[Guest]: one in 1852 with the entrails of a cow.

00:21:44.120 --> 00:21:47.160
[Guest]: These things have a religious overtone as well.

00:21:47.160 --> 00:21:52.040
[Guest]: There may be economic motivations, that may be the main motivation, but the protest is

00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:55.440
[Guest]: articulated and justified through religious ideology.

00:21:55.440 --> 00:22:00.120
[Guest]: You stand up to the landlord who's treating you badly in an economic sense, but you justify

00:22:00.120 --> 00:22:02.160
[Guest]: standing up in religious language.

00:22:02.160 --> 00:22:03.960
[Guest]: So both are true.

00:22:03.960 --> 00:22:06.040
[Guest]: All of these elements are part of the same process.

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:10.120
[Guest]: But there is sometimes in India hesitation to highlight the religious.

00:22:10.120 --> 00:22:14.980
[Guest]: We all, to some extent, succumb to that because it comes so naturally, anything you read tries

00:22:14.980 --> 00:22:17.320
[Guest]: to studiously avoid the religious.

00:22:17.320 --> 00:22:21.280
[Guest]: So it's now taken me some time to peel back those layers, to start realizing that hold

00:22:21.280 --> 00:22:26.760
[Guest]: on, there's certain issues with this and we do need to acknowledge it.

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:32.080
[Guest]: We talk, for example, Kabir's poetry about Hindus and Muslims being one, but even in

00:22:32.080 --> 00:22:36.440
[Guest]: saying that they should be one, you're essentially acknowledging that there's some kind of difference

00:22:36.440 --> 00:22:37.440
[Guest]: between the two.

00:22:37.440 --> 00:22:40.280
[Guest]: You're aware that there is difference and you're trying to bridge it.

00:22:40.280 --> 00:22:43.160
[Guest]: So we have to be aware of that ourselves as well.

00:22:43.160 --> 00:22:47.040
[Guest]: We can't highlight just the uniting of the religions and forget that why is he trying

00:22:47.040 --> 00:22:48.420
[Guest]: to unite them in the first place?

00:22:48.420 --> 00:22:53.280
[Guest]: What is it that is causing him to sort of say, no, let's rise above this?

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:58.920
[Guest]: When we say that kings used religious vocabulary during times of war, true, and they would

00:22:58.920 --> 00:23:04.440
[Guest]: have had political reasons, just as politicians today mine religion for political purposes.

00:23:04.440 --> 00:23:08.520
[Guest]: But it also means that it has some appeal to somebody and to some sections that are

00:23:08.520 --> 00:23:11.880
[Guest]: clearly powerful, because that's why you're using religion, because clearly it's having

00:23:11.880 --> 00:23:13.240
[Guest]: some kind of an effect.

00:23:13.240 --> 00:23:15.480
[Guest]: So religion has an effect in our society today.

00:23:15.480 --> 00:23:20.440
[Guest]: It's possible equally that in the past, at least some sections, some powerful sections

00:23:20.440 --> 00:23:24.680
[Guest]: did work within that frame of politics as well.

00:23:24.680 --> 00:23:29.800
[Guest]: Again, it's tough because you don't want anybody to be victimized because of this, but also

00:23:29.800 --> 00:23:34.040
[Guest]: not talking about it as I think dangerous, because then other people can come and say,

00:23:34.040 --> 00:23:36.000
[Guest]: look, all these historians are liars.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:37.000
[Guest]: All of them are biased.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:38.000
[Guest]: They're not telling you this.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:39.000
[Guest]: They're not telling you that.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:43.440
[Guest]: They're all trying to look the other way, which is dangerous, because that's what creates

00:23:43.440 --> 00:23:47.120
[Guest]: the space for fake news and a lot of misreading of history.

00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:50.720
[Guest]: Another part of your question, what was the second part of your question?

00:23:50.720 --> 00:23:53.040
[Amit Varma]: I said there were two parts I was going to answer.

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:57.720
[Amit Varma]: About whether academic history will gradually become sort of, not become redundant, but

00:23:57.720 --> 00:23:58.720
[Guest]: the role will change.

00:23:58.720 --> 00:24:00.360
[Guest]: The gatekeeping is falling apart.

00:24:00.360 --> 00:24:05.240
[Guest]: Well, yes, that's true, because a lot of material is now much more easily available.

00:24:05.240 --> 00:24:09.280
[Guest]: Archives are being digitized very slow, painfully slow in India, but it is happening.

00:24:09.280 --> 00:24:12.720
[Guest]: A lot of visual material is being digitized.

00:24:12.720 --> 00:24:16.680
[Guest]: The Asiatic Society here in Mumbai, they've got a huge newspaper archive, Times of India

00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:18.560
[Guest]: going back to the 19th century.

00:24:18.560 --> 00:24:22.560
[Guest]: Wonderful resources are now available just a click away in 12,000 rupees a year, which

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:23.560
[Guest]: isn't too bad.

00:24:23.560 --> 00:24:26.480
[Guest]: I mean, it's expensive, but it's not too bad if you're winning it.

00:24:26.480 --> 00:24:28.940
[Guest]: It's a one year subscription, so it's not bad at all.

00:24:28.940 --> 00:24:34.480
[Guest]: But all the same, I think it's also important, democratizing access is one thing, but also

00:24:34.480 --> 00:24:39.800
[Guest]: training people to read that material in the right way also matters.

00:24:39.800 --> 00:24:43.880
[Guest]: You can read something and take it at face value, whereas historians are taught to interrogate

00:24:43.880 --> 00:24:44.880
[Guest]: the source itself.

00:24:44.880 --> 00:24:47.600
[Guest]: They're taught to ask questions of the source itself.

00:24:47.600 --> 00:24:49.360
[Guest]: Why is this document in this format?

00:24:49.360 --> 00:24:51.200
[Guest]: Why is this document written on this date?

00:24:51.200 --> 00:24:52.200
[Guest]: Who's the author?

00:24:52.200 --> 00:24:53.400
[Guest]: What language is it written in?

00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:57.720
[Guest]: All of these questions come in because you're trained to ask those questions.

00:24:57.720 --> 00:25:01.720
[Guest]: If you're not trained and you just go in because the access is there and try to put together

00:25:01.720 --> 00:25:05.920
[Guest]: a narrative, there will be certain flaws in it and people can sort of point out holes

00:25:05.920 --> 00:25:06.920
[Guest]: in it.

00:25:06.920 --> 00:25:09.400
[Guest]: But again, these are issues that will eventually resolve itself.

00:25:09.400 --> 00:25:11.600
[Guest]: The world is in a state of flux.

00:25:11.600 --> 00:25:16.000
[Guest]: Gatekeeping is generally falling away in all fields, as you said, and therefore in future,

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:19.640
[Guest]: in this interim, there may be some chaos, there may be some confusion, people may not

00:25:19.640 --> 00:25:21.720
[Guest]: necessarily do their best work.

00:25:21.720 --> 00:25:26.500
[Guest]: But I think eventually, once this becomes the new normal, a new kind of, let's say system

00:25:26.500 --> 00:25:28.640
[Guest]: of moderation will fall in place.

00:25:28.640 --> 00:25:31.960
[Guest]: And then that will, you know, it will create a kind of balance of its own.

00:25:31.960 --> 00:25:36.400
[Guest]: Things have a way of eventually, you know, once the existing system falls apart, a new

00:25:36.400 --> 00:25:40.480
[Guest]: balance will eventually form on its own is what I feel at least.

00:25:40.480 --> 00:25:45.080
[Amit Varma]: Taking up on what you said earlier about how when you wrote that particular historical

00:25:45.080 --> 00:25:48.720
[Amit Varma]: column, people told you, hey, don't do it because it will be used by so and so for such

00:25:48.720 --> 00:25:49.960
[Amit Varma]: and such reason.

00:25:49.960 --> 00:25:54.880
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that that has that kind of tendency that don't interrogate this right

00:25:54.880 --> 00:26:00.160
[Amit Varma]: now, don't say this right now, that is not just about truth, but there are, you know,

00:26:00.160 --> 00:26:01.360
[Amit Varma]: other issues involved.

00:26:01.360 --> 00:26:05.200
[Amit Varma]: I think it has been there for a long time and is there in other ways also, for example,

00:26:05.200 --> 00:26:09.200
[Amit Varma]: in science, where you will hear people say that don't talk about innate differences between

00:26:09.200 --> 00:26:13.760
[Amit Varma]: men and women, because people might interpret it in a prescriptive way and not a descriptive

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:14.760
[Amit Varma]: way.

00:26:14.760 --> 00:26:15.760
[Amit Varma]: Right?

00:26:15.760 --> 00:26:19.880
[Amit Varma]: Or people might say, don't just talk about genetic differences, because he eugenics happened

00:26:19.880 --> 00:26:22.940
[Amit Varma]: once upon a time, and because it may be misused in this way.

00:26:22.940 --> 00:26:27.040
[Amit Varma]: And just in the context of history, I read an episode with Kapil Komireddy, who wrote

00:26:27.040 --> 00:26:31.720
[Amit Varma]: the book, the provocative book, Malevolent Republic, an excellent read, where one of

00:26:31.720 --> 00:26:37.000
[Amit Varma]: his central points was that historians of the 50s and 60s in India made exactly the

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:38.520
[Amit Varma]: mistake that you're alluding to.

00:26:38.520 --> 00:26:44.800
[Amit Varma]: This is his take on things that because they saw that India was fragile, because you cannot

00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:48.800
[Amit Varma]: take it for granted that the center will hold and there were all these competing passions

00:26:48.800 --> 00:26:55.220
[Amit Varma]: which could be out of place, they felt that it's best to sort of when you write history,

00:26:55.220 --> 00:26:58.640
[Amit Varma]: you talk about the Mughals, you talk about all that, you minimize the damage that they

00:26:58.640 --> 00:27:02.060
[Amit Varma]: did so that there aren't repercussions in the present time.

00:27:02.060 --> 00:27:07.720
[Amit Varma]: And Kapil's point was that this actually had the unintended effect of making things worse.

00:27:07.720 --> 00:27:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Because so many people just felt that the elites are not even acknowledging what has

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:13.380
[Amit Varma]: been done to us.

00:27:13.380 --> 00:27:17.760
[Amit Varma]: And that has actually worsened the passions that we see in play today.

00:27:17.760 --> 00:27:23.380
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, the doing of history with this kind of impulse or with any impulse that is

00:27:23.380 --> 00:27:27.720
[Amit Varma]: not just about telling the truth, the best way that you can, I mean, obviously, no one

00:27:27.720 --> 00:27:31.440
[Amit Varma]: has a monopoly on the truth, but the best way that you can making a good faith effort,

00:27:31.440 --> 00:27:36.600
[Amit Varma]: but instead letting these extraneous considerations come in, it can't end well, that was a point

00:27:36.600 --> 00:27:37.600
[Amit Varma]: he was making.

00:27:37.600 --> 00:27:39.040
[Guest]: So what do you think about that?

00:27:39.040 --> 00:27:41.200
[Guest]: I mostly agree with that, with that position.

00:27:41.200 --> 00:27:45.560
[Guest]: A lot of the historians of the 50s and 60s, I don't think they did it consciously.

00:27:45.560 --> 00:27:48.840
[Guest]: To a great extent, this would just have been the dominant narrative at the time.

00:27:48.840 --> 00:27:52.960
[Guest]: And without us even realizing it, the dominant narratives do shape how we think.

00:27:52.960 --> 00:27:56.080
[Guest]: It sort of adds a filter in front of our eyes, and we start looking at everything through

00:27:56.080 --> 00:27:57.080
[Guest]: that filter.

00:27:57.080 --> 00:28:01.960
[Guest]: You know, when the British Empire was in power, you know, a lot of people had sympathy with

00:28:01.960 --> 00:28:05.400
[Guest]: India, but they were still broadly thinking within the terms of the empire, they would

00:28:05.400 --> 00:28:09.440
[Guest]: still think that, oh, the British still need to be in India to civilize India, but they

00:28:09.440 --> 00:28:11.080
[Guest]: could be kinder, they could be nicer.

00:28:11.080 --> 00:28:13.580
[Guest]: So that basic filter doesn't move away.

00:28:13.580 --> 00:28:17.800
[Guest]: So in the same way, you know, post-independence, partition, secessionist movements, insurgency,

00:28:17.800 --> 00:28:19.120
[Guest]: all of this is happening.

00:28:19.120 --> 00:28:24.040
[Guest]: So I suppose there was an impulse, almost subconsciously, to try and sort of do something

00:28:24.040 --> 00:28:28.640
[Guest]: that is unifying and takes people together, rather than exacerbates differences that are

00:28:28.640 --> 00:28:30.280
[Guest]: already there on the ground.

00:28:30.280 --> 00:28:35.320
[Guest]: But I think 70 years into independence, if we don't start acting a little more maturely

00:28:35.320 --> 00:28:40.600
[Guest]: about these sensitive topics and start sort of talking about them transparently, without

00:28:40.600 --> 00:28:45.280
[Guest]: too much hesitation, without too much shame, and things like that, it's not worth it, you

00:28:45.280 --> 00:28:46.280
[Guest]: know.

00:28:46.280 --> 00:28:47.760
[Guest]: Then what are we ultimately doing?

00:28:47.760 --> 00:28:52.720
[Guest]: 70 years have passed, we can take that risk, we can take that gamble, because we're already

00:28:52.720 --> 00:28:55.840
[Guest]: seeing why the risks involved in not doing it.

00:28:55.840 --> 00:29:01.960
[Guest]: You know, not doing it, as I said, we're creating room for people to peddle rubbish as history.

00:29:01.960 --> 00:29:06.000
[Guest]: And to some extent, the blame sits with us itself, because we've not acknowledged these

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.600
[Guest]: areas, we've not focused on these areas.

00:29:08.600 --> 00:29:10.000
[Guest]: And you know, religion matters to people.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:13.640
[Guest]: There was that Pew research that came out a couple of months ago, which tells you how

00:29:13.640 --> 00:29:16.320
[Guest]: much to this day, religion matters to people.

00:29:16.320 --> 00:29:20.840
[Guest]: It reminds me of a quote, in the 18th century, I think there was this one East India Company

00:29:20.840 --> 00:29:24.600
[Guest]: official who says that in this country, he's talking in Madras, but he's like, in this

00:29:24.600 --> 00:29:28.440
[Guest]: country, when a person makes money, he finds no other way to show it off but to start building

00:29:28.440 --> 00:29:29.440
[Guest]: a new temple.

00:29:29.440 --> 00:29:32.400
[Guest]: And, you know, it's interesting, because I see the same thing in Kerala, where the Gulf

00:29:32.400 --> 00:29:36.600
[Guest]: boom comes in, people have disposable income, they're building big houses, but there's also

00:29:36.600 --> 00:29:43.240
[Guest]: this huge boom in renovating old family temples, groves, resuming pujas, astrologers are making

00:29:43.240 --> 00:29:48.120
[Guest]: a lot of money, because people do sort of fall back on what they think is traditional

00:29:48.120 --> 00:29:52.400
[Guest]: high culture, which they did not perhaps have access to earlier, they do fall back onto

00:29:52.400 --> 00:29:53.400
[Guest]: those things.

00:29:53.400 --> 00:29:56.880
[Guest]: And it's fascinating that, you know, that 18th century quote, in some ways, fits this

00:29:56.880 --> 00:30:00.000
[Guest]: this late 20th century context in Kerala as well.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:04.800
[Guest]: So it is real, it is, it's not a phenomenon we can play down, religion did have an impact

00:30:04.800 --> 00:30:09.080
[Guest]: on people's lives, it could be syncretic, in other cases, it may not be, but we should

00:30:09.080 --> 00:30:11.760
[Guest]: be able to have an open conversation about it.

00:30:11.760 --> 00:30:16.840
[Guest]: And if it is unpleasant at certain moments, we should still be able to talk about it without

00:30:16.840 --> 00:30:21.560
[Guest]: resorting to name calling and immediately sort of branding people on that account.

00:30:21.560 --> 00:30:24.760
[Guest]: I think otherwise, it doesn't serve the purpose of history itself.

00:30:24.760 --> 00:30:28.400
[Guest]: You know, we were again falling into the same old trap, if you want to break out of the

00:30:28.400 --> 00:30:33.680
[Guest]: trap, you also need to learn to have some of these, let's say, uncomfortable conversations

00:30:33.680 --> 00:30:35.360
[Guest]: around uncomfortable topics.

00:30:35.360 --> 00:30:39.160
[Guest]: If we have it today, 20 years later, it won't be an issue, because we've already dealt with

00:30:39.160 --> 00:30:40.160
[Guest]: it.

00:30:40.160 --> 00:30:43.000
[Guest]: We've already crossed that bridge, instead of avoiding it and sort of, you know, skirting

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:45.240
[Guest]: it, we've already got there.

00:30:45.240 --> 00:30:48.360
[Amit Varma]: Except that, you know, the bridge is not being crossed, the bridge is being blown up, there

00:30:48.360 --> 00:30:50.160
[Amit Varma]: is a war in the middle of the bridge.

00:30:50.160 --> 00:30:54.760
[Amit Varma]: What we kind of see nowadays is this narrative warfare that actually doesn't have any regard

00:30:54.760 --> 00:30:55.760
[Amit Varma]: for the truth.

00:30:55.760 --> 00:30:56.760
[Amit Varma]: Right?

00:30:56.760 --> 00:31:00.080
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't matter what happened, what archives you can go into and how rigorous you can get.

00:31:00.080 --> 00:31:02.940
[Amit Varma]: It's all about what narrative you can sell better.

00:31:02.940 --> 00:31:07.800
[Amit Varma]: And the necessary thing about all these narratives is that they are necessarily simplistic.

00:31:07.800 --> 00:31:11.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, one of the cliches on my show is how I keep quoting Whitman and that whole,

00:31:11.360 --> 00:31:13.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, people contain multitudes kind of thing.

00:31:13.920 --> 00:31:16.840
[Amit Varma]: But the thing is that they do, that's what good history brings out.

00:31:16.840 --> 00:31:21.620
[Amit Varma]: That is, in fact, the very thing that False Allies aims to do, to kind of beat back a

00:31:21.620 --> 00:31:26.880
[Amit Varma]: simple narrative and show different layers of it and it succeeds so well in doing that.

00:31:26.880 --> 00:31:31.040
[Amit Varma]: But if anything, I think the tendency of the times is to ignore that, like from what I

00:31:31.040 --> 00:31:35.920
[Amit Varma]: remember just 15 years back, you could read more nuanced pieces about Nehru than you can

00:31:35.920 --> 00:31:36.920
[Amit Varma]: today.

00:31:36.920 --> 00:31:37.920
[Amit Varma]: Today, you can't.

00:31:37.920 --> 00:31:41.880
[Amit Varma]: Today, he's either a demon who destroyed India and is responsible for, you know, everything

00:31:41.880 --> 00:31:46.360
[Amit Varma]: that happens today, including Amit Shah getting acidity on a Wednesday afternoon, or he's

00:31:46.360 --> 00:31:50.240
[Amit Varma]: a saint who did nothing wrong and who built this great modern India that the barbarians

00:31:50.240 --> 00:31:51.720
[Amit Varma]: are going to take down.

00:31:51.720 --> 00:31:53.720
[Amit Varma]: And these are both nonsensical narratives.

00:31:53.720 --> 00:31:54.720
[Amit Varma]: He was deeply complex.

00:31:54.720 --> 00:31:55.720
[Amit Varma]: He did great things.

00:31:55.720 --> 00:31:58.300
[Amit Varma]: He messed up in various areas.

00:31:58.300 --> 00:32:03.900
[Amit Varma]: But it seems that the space for those kinds of nuanced narratives is kind of going down.

00:32:03.900 --> 00:32:06.280
[Amit Varma]: And I won't even say to throw an additional thought there.

00:32:06.280 --> 00:32:09.360
[Amit Varma]: I don't think the appetite for those nuanced narratives is going down.

00:32:09.360 --> 00:32:14.240
[Amit Varma]: I just think that the vocal minorities kind of shout out the silent majorities.

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:18.240
[Amit Varma]: So even someone writing about it today will be more inclined to cater to one side or the

00:32:18.240 --> 00:32:21.400
[Amit Varma]: other, especially if they've kind of joined the camp.

00:32:21.400 --> 00:32:25.800
[Amit Varma]: And I've not in the specific context of Nehru, but in some other context, I've forgotten.

00:32:25.800 --> 00:32:31.080
[Amit Varma]: I've had the argument made to me that I know that X is a more complex subject, but I'm

00:32:31.080 --> 00:32:35.440
[Amit Varma]: going to write about it in this particular way, because otherwise the other side will,

00:32:35.440 --> 00:32:40.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, pick up on whatever the exact same thing that you said about the Maplar Rebellion.

00:32:40.160 --> 00:32:41.920
[Amit Varma]: So what's kind of your take on that?

00:32:41.920 --> 00:32:46.280
[Amit Varma]: Because at one level, I feel hopeful that anybody can do history, that the gatekeepers

00:32:46.280 --> 00:32:48.640
[Amit Varma]: are kind of gone, anyone can dig in for their own research.

00:32:48.640 --> 00:32:52.160
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you would imagine that in this marketplace of ideas, the truth will eventually

00:32:52.160 --> 00:32:55.480
[Amit Varma]: prevail, that quality will rise to the surface.

00:32:55.480 --> 00:32:59.920
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, we are so dominated by simple narratives that people are actually

00:32:59.920 --> 00:33:05.400
[Amit Varma]: becoming scared to say nuanced things, because they'll get attacked from both sides.

00:33:05.400 --> 00:33:06.400
[Guest]: That's true.

00:33:06.400 --> 00:33:10.040
[Guest]: And I think the important word or the term you used is that vocal minority.

00:33:10.040 --> 00:33:12.680
[Guest]: I think a lot of this happens on social media.

00:33:12.680 --> 00:33:16.680
[Guest]: In my personal experience, I speak at a lot of colleges, not all of them are in your big

00:33:16.680 --> 00:33:17.680
[Guest]: cities.

00:33:17.680 --> 00:33:20.920
[Guest]: In Kerala, for example, I've spoken at fairly smallish colleges and towns.

00:33:20.920 --> 00:33:24.720
[Guest]: And you know, yesterday, I had a session with students at Loyola College in Chennai.

00:33:24.720 --> 00:33:28.400
[Guest]: You speak to students in those contexts, and you realize actually, there is a huge appetite

00:33:28.400 --> 00:33:30.600
[Guest]: for nuanced history.

00:33:30.600 --> 00:33:35.200
[Guest]: People don't get upset if you talk about things, which are even uncomfortable, people, especially

00:33:35.200 --> 00:33:39.120
[Guest]: kids, they're willing to listen to you, they're willing to entertain an argument, even if

00:33:39.120 --> 00:33:43.760
[Guest]: it seems unsavory, even if it goes against a seemingly dominant ideology.

00:33:43.760 --> 00:33:46.000
[Guest]: A lot of the noise happens on social media.

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:50.340
[Guest]: And I think the tragedy is that that social media noise has somehow started translating

00:33:50.340 --> 00:33:55.040
[Guest]: to newspaper clout and press clout and generally, other areas also where these subjects are

00:33:55.040 --> 00:33:59.440
[Guest]: discussed at a lot of top level, which is tragic, because on the ground, that's still

00:33:59.440 --> 00:34:04.680
[Guest]: not the case, you know, at least in my experience, lit fests, other contexts, if you're physically

00:34:04.680 --> 00:34:09.320
[Guest]: in a room with, say, 100-200 young people, it is not the response you would get for saying

00:34:09.320 --> 00:34:14.040
[Guest]: the same thing on social media, which to me gives me a great deal of optimism.

00:34:14.040 --> 00:34:18.320
[Guest]: As you said, silent vocal minorities can often change the course of history, they can often

00:34:18.320 --> 00:34:21.680
[Guest]: wield disproportionate influence, so it's dangerous.

00:34:21.680 --> 00:34:25.580
[Guest]: But I think it's important also for some of us to keep our head down, focus on what we're

00:34:25.580 --> 00:34:28.960
[Guest]: supposed to do, and not immediately get drawn into these debates.

00:34:28.960 --> 00:34:31.920
[Guest]: I use Twitter very little, I just retweet things constantly.

00:34:31.920 --> 00:34:37.320
[Guest]: I don't air opinions, I'm not posting things, even when some rubbish comes up, I'm not the

00:34:37.320 --> 00:34:41.160
[Guest]: one who, if somebody else points out holes in it, I may retweet it, but I don't personally

00:34:41.160 --> 00:34:45.440
[Guest]: go out and do it, because I've got my job, my task cut out for me, and I want to focus

00:34:45.440 --> 00:34:46.440
[Guest]: on that.

00:34:46.440 --> 00:34:50.680
[Guest]: Because if one tries to do everything all at once, one tries to fight all these battles

00:34:50.680 --> 00:34:55.720
[Guest]: at all fronts, it's going to be a losing process, and it's going to be a very frustrating process.

00:34:55.720 --> 00:34:59.600
[Guest]: And I don't want to do that to myself to begin with, and I want to focus on one area where

00:34:59.600 --> 00:35:04.920
[Guest]: I can do something well, play to my strengths, and make a contribution that will hopefully

00:35:04.920 --> 00:35:05.920
[Guest]: last.

00:35:05.920 --> 00:35:11.040
[Guest]: It may be an idealistic way of thinking, but I think it has some meaning, perhaps not in

00:35:11.040 --> 00:35:16.600
[Guest]: the short term, but I think in the medium and long term, people eventually, fake news,

00:35:16.600 --> 00:35:21.300
[Guest]: all the saturation of noise, etc, everything has a shelf life.

00:35:21.300 --> 00:35:26.680
[Guest]: When that shelf life comes to an end, when people have finally had it, they will eventually

00:35:26.680 --> 00:35:30.000
[Guest]: come back to the books, to the bookshelf, and pick up things.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:35.340
[Guest]: And I would rather try and contribute to filling that bookshelf, even if it's a less glamorous

00:35:35.340 --> 00:35:40.080
[Guest]: task for the next 10 years, but I think that in the long term is a better cause to follow

00:35:40.080 --> 00:35:46.080
[Guest]: than get into these debates, into this online noise and these online battles, online is

00:35:46.080 --> 00:35:49.480
[Guest]: going to be noisy, it's going to be about these battles, every day, somebody is going

00:35:49.480 --> 00:35:53.540
[Guest]: to invent a new controversy, I'm not prepared to play that game, I'm going to play the game

00:35:53.540 --> 00:35:54.540
[Guest]: on my terms.

00:35:54.540 --> 00:35:58.480
[Guest]: And I will wait for the day that the terms in general also change and then hopefully

00:35:58.480 --> 00:36:02.560
[Guest]: then people like me will be in a position of strength because we've put in the hours

00:36:02.560 --> 00:36:08.440
[Guest]: and taken those years of sort of effort to try and contribute something more long lasting,

00:36:08.440 --> 00:36:12.840
[Guest]: you know, and not so transient as an online debate that happened one Friday and next Friday

00:36:12.840 --> 00:36:17.720
[Guest]: it's a new thing, and the next month something else comes up, you know, it's a completely

00:36:17.720 --> 00:36:18.720
[Guest]: different set of things.

00:36:18.720 --> 00:36:21.880
[Guest]: I'm not, I'm not playing that game, because that game is skewed anyway.

00:36:21.880 --> 00:36:26.400
[Guest]: It's skewed towards a certain set of people, you're always on the defensive, you're always

00:36:26.400 --> 00:36:30.900
[Guest]: trying to sort of show why something else is not what it is, what people are claiming

00:36:30.900 --> 00:36:31.900
[Guest]: it is.

00:36:31.900 --> 00:36:33.640
[Guest]: I would rather proactively make that case.

00:36:33.640 --> 00:36:38.880
[Guest]: It may not be in a tweet, it may be in a 500 page book, but to me, it seems like the most

00:36:38.880 --> 00:36:43.880
[Guest]: sensible thing to do with my time and energy, rather than flittering it away with in these

00:36:43.880 --> 00:36:44.880
[Amit Varma]: things.

00:36:44.880 --> 00:36:46.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, very wise words.

00:36:46.120 --> 00:36:48.920
[Amit Varma]: I wish I could spend less time on social media.

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:50.920
[Amit Varma]: It's almost like you're a social media celebrity.

00:36:50.920 --> 00:36:55.080
[Amit Varma]: No, no, it's, it's with a perverse fascination that I keep going to Twitter and doom scrolling

00:36:55.080 --> 00:36:56.080
[Amit Varma]: as well.

00:36:56.080 --> 00:36:58.640
[Amit Varma]: I think it's fairly toxic even for me.

00:36:58.640 --> 00:37:02.580
[Amit Varma]: One of the mistakes I think I made when I was a young man and which I tell my writing

00:37:02.580 --> 00:37:07.560
[Amit Varma]: students today not to do, is of thinking of life or even writing or whatever one does,

00:37:07.560 --> 00:37:12.800
[Amit Varma]: in terms of goals, in terms of things to do, you know, rather than in terms of processes

00:37:12.800 --> 00:37:16.040
[Amit Varma]: in terms of, you know, what you want to be.

00:37:16.040 --> 00:37:20.580
[Amit Varma]: So now, if I can throw that back at you, when you started the ivory throne, I'm assuming

00:37:20.580 --> 00:37:25.600
[Amit Varma]: at some level, it was about I want to write this book, and it is going to be very enjoyable

00:37:25.600 --> 00:37:26.600
[Amit Varma]: for me.

00:37:26.600 --> 00:37:27.800
[Amit Varma]: And it is a goal.

00:37:27.800 --> 00:37:33.080
[Amit Varma]: But in the course somewhere along the way, I'm assuming that it became less about what

00:37:33.080 --> 00:37:35.520
[Amit Varma]: you are doing, but more about what you are.

00:37:35.520 --> 00:37:41.120
[Amit Varma]: So is there a point where you feel that you just define yourself as I am a person who

00:37:41.120 --> 00:37:45.520
[Amit Varma]: does history, and then whatever else happens, various books that you've written, and all

00:37:45.520 --> 00:37:50.080
[Amit Varma]: the columns that you write, and all of that kind of happens by the way, but you have kind

00:37:50.080 --> 00:37:53.440
[Amit Varma]: of come to a firmer definition of who you are.

00:37:53.440 --> 00:37:58.560
[Amit Varma]: Because to me, I think people who get that kind of notion of what they are, that consciousness,

00:37:58.560 --> 00:38:03.000
[Amit Varma]: I am this, I am happy doing this, you know, I wake up every morning looking forward to

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:07.280
[Amit Varma]: doing this, and I get to do this, which is such great fortune and great privilege.

00:38:07.280 --> 00:38:10.800
[Amit Varma]: So do you feel that happened to you along the way, or were you clear from the start

00:38:10.800 --> 00:38:11.800
[Guest]: that I love doing this?

00:38:11.800 --> 00:38:16.160
[Guest]: No, I wasn't clear from the start, I knew I wanted to do that one book, I knew I wanted

00:38:16.160 --> 00:38:20.040
[Guest]: to tell the story of Sethu Lakshmibai, because injustice had been done to her in historical

00:38:20.040 --> 00:38:24.360
[Guest]: terms, that person deserved a better sort of reading from a historian.

00:38:24.360 --> 00:38:28.480
[Guest]: So that was very clear in my mind, but there was no long term plan, I knew I could write,

00:38:28.480 --> 00:38:30.200
[Guest]: I enjoyed writing and all of that.

00:38:30.200 --> 00:38:32.600
[Guest]: But frankly, my interest in those days was foreign policy.

00:38:32.600 --> 00:38:37.480
[Guest]: In fact, I still keep one toe in that field, I still go for these conferences, and international

00:38:37.480 --> 00:38:39.560
[Guest]: seminars and all that on that.

00:38:39.560 --> 00:38:42.200
[Guest]: But it's a very small part of my life now.

00:38:42.200 --> 00:38:43.760
[Guest]: At that time, that is what interested me.

00:38:43.760 --> 00:38:46.380
[Guest]: That's why I went and worked with Shashi Tharoor in Parliament, because he had just come back

00:38:46.380 --> 00:38:49.680
[Guest]: from the UN, and he was head of the Foreign Affairs Committee, all of that.

00:38:49.680 --> 00:38:52.760
[Guest]: So I went and worked with a member of the House of Lords.

00:38:52.760 --> 00:38:57.400
[Guest]: All of that was part of that, what I thought would be my professional trajectory.

00:38:57.400 --> 00:39:02.720
[Guest]: Then Ivory Throne happened, it was a six year process, it changed me, you know, people congratulate

00:39:02.720 --> 00:39:06.360
[Guest]: me on the book, but frankly, I owe the book a great deal, because it, in some ways taught

00:39:06.360 --> 00:39:12.120
[Guest]: me who I am, and had a huge impact in shaping the kind of person I became.

00:39:12.120 --> 00:39:17.120
[Guest]: And that then, and I think, I mean, this is probably immodest to say, but success, I think

00:39:17.120 --> 00:39:21.480
[Guest]: often helps, which is that the book did so well, and it had such a tremendous response

00:39:21.480 --> 00:39:23.160
[Guest]: from so many people.

00:39:23.160 --> 00:39:27.360
[Guest]: It gives you the confidence then to start thinking, oh, wow, okay, hold on, maybe I

00:39:27.360 --> 00:39:30.040
[Guest]: can take this up as something, I enjoy doing it.

00:39:30.040 --> 00:39:32.440
[Guest]: Why didn't I even think of it as a career option?

00:39:32.440 --> 00:39:36.120
[Guest]: Because nobody tells you being a writer or being a historian is a career option.

00:39:36.120 --> 00:39:40.760
[Guest]: So then that sort of gave me pause, and I decided, let me see if I can, you know, make

00:39:40.760 --> 00:39:41.760
[Guest]: this work.

00:39:41.760 --> 00:39:44.800
[Guest]: And since then, as of now, I've managed to make it work.

00:39:44.800 --> 00:39:47.240
[Guest]: And yeah, now I'm quite content with where I am.

00:39:47.240 --> 00:39:48.860
[Guest]: I'm enjoying what I'm doing.

00:39:48.860 --> 00:39:53.040
[Guest]: You asked me earlier, why I don't start a podcast of my own, partly for this reason.

00:39:53.040 --> 00:39:56.080
[Guest]: You know, one may be tempted to do several things.

00:39:56.080 --> 00:40:00.240
[Guest]: But if there is something one already enjoys, and you're good at it, focus on that.

00:40:00.240 --> 00:40:03.680
[Guest]: In today's world, it's very easy to be drawn and attracted to lots of things.

00:40:03.680 --> 00:40:07.640
[Guest]: I don't want to at the moment, do that, you know, I'm enjoying what I'm doing, writing

00:40:07.640 --> 00:40:12.040
[Guest]: the research, the slogging, even the complaining about the research, all of that is part of,

00:40:12.040 --> 00:40:13.360
[Guest]: you know, my life now.

00:40:13.360 --> 00:40:14.360
[Guest]: And I enjoy that.

00:40:14.360 --> 00:40:19.560
[Guest]: It really brightens my overall sort of perspective about things, as opposed to, you know, just

00:40:19.560 --> 00:40:22.960
[Guest]: because you may be good at something, then trying that and then trying something else.

00:40:22.960 --> 00:40:23.960
[Guest]: That's not my style.

00:40:23.960 --> 00:40:27.820
[Guest]: At least I want to focus on what I've clearly decided is my path.

00:40:27.820 --> 00:40:30.640
[Guest]: The other thing is, because writing is also in some ways precarious, you know, you may

00:40:30.640 --> 00:40:34.800
[Guest]: have several successes, but what if one book doesn't do well, immediately your stock in

00:40:34.800 --> 00:40:38.880
[Guest]: the market goes down a little bit, you know, your advances go down a little bit, publishers

00:40:38.880 --> 00:40:42.600
[Guest]: take a pause, you know, as to whether they want to necessarily go ahead with you with

00:40:42.600 --> 00:40:43.600
[Guest]: the next book.

00:40:43.600 --> 00:40:48.880
[Guest]: So some of those fears also exist, which means at some level, I'm also like, I really need

00:40:48.880 --> 00:40:54.360
[Guest]: to keep my game up as far as this is concerned, so that I'm in that position of strength where

00:40:54.360 --> 00:40:56.520
[Guest]: I can keep doing more and more of what I enjoy.

00:40:56.520 --> 00:41:02.240
[Guest]: Whereas if I fritter that energy away, then what if I fall and then it may be tough to

00:41:02.240 --> 00:41:04.080
[Guest]: again sort of come back.

00:41:04.080 --> 00:41:07.360
[Guest]: So there's some of those practical constraints and fears as well.

00:41:07.360 --> 00:41:12.120
[Guest]: So it's not completely all, you know, wonderful colors and perfect, different elements come

00:41:12.120 --> 00:41:13.120
[Guest]: into it.

00:41:13.120 --> 00:41:15.560
[Guest]: But it's very clear that this is what I want to do.

00:41:15.560 --> 00:41:18.520
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned that Ivory Throne changed you as a person or it helped you discover

00:41:18.520 --> 00:41:19.920
[Amit Varma]: who you were as a person.

00:41:19.920 --> 00:41:22.160
[Guest]: Can you elaborate on that a little?

00:41:22.160 --> 00:41:26.880
[Guest]: It was a very isolating process because, you know, I started at 19, in your early 20s,

00:41:26.880 --> 00:41:30.840
[Guest]: you're still a student, you're still sort of with young people, I've had my fair share

00:41:30.840 --> 00:41:35.080
[Guest]: of getting drunk and partying and all of that, I was a very social person in general.

00:41:35.080 --> 00:41:40.360
[Guest]: So for me to be chained to a desk for 12 hours at a stretch to sit in a in a in a library

00:41:40.360 --> 00:41:45.640
[Guest]: hall in an archive, a room in the archives, for long hours without a single person around

00:41:45.640 --> 00:41:49.160
[Guest]: me uttering a word, that kind of thing was initially a challenge, you know, because I'm

00:41:49.160 --> 00:41:52.360
[Guest]: not that person, I'm generally quite talkative and all of that.

00:41:52.360 --> 00:41:57.280
[Guest]: So it's almost meditative, you're almost, I mean, quite literally with just yourself

00:41:57.280 --> 00:42:01.460
[Guest]: and of course, the files, but it also does sort of hold up a mirror to you.

00:42:01.460 --> 00:42:05.440
[Guest]: So you, you know, in my early 20s, I would see, you do feel peer pressure, right?

00:42:05.440 --> 00:42:08.840
[Guest]: You see your friends, some of them making lots of money in corporate jobs or whatever

00:42:08.840 --> 00:42:11.440
[Guest]: their first corporate jobs.

00:42:11.440 --> 00:42:14.880
[Guest]: Many of them are traveling, they're partying, they've got these wonderful Facebook photographs

00:42:14.880 --> 00:42:20.480
[Guest]: and here I am sitting with my with my parchment and paper and you know, coming back at nine

00:42:20.480 --> 00:42:22.880
[Guest]: o'clock and then staying up till three to write.

00:42:22.880 --> 00:42:27.360
[Guest]: You do feel a little lonely and isolated, but that isolation also becomes a means for

00:42:27.360 --> 00:42:31.920
[Guest]: self reflection, you start figuring out what works for you, what doesn't, what is an issue

00:42:31.920 --> 00:42:36.600
[Guest]: for you and what is not and you are also able to surmount a lot of those pressures.

00:42:36.600 --> 00:42:40.040
[Guest]: Earlier I might have felt left out that, oh, you know, why am I stuck with this project

00:42:40.040 --> 00:42:43.680
[Guest]: while everybody else is having fun, but very quickly I was able to get over it and then

00:42:43.680 --> 00:42:45.560
[Guest]: you realize, actually, look, it doesn't matter.

00:42:45.560 --> 00:42:48.960
[Guest]: I can go out and have fun on my terms, but the fun doesn't define me.

00:42:48.960 --> 00:42:53.120
[Guest]: I decide when I want to go and have fun and then the rest of the time I can equally with

00:42:53.120 --> 00:42:57.160
[Guest]: just the same appetite, direct my energy at work and have no issues with it.

00:42:57.160 --> 00:43:01.480
[Guest]: So I can go an entire year without socializing with just research and I can go another year

00:43:01.480 --> 00:43:04.560
[Guest]: just for socializing, but doing no other serious work.

00:43:04.560 --> 00:43:07.240
[Guest]: It's possible because I have control over that process now.

00:43:07.240 --> 00:43:11.160
[Guest]: And that control is something I developed when I was working on The Ivory Throne.

00:43:11.160 --> 00:43:15.160
[Guest]: For better or worse, it happened when I was very young, in my early twenties, which meant

00:43:15.160 --> 00:43:20.640
[Guest]: that at a relatively early age, I had figured out what I wanted to do, how I was as a person,

00:43:20.640 --> 00:43:24.640
[Guest]: what my strengths were, what my weaknesses were, what upset me, what made me happy.

00:43:24.640 --> 00:43:28.560
[Guest]: Those things all were wrapped up in that book, you know, I've, for example, small things,

00:43:28.560 --> 00:43:32.240
[Guest]: I was always a very skinny person and, you know, the one time I put on weight was when

00:43:32.240 --> 00:43:35.280
[Guest]: I was doing this book because I was stress eating at this one stage where the book was

00:43:35.280 --> 00:43:39.860
[Guest]: simply not moving forward and I was eating and since then I have, I mean, I have an obsession

00:43:39.860 --> 00:43:44.440
[Guest]: with cake, but I have to really control myself because even now if it's sugar, I can lose

00:43:44.440 --> 00:43:46.240
[Guest]: control very quickly.

00:43:46.240 --> 00:43:49.560
[Guest]: And it was in that time that I realized this about myself, that, you know, this, this stress

00:43:49.560 --> 00:43:51.400
[Guest]: eating is, is a part of this.

00:43:51.400 --> 00:43:54.840
[Guest]: It's obviously a sign that you're depressed in some way and you're trying to sort of fill

00:43:54.840 --> 00:43:57.380
[Guest]: that vacuum with as much sugar as you can.

00:43:57.380 --> 00:44:00.560
[Guest]: These are all methods of figuring out also who you are.

00:44:00.560 --> 00:44:04.520
[Guest]: And it was in some ways enlightening in your early twenties to be able to understand all

00:44:04.520 --> 00:44:05.520
[Guest]: that.

00:44:05.520 --> 00:44:07.640
[Guest]: I've made my share of mistakes and all of that.

00:44:07.640 --> 00:44:11.680
[Guest]: I have no regrets, but yeah, it, for me, it was a, it was also a process where I was growing

00:44:11.680 --> 00:44:12.680
[Guest]: up.

00:44:12.680 --> 00:44:13.680
[Guest]: So I wrote the book.

00:44:13.680 --> 00:44:14.680
[Guest]: Yes.

00:44:14.680 --> 00:44:15.680
[Guest]: The book did well.

00:44:15.680 --> 00:44:19.400
[Guest]: It got its award and acclaim and all of that, but the book also did play a big role in helping

00:44:19.400 --> 00:44:21.240
[Guest]: me figure out who I was.

00:44:21.240 --> 00:44:25.680
[Guest]: So as I say, the person who went in at 19 is not the person who emerged at 25.

00:44:25.680 --> 00:44:32.080
[Guest]: And that six year gap really was a very meditative, personal, interesting time.

00:44:32.080 --> 00:44:36.560
[Amit Varma]: And do you feel that it helped you discover yourself, or do you feel that it actively

00:44:36.560 --> 00:44:37.800
[Amit Varma]: shaped you?

00:44:37.800 --> 00:44:42.400
[Amit Varma]: Because one of the things that I hold is that what you do shapes you actively, even in terms

00:44:42.400 --> 00:44:47.320
[Amit Varma]: of the forms you choose while you're writing, like I'd written an essay on how a simple

00:44:47.320 --> 00:44:52.440
[Amit Varma]: thing like the length of a podcast, if you're a podcaster, can end up changing the person

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:53.440
[Amit Varma]: you are.

00:44:53.440 --> 00:44:56.720
[Amit Varma]: So if you're doing a three hour podcast, for example, you do way more research, you go

00:44:56.720 --> 00:45:00.480
[Amit Varma]: much more deeply, you learn to listen, listening is the most important part of conversation.

00:45:00.480 --> 00:45:03.400
[Amit Varma]: Whereas if you're doing a five minute podcast, you don't even have to read the book, you

00:45:03.400 --> 00:45:06.880
[Amit Varma]: just ask a couple of stock questions, and you're done, you can stay shallow.

00:45:06.880 --> 00:45:11.880
[Amit Varma]: So the form forces a certain kind of content, the content forces a certain kind of behavior.

00:45:11.880 --> 00:45:15.240
[Amit Varma]: And then that changes you in the long run, like I definitely think that I'm more open

00:45:15.240 --> 00:45:19.960
[Amit Varma]: and a better listener now, after all these years of doing this podcast than I was before.

00:45:19.960 --> 00:45:25.520
[Amit Varma]: And I would imagine that is perhaps a similar thing with writing, not just something that

00:45:25.520 --> 00:45:29.520
[Amit Varma]: is book length, but something that by the nature of being history and by the nature

00:45:29.520 --> 00:45:35.320
[Amit Varma]: of the rigor that that involves, involves your constantly looking deeper peeling back

00:45:35.320 --> 00:45:36.560
[Amit Varma]: the layers.

00:45:36.560 --> 00:45:40.720
[Amit Varma]: So do you feel that that also played a part like had you done something else?

00:45:40.720 --> 00:45:43.960
[Amit Varma]: Do you think you'd be fundamentally a different person like had you become a banker?

00:45:43.960 --> 00:45:47.080
[Guest]: Oh, God, can't even imagine that.

00:45:47.080 --> 00:45:51.600
[Guest]: The only alternate career I thought of in my teens was architecture, but you know, that

00:45:51.600 --> 00:45:52.600
[Amit Varma]: didn't happen anyway.

00:45:52.600 --> 00:45:57.080
[Amit Varma]: So I can't be a different person if you think I would have, I think so, I have a feeling

00:45:57.080 --> 00:45:58.120
[Guest]: I might have.

00:45:58.120 --> 00:46:01.760
[Guest]: Because I think because the first book was also biographical, it was also about trying

00:46:01.760 --> 00:46:05.560
[Guest]: to get into the head of this woman who had died so long ago, and occupied a completely

00:46:05.560 --> 00:46:06.560
[Guest]: different world.

00:46:06.560 --> 00:46:10.960
[Guest]: You're not just peeling back the layers or trying to get into their mind, you're also

00:46:10.960 --> 00:46:15.000
[Guest]: learning how to peel back your own layers, you know, so you are also evolving into a

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:19.760
[Guest]: different person that when I say the book changed me, it was partly because I was trying

00:46:19.760 --> 00:46:22.840
[Guest]: to get into somebody's head and the methods by which I was trying to do that, I could

00:46:22.840 --> 00:46:24.280
[Guest]: also apply to myself.

00:46:24.280 --> 00:46:27.880
[Guest]: And I could also start figuring out a lot of things about myself in the process.

00:46:27.880 --> 00:46:30.400
[Guest]: So yeah, I think it fundamentally changed me.

00:46:30.400 --> 00:46:34.200
[Guest]: I don't think if I was in another line of work, I would be this person, there would

00:46:34.200 --> 00:46:37.680
[Guest]: be it would have been another person, another version, that version, that version would

00:46:37.680 --> 00:46:40.120
[Guest]: have had its own issues and challenges.

00:46:40.120 --> 00:46:43.400
[Guest]: Perhaps there would have been other experiences that would shape that person.

00:46:43.400 --> 00:46:47.560
[Guest]: But what happened with this, this book in the first six years of my research was very

00:46:47.560 --> 00:46:52.220
[Guest]: unique and very special to tailoring me into this particular avatar.

00:46:52.220 --> 00:46:57.320
[Guest]: And I don't think anything else could have done it with that kind of force and, and yeah.

00:46:57.320 --> 00:47:00.260
[Amit Varma]: And as far as the craft of writing is concerned, how did that evolve?

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:04.440
[Amit Varma]: Because one of the things that I have pointed out about your previous books and in our previous

00:47:04.440 --> 00:47:07.920
[Amit Varma]: conversations is just your storytelling ability.

00:47:07.920 --> 00:47:11.880
[Amit Varma]: And some of it of course, comes from the stories, Mad Rampaging Elephants and all of that.

00:47:11.880 --> 00:47:16.320
[Amit Varma]: It's just, you know, your history books are as much fun as the Game of Thrones.

00:47:16.320 --> 00:47:18.040
[Amit Varma]: But some of it comes from the craft.

00:47:18.040 --> 00:47:22.640
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that, you know, to get that kind of craft so early is tough.

00:47:22.640 --> 00:47:27.120
[Amit Varma]: Because I look back on how I wrote in my 20s, or how so many young people who do my class

00:47:27.120 --> 00:47:31.120
[Amit Varma]: kind of write is that they'll overthink it, they'll go overboard, they'll try too hard

00:47:31.120 --> 00:47:36.000
[Amit Varma]: to impress others or to convince themselves that wow, I can write.

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:37.560
[Amit Varma]: And there is none of that in your writing.

00:47:37.560 --> 00:47:41.360
[Amit Varma]: It's in that sense, you are always lost in the story, you're never noticing the pros

00:47:41.360 --> 00:47:46.920
[Amit Varma]: for itself, unless you're also you know, somebody keenly involved in the craft and you're looking

00:47:46.920 --> 00:47:47.920
[Amit Varma]: for that.

00:47:47.920 --> 00:47:48.920
[Amit Varma]: So how did that evolve?

00:47:48.920 --> 00:47:49.920
[Amit Varma]: Were there any models?

00:47:49.920 --> 00:47:50.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, were there drafts?

00:47:50.920 --> 00:47:53.960
[Amit Varma]: Did you do a first draft and then look at it and say, no, the writing isn't working,

00:47:53.960 --> 00:47:56.240
[Guest]: I got to tell me a bit about that.

00:47:56.240 --> 00:47:57.240
[Guest]: There were drafts.

00:47:57.240 --> 00:48:00.520
[Guest]: In fact, the early drafts of the Ivory Throne are frankly embarrassing now, because I was

00:48:00.520 --> 00:48:01.800
[Guest]: trying very hard then.

00:48:01.800 --> 00:48:04.560
[Guest]: Because at that time, you know, somebody had told me that, oh, you know, it has to be exciting

00:48:04.560 --> 00:48:05.560
[Guest]: for the reader.

00:48:05.560 --> 00:48:08.160
[Guest]: And I said, Oh, how do I make it exciting for the reader, let me just be very dramatic

00:48:08.160 --> 00:48:09.240
[Guest]: and all of that.

00:48:09.240 --> 00:48:12.960
[Guest]: Even in the final version, something which may not work for all readers is, I thought

00:48:12.960 --> 00:48:16.400
[Guest]: I was being very clever, where I, if you if you've noticed the Ivory Throne, it begins

00:48:16.400 --> 00:48:19.440
[Guest]: with a flourish, like there's a lot of archaic language in the start.

00:48:19.440 --> 00:48:24.800
[Guest]: And then as the era develops, so you begin in the 19th century, and it ends in 1985.

00:48:24.800 --> 00:48:28.360
[Guest]: The language also slowly, let's say, gets more and more modern, more and more contemporary

00:48:28.360 --> 00:48:31.560
[Guest]: as the book proceeds, which I was doing as a deliberate thing, thinking that, oh, you

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:35.240
[Guest]: know, it begins in the 19th century, 1860s, Ravi Varma, all of that.

00:48:35.240 --> 00:48:38.440
[Guest]: So let me use more antiquated words there and then slowly build up.

00:48:38.440 --> 00:48:41.040
[Guest]: But that doesn't mean, you know, I write like that all the time.

00:48:41.040 --> 00:48:44.440
[Guest]: You know, somebody asked me, you know, how do you write with such antiquated words all

00:48:44.440 --> 00:48:45.440
[Guest]: the time?

00:48:45.440 --> 00:48:48.640
[Guest]: And I said, I don't actually write that kind of antiquated language.

00:48:48.640 --> 00:48:53.920
[Guest]: So there was some conscious sort of, you know, tailoring of the prose to that extent.

00:48:53.920 --> 00:48:55.720
[Guest]: A lot of it just came from reading.

00:48:55.720 --> 00:48:59.400
[Guest]: And you know, I think I may have said this in your on your podcast earlier, which is

00:48:59.400 --> 00:49:04.120
[Guest]: that fiction and especially Woodhouse had a great impact and in the way I write and

00:49:04.120 --> 00:49:09.720
[Guest]: try to sort of, what I think is subtle, but subtly, you know, weave in some humor into

00:49:09.720 --> 00:49:13.680
[Guest]: the into the text without necessarily pointing out saying, oh, this is humorous, you know,

00:49:13.680 --> 00:49:14.680
[Guest]: this is funny.

00:49:14.680 --> 00:49:15.680
[Guest]: I don't have to say this is funny.

00:49:15.680 --> 00:49:16.680
[Guest]: It's just the tone sometimes.

00:49:16.680 --> 00:49:18.940
[Guest]: It's just your choice of words sometimes.

00:49:18.940 --> 00:49:23.400
[Guest]: If you're trying to convey irreverence, you can do it without having to sort of mark it

00:49:23.400 --> 00:49:27.280
[Guest]: as irreverence and put a flag there saying that, oh, look, this is the irreverent section.

00:49:27.280 --> 00:49:31.880
[Guest]: So fiction, to some extent, did play a role in sort of giving me that general sense of

00:49:31.880 --> 00:49:33.120
[Guest]: how I wanted to sound.

00:49:33.120 --> 00:49:35.480
[Guest]: This is what people call the writer's voice.

00:49:35.480 --> 00:49:40.240
[Guest]: And you know, in my case, the voice was informed a great deal by fiction because I'd read plenty

00:49:40.240 --> 00:49:44.680
[Guest]: of nonfiction and there was often a certain dryness, except, for example, Dalrymple's

00:49:44.680 --> 00:49:45.680
[Guest]: work.

00:49:45.680 --> 00:49:49.160
[Guest]: William Dalrymple was the first person, I think, in India who wrote that kind of accessible,

00:49:49.160 --> 00:49:52.440
[Guest]: you know, storytelling format while also being good on research.

00:49:52.440 --> 00:49:56.480
[Guest]: And that to me was wonderful because this is exactly how I grew up hearing stories.

00:49:56.480 --> 00:49:58.880
[Guest]: This is exactly how I took an interest in the past.

00:49:58.880 --> 00:50:00.760
[Guest]: And if I did it, why not others?

00:50:00.760 --> 00:50:06.200
[Guest]: So yeah, there was, I would say that, you know, there was some conscious effort to please

00:50:06.200 --> 00:50:07.440
[Guest]: in the early drafts.

00:50:07.440 --> 00:50:12.280
[Guest]: But then as time passed, and as I got older, it became clear to me that, you know, let's

00:50:12.280 --> 00:50:17.600
[Guest]: just focus on telling the story well, and not get so focused on how it sounds to a certain

00:50:17.600 --> 00:50:19.880
[Guest]: person or an intended audience.

00:50:19.880 --> 00:50:23.760
[Guest]: I was very clear that I wanted the reader to want to turn the pages, you know, you have

00:50:23.760 --> 00:50:27.240
[Guest]: to keep the reader in mind, you can't just write to please yourself.

00:50:27.240 --> 00:50:28.240
[Guest]: Because that's another trap.

00:50:28.240 --> 00:50:30.800
[Guest]: You're writing just to please yourself and you're writing essentially for your mother

00:50:30.800 --> 00:50:31.800
[Guest]: and your aunt and your sister.

00:50:31.800 --> 00:50:35.280
[Guest]: There's nobody else who's going to read the book and enjoy it.

00:50:35.280 --> 00:50:39.820
[Guest]: So to a certain extent, yes, impressing the reader, or rather wooing the reader and persuading

00:50:39.820 --> 00:50:42.000
[Guest]: them to turn the pages is important.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:45.760
[Guest]: But then just tell the story and develop your own style and your own voice.

00:50:45.760 --> 00:50:49.720
[Guest]: More than any kind of creative or conscious polishing of the prose.

00:50:49.720 --> 00:50:54.040
[Guest]: It really is about figuring out how you want to tell that story and how you have a style

00:50:54.040 --> 00:50:57.520
[Guest]: in developing your own special way of doing that.

00:50:57.520 --> 00:51:01.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I love many of the touches of humor that come up in your prose and some of it

00:51:01.120 --> 00:51:05.040
[Amit Varma]: is of course, because of the content like in previous books, you've discussed mad elephants

00:51:05.040 --> 00:51:07.160
[Amit Varma]: being let loose on to punish people.

00:51:07.160 --> 00:51:11.480
[Amit Varma]: But in this book, you also have a bit about how they were royals who fornicated with elephants

00:51:11.480 --> 00:51:12.680
[Amit Varma]: allegedly.

00:51:12.680 --> 00:51:17.920
[Amit Varma]: And I loved your description of Malhar Rai Gaikwad, for example, as quote, textbook dubious,

00:51:17.920 --> 00:51:20.000
[Amit Varma]: stop quote, which is such a lovely phrase.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:21.880
[Amit Varma]: And of course, you go on to elaborate upon that.

00:51:21.880 --> 00:51:26.800
[Amit Varma]: And there is no textbook where those ways of dubiousness are mentioned, but it's quite

00:51:26.800 --> 00:51:27.960
[Amit Varma]: sort of delightful.

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:32.200
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about how the subjects are evolving in your head, because you do the ivory throne,

00:51:32.200 --> 00:51:37.160
[Amit Varma]: then you do the courtesan book is of course, a collection of your essays, and we had a

00:51:37.160 --> 00:51:39.120
[Amit Varma]: great episode on that as well.

00:51:39.120 --> 00:51:43.560
[Amit Varma]: And you have, you know, those middle centuries in the Deccan and all of that, which we did

00:51:43.560 --> 00:51:48.800
[Amit Varma]: our first episode on, I think, how did you arrive at the subject for False Lies?

00:51:48.800 --> 00:51:55.400
[Amit Varma]: And since so much of it is based on Raja Ravi Verma, like in a very loose sense, he is sort

00:51:55.400 --> 00:51:59.840
[Amit Varma]: of not the sutradhar per se, but like a sutradhar, he kind of travels through the story.

00:51:59.840 --> 00:52:03.960
[Amit Varma]: And in all of these princely states, he's been there, he's painted these people and

00:52:03.960 --> 00:52:07.160
[Amit Varma]: all of that, which seemed a very interesting thread.

00:52:07.160 --> 00:52:12.160
[Amit Varma]: So was it just sort of a continuation of that early interest into Raja Ravi Verma?

00:52:12.160 --> 00:52:16.160
[Amit Varma]: Or did you feel that this theme is something that needs to be tackled?

00:52:16.160 --> 00:52:17.520
[Amit Varma]: How did you arrive at this book?

00:52:17.520 --> 00:52:18.920
[Amit Varma]: And what else are you working on?

00:52:18.920 --> 00:52:21.400
[Amit Varma]: Because you said this is one of two books you're working on simultaneously.

00:52:21.400 --> 00:52:26.000
[Guest]: Yes, so, you know, the books that came before this, it's very interesting, Ivory Throne,

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:27.160
[Guest]: I came across a great story.

00:52:27.160 --> 00:52:30.800
[Guest]: I was very interested in Kerala history because my family is from Kerala.

00:52:30.800 --> 00:52:35.280
[Guest]: So it gave me an opportunity to dig into that and to tell that particular story.

00:52:35.280 --> 00:52:37.440
[Guest]: The Deccan book I did because I grew up in Maharashtra.

00:52:37.440 --> 00:52:41.440
[Guest]: And here, you know, as I said on your podcast as well, we discuss the Deccan in terms of

00:52:41.440 --> 00:52:45.480
[Guest]: the Mughals and the Marathas and we forget that there was a whole five century period

00:52:45.480 --> 00:52:47.760
[Guest]: where there were Islamic sultanates in the Deccan.

00:52:47.760 --> 00:52:50.240
[Guest]: And I thought, you know, I usually work on the colonial period.

00:52:50.240 --> 00:52:51.240
[Guest]: That is my strong point.

00:52:51.240 --> 00:52:52.880
[Guest]: I don't work on the early modern period.

00:52:52.880 --> 00:52:55.280
[Guest]: I don't read Persian, for example.

00:52:55.280 --> 00:52:59.080
[Guest]: So I knew that this was not a core area that I was interested in.

00:52:59.080 --> 00:53:03.160
[Guest]: But all the same as somebody who grew up here, all the same as somebody who only found academic

00:53:03.160 --> 00:53:07.120
[Guest]: texts on the Deccan, I thought there was a gap that needed to be filled.

00:53:07.120 --> 00:53:10.800
[Guest]: Something accessible for people to just go pick up in case they're interested in Deccan

00:53:10.800 --> 00:53:11.960
[Guest]: history.

00:53:11.960 --> 00:53:15.920
[Guest]: But this was also about challenging myself because the Ivory Throne was such a long book,

00:53:15.920 --> 00:53:17.360
[Guest]: 704 pages.

00:53:17.360 --> 00:53:19.640
[Guest]: Each chapter was about the length of a master's thesis.

00:53:19.640 --> 00:53:22.440
[Guest]: You know, my master's thesis in London was 15,000 words.

00:53:22.440 --> 00:53:25.960
[Guest]: And each chapter is between 12 and 20,000 words in that book.

00:53:25.960 --> 00:53:28.480
[Guest]: I got very used to having that kind of space.

00:53:28.480 --> 00:53:33.160
[Guest]: So it was the career and the life of these Maharanis in the 20th century spread over

00:53:33.160 --> 00:53:34.160
[Guest]: 700 pages.

00:53:34.160 --> 00:53:36.760
[Guest]: With rebel sultans, I was trying to do the opposite.

00:53:36.760 --> 00:53:41.640
[Guest]: Five centuries, you know, sort of compressed into just over 200 pages and the rest is notes.

00:53:41.640 --> 00:53:45.760
[Guest]: It was also a way to challenge myself to see if I could do that kind of brisker, faster

00:53:45.760 --> 00:53:47.960
[Guest]: sort of broad canvas storytelling.

00:53:47.960 --> 00:53:51.760
[Guest]: The book's done well, but what's interesting is people who've read Rebel Sultans have not

00:53:51.760 --> 00:53:55.720
[Guest]: necessarily liked Ivory Throne because it's such a big shift for them in style.

00:53:55.720 --> 00:53:59.440
[Guest]: People who've read the Ivory Throne first find Rebel Sultans too fast and too brisk

00:53:59.440 --> 00:54:01.520
[Guest]: for their comfort.

00:54:01.520 --> 00:54:05.040
[Guest]: But for me personally, it wasn't about impressing anybody as such.

00:54:05.040 --> 00:54:07.520
[Guest]: It was really about figuring out whether I could do it.

00:54:07.520 --> 00:54:10.880
[Guest]: And because the publisher liked it, it ended up getting published.

00:54:10.880 --> 00:54:15.040
[Guest]: Same with the collection of essays, because I wanted to see if I could encapsulate something

00:54:15.040 --> 00:54:16.040
[Guest]: in 1000 words.

00:54:16.040 --> 00:54:19.860
[Guest]: You know, your newspaper column has a fixed space when it's a print column.

00:54:19.860 --> 00:54:23.160
[Guest]: In that newspaper, you have that much real estate and you really can't go over your word

00:54:23.160 --> 00:54:24.600
[Guest]: limit any week.

00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:28.800
[Guest]: So each week trying to sort of condense a story, and obviously there would be strengths

00:54:28.800 --> 00:54:33.840
[Guest]: and weaknesses, but just the process of doing that was also a way for me to learn.

00:54:33.840 --> 00:54:34.880
[Guest]: And I was getting paid to learn.

00:54:34.880 --> 00:54:36.280
[Guest]: So why should I not do it?

00:54:36.280 --> 00:54:37.760
[Guest]: So that's how that happened.

00:54:37.760 --> 00:54:41.800
[Guest]: The fourth book, False Allies, is partly because, you know, when I was doing the Travenco book,

00:54:41.800 --> 00:54:46.040
[Guest]: that's when I realized that this whole cliche of princely states being about elephants,

00:54:46.040 --> 00:54:49.920
[Guest]: dancing girls, and the British sort of controlling these rajas is far too simplistic.

00:54:49.920 --> 00:54:54.360
[Guest]: Like in Travenco, you know, you have firstly internal palace dynamics, then there's a history

00:54:54.360 --> 00:54:57.880
[Guest]: of how the dynasty comes to power and that edifice of power is constructed.

00:54:57.880 --> 00:55:00.960
[Guest]: You have local politics, which has nothing to do with the nationalist struggle.

00:55:00.960 --> 00:55:03.420
[Guest]: It has nothing to do with what's happening in British India.

00:55:03.420 --> 00:55:07.580
[Guest]: It's rooted entirely in local caste, local religious identities, and what people would

00:55:07.580 --> 00:55:09.160
[Guest]: call communalism.

00:55:09.160 --> 00:55:12.960
[Guest]: And that sort of bubbles up, eventually it results in communism becoming powerful in

00:55:12.960 --> 00:55:14.800
[Guest]: that particular region.

00:55:14.800 --> 00:55:18.080
[Guest]: It's an internal history, and it's fascinating in its own right.

00:55:18.080 --> 00:55:21.340
[Guest]: It's when we say that, you know, history of India in the modern period, the emphasis is

00:55:21.340 --> 00:55:23.200
[Guest]: always on British India.

00:55:23.200 --> 00:55:27.500
[Guest]: But the princely states covered about 40% of the territory of this country, which means

00:55:27.500 --> 00:55:31.680
[Guest]: that what is happening, the micro histories of each of these states is also fascinating.

00:55:31.680 --> 00:55:36.440
[Guest]: And Travenco gave me a very in-depth sort of study of that, you know, understanding

00:55:36.440 --> 00:55:42.160
[Guest]: what that whole process was and why a single princely state like that could be so fascinating.

00:55:42.160 --> 00:55:45.280
[Guest]: And that then, you know, since then, I've wanted to do a princely states book.

00:55:45.280 --> 00:55:47.460
[Guest]: I was very keen to do a princely states book.

00:55:47.460 --> 00:55:51.480
[Guest]: But then, you know, the Ravi Varma thing happened because I was asked by the Ravi Varma Foundation

00:55:51.480 --> 00:55:55.560
[Guest]: in Bangalore to do a coffee table book on him and his journeys in various princely states,

00:55:55.560 --> 00:55:56.560
[Guest]: which I did.

00:55:56.560 --> 00:55:59.080
[Guest]: It was a private publication that came out last year.

00:55:59.080 --> 00:56:02.280
[Guest]: But they read it and they said, oh, you know, you should try and publish this for a general

00:56:02.280 --> 00:56:04.280
[Guest]: audience because we found it really interesting.

00:56:04.280 --> 00:56:07.280
[Guest]: So then I sort of spruced up the manuscript, made it longer.

00:56:07.280 --> 00:56:12.680
[Guest]: This is a 550 page book, even though, again, here, 150 pages are notes, but still.

00:56:12.680 --> 00:56:16.080
[Guest]: So I decided that what I would do is 562 states.

00:56:16.080 --> 00:56:17.560
[Guest]: You obviously can't choose.

00:56:17.560 --> 00:56:19.960
[Guest]: How do you choose from such a large number?

00:56:19.960 --> 00:56:25.240
[Guest]: One way is get rid of about 300-odd because when people say that India had 562 states,

00:56:25.240 --> 00:56:27.960
[Guest]: there's already a little bit of, let's say, negative thing in that.

00:56:27.960 --> 00:56:32.280
[Guest]: Saying, oh, look, so many of them, chota mota rajas everywhere, none of them had any value.

00:56:32.280 --> 00:56:37.480
[Guest]: The frank truth is about 300 states were spread over just 6,500 square miles in what is called

00:56:37.480 --> 00:56:38.480
[Guest]: Kathiawar.

00:56:38.480 --> 00:56:41.760
[Guest]: So you get rid of them, you're down to just about 400 and something states.

00:56:41.760 --> 00:56:47.280
[Guest]: The real major states who qualify, frankly, to be called partially sovereign states, as

00:56:47.280 --> 00:56:51.540
[Guest]: opposed to zamindaris, jagirs, etc., were just over a hundred states.

00:56:51.540 --> 00:56:54.560
[Guest]: So that reduces your options a great deal.

00:56:54.560 --> 00:56:55.800
[Guest]: And in that, again, there's variety.

00:56:55.800 --> 00:56:59.960
[Guest]: We think of Maharajas as drowning in alcohol, sitting with their dancing girls.

00:56:59.960 --> 00:57:03.600
[Guest]: Maharaja of Gondal, who ruled for decades, was a doctor and used to practice as a doctor

00:57:03.600 --> 00:57:04.600
[Guest]: in his state.

00:57:04.600 --> 00:57:07.600
[Guest]: Ruled over 1,000 square miles, but interesting character.

00:57:07.600 --> 00:57:10.720
[Guest]: Maharaja of Kuchin was, you would not find him in the lap of a dancing girl.

00:57:10.720 --> 00:57:14.580
[Guest]: He would be poring over his Sanskrit manuscripts, very different kind of character.

00:57:14.580 --> 00:57:18.240
[Guest]: But also the bigger states were interesting because there's more happening within these

00:57:18.240 --> 00:57:19.240
[Guest]: states.

00:57:19.240 --> 00:57:23.760
[Guest]: So a state like Baroda, for example, you have a Maratha royal family ruling over Gujaratis.

00:57:23.760 --> 00:57:28.040
[Guest]: The political dynamics in that state are very different because of that natural, to a lot

00:57:28.040 --> 00:57:31.280
[Guest]: of the Gujaratis there in Baroda state, it was the Marathas who were the colonizers,

00:57:31.280 --> 00:57:33.080
[Guest]: not the East India Company, not the British.

00:57:33.080 --> 00:57:35.480
[Guest]: When you refer to an outsider, it is your king.

00:57:35.480 --> 00:57:37.000
[Guest]: He's an outside invader who's coming.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:40.640
[Guest]: So how did that polity and how did its system evolve?

00:57:40.640 --> 00:57:41.960
[Guest]: That was one question.

00:57:41.960 --> 00:57:46.240
[Guest]: Mysore, you have an aristocracy that is powerful, but numerically very small.

00:57:46.240 --> 00:57:49.000
[Guest]: And politics is controlled by the vokaligas and the lingayats.

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:52.600
[Guest]: These are two powerful rural elements, which is still the case in Karnataka.

00:57:52.600 --> 00:57:56.100
[Guest]: Even now in Karnataka, Karnataka politics is dominated by these two communities.

00:57:56.100 --> 00:58:00.080
[Guest]: And you can actually trace that back into princely Mysore politics as well.

00:58:00.080 --> 00:58:04.360
[Guest]: You go to a state like Pudukottai, different set of issues because the ruling caste is

00:58:04.360 --> 00:58:06.560
[Guest]: technically a low caste of robbers.

00:58:06.560 --> 00:58:10.900
[Guest]: You know, they're a robber caste, the very term kallar means to rob or thieves.

00:58:10.900 --> 00:58:12.920
[Guest]: And they're the ones who become kings here.

00:58:12.920 --> 00:58:15.320
[Guest]: Dynamics are very different compared to other places.

00:58:15.320 --> 00:58:20.080
[Guest]: Rajputana, on the other hand, completely complicated because the king is present and you would

00:58:20.080 --> 00:58:22.840
[Guest]: think the king only has to deal with the British, but not true.

00:58:22.840 --> 00:58:27.260
[Guest]: The king has subordinate vassal lords who are very autonomous in their own territories.

00:58:27.260 --> 00:58:31.040
[Guest]: And he's also trying to fight off their efforts to reduce his power.

00:58:31.040 --> 00:58:35.200
[Guest]: So each of these states have almost distinct political structures.

00:58:35.200 --> 00:58:38.880
[Guest]: Each of their rulers is dealing with a different set of pressures.

00:58:38.880 --> 00:58:43.600
[Guest]: So colonialism and the rajas wasn't just about the British coming, the raja hosting a darbar,

00:58:43.600 --> 00:58:44.600
[Guest]: people having parties.

00:58:44.600 --> 00:58:50.120
[Guest]: There's a lot of political nuance and intricacy and layers of politics that you can see in

00:58:50.120 --> 00:58:51.560
[Guest]: these princely states.

00:58:51.560 --> 00:58:54.960
[Guest]: And I was very keen to sort of, you know, do a book on these princely states.

00:58:54.960 --> 00:58:58.960
[Guest]: Here, Ravi Varma comes in because this man went, firstly, he's from a princely state.

00:58:58.960 --> 00:59:02.200
[Guest]: His sisters-in-law, his granddaughters were rulers of those princely states.

00:59:02.200 --> 00:59:04.120
[Guest]: They were part of the royal family.

00:59:04.120 --> 00:59:07.140
[Guest]: And then he also traveled through some of these major princely states doing portraits

00:59:07.140 --> 00:59:08.360
[Guest]: for the rajas.

00:59:08.360 --> 00:59:10.800
[Guest]: So I thought, you take him, follow his career.

00:59:10.800 --> 00:59:14.000
[Guest]: So 1860 to say 1880, he's working in Travancore.

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:18.160
[Guest]: In late 1870s, for the first time, he leaves the state and does a portrait commission in

00:59:18.160 --> 00:59:19.160
[Guest]: Pudukottai.

00:59:19.160 --> 00:59:21.600
[Guest]: So that gives me an opportunity to discuss Pudukottai.

00:59:21.600 --> 00:59:23.480
[Guest]: Then 1880s, he comes to Baroda.

00:59:23.480 --> 00:59:25.600
[Guest]: So you get a chapter on Baroda.

00:59:25.600 --> 00:59:27.240
[Guest]: Then he comes off to Mysore.

00:59:27.240 --> 00:59:28.640
[Guest]: So you get a chapter on Mysore.

00:59:28.640 --> 00:59:32.280
[Guest]: And shortly before his death, he goes to Udaipur and therefore you have a chapter on Mewar.

00:59:32.280 --> 00:59:35.780
[Guest]: 1906, 1901 he goes to Udaipur, 1906 he dies.

00:59:35.780 --> 00:59:36.780
[Guest]: And that is it.

00:59:36.780 --> 00:59:41.400
[Guest]: You know, it sort of enabled me to weave five states, rather different in their internal

00:59:41.400 --> 00:59:45.720
[Guest]: composition, rather different in their internal politics, and try and sort of use him as the

00:59:45.720 --> 00:59:46.760
[Guest]: common thread.

00:59:46.760 --> 00:59:48.760
[Guest]: In many chapters, he's just a cameo appearance.

00:59:48.760 --> 00:59:51.160
[Guest]: He's in the background, he's visiting.

00:59:51.160 --> 00:59:53.680
[Guest]: And I'll describe the portrait he's done of the ruler.

00:59:53.680 --> 00:59:57.000
[Guest]: But the chapters really are about the states, about the rulers and the states and what's

00:59:57.000 --> 00:59:58.920
[Guest]: happening inside these states.

00:59:58.920 --> 01:00:04.000
[Guest]: He's merely an excuse to sort of look at those states, otherwise, choosing individual states

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:08.160
[Guest]: and then sort of having a mechanical sort of one chapter per state without necessarily

01:00:08.160 --> 01:00:09.460
[Guest]: connecting them.

01:00:09.460 --> 01:00:13.920
[Guest]: That didn't appeal to me too much here, he may be a very slender thread, but he's a thread.

01:00:13.920 --> 01:00:16.600
[Guest]: So I thought I would I would structure the book that way.

01:00:16.600 --> 01:00:19.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, he kind of appears in things much the way Hitchcock appeared in his films, like

01:00:19.920 --> 01:00:22.200
[Amit Varma]: Hitchcock always made these guest appearances in his films.

01:00:22.200 --> 01:00:25.520
[Amit Varma]: And there's one film where I think these people are marooned on a boat.

01:00:25.520 --> 01:00:27.240
[Amit Varma]: So you wonder how will he make an appearance.

01:00:27.240 --> 01:00:32.800
[Amit Varma]: But if I remember correctly, there's a newspaper cutting and his picture is in that.

01:00:32.800 --> 01:00:35.680
[Amit Varma]: But of course, all those stories were shaped by Hitchcock here.

01:00:35.680 --> 01:00:40.960
[Amit Varma]: I think in many of these cases, Raja Ravi Verma was just kind of a bystander, a bit

01:00:40.960 --> 01:00:41.960
[Amit Varma]: player.

01:00:41.960 --> 01:00:47.280
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, obviously, it is convenient for, you know, the British to paint the Maharajas

01:00:47.280 --> 01:00:51.640
[Amit Varma]: as dissolute, because then they can advance a narrative that listen, Indians can't govern

01:00:51.640 --> 01:00:53.560
[Amit Varma]: themselves, we have to do it for them.

01:00:53.560 --> 01:00:58.920
[Amit Varma]: And equally, it is convenient for the congressmen or the freedom fighters who eventually, you

01:00:58.920 --> 01:01:02.920
[Amit Varma]: know, take over independent India to paint them that way, because then they can justify

01:01:02.920 --> 01:01:07.560
[Amit Varma]: what in a sense was their own act of colonialism, just getting rid of all the princely states,

01:01:07.560 --> 01:01:12.040
[Amit Varma]: using the colonial apparatus which exists to this day of predatory Indian state and

01:01:12.040 --> 01:01:13.040
[Amit Varma]: just using that.

01:01:13.040 --> 01:01:15.000
[Amit Varma]: There's a convenient narrative for both of them.

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:19.320
[Amit Varma]: Now, what of course you've done is that shown in this book, given glimpses of the multitudes

01:01:19.320 --> 01:01:20.880
[Amit Varma]: that are contained within.

01:01:20.880 --> 01:01:25.640
[Amit Varma]: But I think the danger for anyone looking at the past, not just a historian, must be

01:01:25.640 --> 01:01:29.320
[Amit Varma]: the danger of hindsight that you already know what has happened.

01:01:29.320 --> 01:01:33.680
[Amit Varma]: And that can sometimes change the way you look at stuff in the past.

01:01:33.680 --> 01:01:38.960
[Amit Varma]: How difficult is it to actually make that imaginative leap, where you actually put yourself

01:01:38.960 --> 01:01:39.960
[Amit Varma]: in somebody's eyes, right?

01:01:39.960 --> 01:01:41.560
[Amit Varma]: What does the world look like to me?

01:01:41.560 --> 01:01:43.640
[Amit Varma]: Like today, we know how history unfolded.

01:01:43.640 --> 01:01:49.280
[Amit Varma]: If you're sitting in 1860 in say, Travancore, you haven't heard the word colonialism, the

01:01:49.280 --> 01:01:56.040
[Amit Varma]: idea of India, you know, what is it, you know, maybe it's not there for you.

01:01:56.040 --> 01:01:58.280
[Amit Varma]: Maybe it's incredibly nebulous.

01:01:58.280 --> 01:02:02.560
[Amit Varma]: So is that a shift that you keep making and that you have to remind yourself to make like

01:02:02.560 --> 01:02:07.080
[Amit Varma]: I remember, you know, one of the main characters in your book is T Madhava Rao.

01:02:07.080 --> 01:02:12.700
[Amit Varma]: And you point out about how, when he was dying, despite his immense eminence and the admiration

01:02:12.700 --> 01:02:16.360
[Amit Varma]: he was held in and the great work he did in administrative terms in the princely states

01:02:16.360 --> 01:02:20.840
[Amit Varma]: where he was the main administrator and the regard that the Empire held him in.

01:02:20.840 --> 01:02:24.640
[Amit Varma]: At the end of his life, he was kind of irrelevant because a modern day radical freedom fighters

01:02:24.640 --> 01:02:28.600
[Amit Varma]: who were coming up were like, oh, this guy is a stooge and this guy is like supporting

01:02:28.600 --> 01:02:30.560
[Amit Varma]: the Empire and all of that.

01:02:30.560 --> 01:02:36.040
[Amit Varma]: And even they, you know, even a person sitting in 1890 is not making that imaginative leap

01:02:36.040 --> 01:02:38.120
[Amit Varma]: or what the world looked like in 1880.

01:02:38.120 --> 01:02:43.000
[Amit Varma]: So from this distance, how hard is it and is that something that you've learned to habitually

01:02:43.000 --> 01:02:48.120
[Amit Varma]: do to first construct that contemporary world, so you can see it from their eyes?

01:02:48.120 --> 01:02:50.080
[Amit Varma]: Or do you have to keep reminding yourself to do that?

01:02:50.080 --> 01:02:52.720
[Amit Varma]: Or do you feel that you've ever fallen into that trap sometimes?

01:02:52.720 --> 01:02:53.720
[Guest]: No, this is the thing, right?

01:02:53.720 --> 01:02:58.360
[Guest]: So as somebody who gets more and more used to sort of dealing with historical material,

01:02:58.360 --> 01:03:01.560
[Guest]: you realize that none of these narratives can be taken for granted.

01:03:01.560 --> 01:03:05.920
[Guest]: All these narratives were constructed either by somebody, not one individual, but by a

01:03:05.920 --> 01:03:08.160
[Guest]: generation for a certain purpose.

01:03:08.160 --> 01:03:11.360
[Guest]: And therefore, that's the logic for the narrative's existence.

01:03:11.360 --> 01:03:14.000
[Guest]: But you know, with the princely states, for example, we would often assume that these

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:18.600
[Guest]: were always inevitably going to fail, for example, inevitably, they would have to go,

01:03:18.600 --> 01:03:19.600
[Guest]: which is not true.

01:03:19.600 --> 01:03:24.120
[Guest]: If you look at the evidence, as late as the 1930s, there was a seat at the table during

01:03:24.120 --> 01:03:28.960
[Guest]: the negotiations of the 1935 Government of India Act, which is what the British called

01:03:28.960 --> 01:03:30.760
[Guest]: India's constitution in that year.

01:03:30.760 --> 01:03:31.760
[Guest]: They had a seat at the table.

01:03:31.760 --> 01:03:35.400
[Guest]: There was actually a federal system that was being planned where the princes would be a

01:03:35.400 --> 01:03:37.840
[Guest]: part of the political structure.

01:03:37.840 --> 01:03:41.880
[Guest]: Go back to the 1860s, nobody would have dreamed that 100 years later, the princes would not

01:03:41.880 --> 01:03:42.880
[Guest]: exist.

01:03:42.880 --> 01:03:45.880
[Guest]: You know, we now think that, oh, they were feudalistic, they were backward, therefore

01:03:45.880 --> 01:03:47.920
[Guest]: nobody, we don't need to respect them.

01:03:47.920 --> 01:03:52.040
[Guest]: The frank truth is that in the 1860s and 70s, people did respect them, the nationalists

01:03:52.040 --> 01:03:53.040
[Guest]: respected them.

01:03:53.040 --> 01:03:57.000
[Guest]: For the nationalists, for example, the British interfering in a princely state and say, toppling

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:00.080
[Guest]: a Maharaja, replacing him by somebody else.

01:04:00.080 --> 01:04:01.720
[Guest]: These were not some things the British were supposed to do.

01:04:01.720 --> 01:04:05.520
[Guest]: It was a nationalist cause to preserve the autonomy of the states because these were

01:04:05.520 --> 01:04:09.360
[Guest]: the final enclaves where the British did not directly affect policy.

01:04:09.360 --> 01:04:12.760
[Guest]: You know, it did not directly affect the lives of Indians, it was where Indians were able

01:04:12.760 --> 01:04:13.760
[Guest]: to rule.

01:04:13.760 --> 01:04:17.120
[Guest]: Dadabhai Naoroji, if you've read Dinyar Patel's book, he was on your show, you know, there's

01:04:17.120 --> 01:04:21.300
[Guest]: this quote I've used from his book in this book, which is where Dadabhai Naoroji comes

01:04:21.300 --> 01:04:25.760
[Guest]: to Baroda as Diwan, we've never heard of this, we always talk about Dadabhai Naoroji winning

01:04:25.760 --> 01:04:30.560
[Guest]: an election to Parliament in Britain, but not that he was a Diwan in a princely state.

01:04:30.560 --> 01:04:33.640
[Guest]: And he says that we've not come to serve the man, we've come to serve the cause.

01:04:33.640 --> 01:04:37.820
[Guest]: And the cause is precisely this, preserving the autonomy of the princely state, preserving

01:04:37.820 --> 01:04:40.320
[Guest]: it from British inroads, because that matters.

01:04:40.320 --> 01:04:41.320
[Guest]: It mattered to nationalists.

01:04:41.320 --> 01:04:42.320
[Guest]: M.G.

01:04:42.320 --> 01:04:46.420
[Guest]: Ranade, when he, if you look at his collected writings, he's got this bit where he talks

01:04:46.420 --> 01:04:48.540
[Guest]: about the future Indian Parliament.

01:04:48.540 --> 01:04:52.720
[Guest]: And he actually sees it as a house of commons represented by people in British India, and

01:04:52.720 --> 01:04:57.400
[Guest]: a house of lords, where the princes and their people are represented, which suggests that

01:04:57.400 --> 01:05:02.800
[Guest]: he also saw the princes very much as a legitimate element in Indian politics, not illegitimate.

01:05:02.800 --> 01:05:08.440
[Guest]: Gandhiji, as late as the mid 1930s, he was always hesitant to interfere in princely states.

01:05:08.440 --> 01:05:11.960
[Guest]: As late as the early mid 1930s, he was saying that, you know, interfering in a princely

01:05:11.960 --> 01:05:15.820
[Guest]: state is like interfering in Afghanistan or Sri Lanka, you know, that's not something

01:05:15.820 --> 01:05:19.560
[Guest]: the Congress party can do, because we are only focused on British India, where the British

01:05:19.560 --> 01:05:20.600
[Guest]: are directly.

01:05:20.600 --> 01:05:23.920
[Guest]: The funny thing is, Dadabhai Naoroji won the election in Parliament, and that election

01:05:23.920 --> 01:05:27.440
[Guest]: was funded by a lot of Maharajas, you know, they were the ones helping him, because they

01:05:27.440 --> 01:05:33.040
[Guest]: had an active interest in having somebody, an Indian, a brown, or as the British, I think

01:05:33.040 --> 01:05:36.360
[Guest]: a British politician called him a black man, you know, wanting him in Parliament, because

01:05:36.360 --> 01:05:41.080
[Guest]: he, that was their way of sort of giving a poke at the imperial power.

01:05:41.080 --> 01:05:45.160
[Guest]: In the late 19th century, and from a good chunk of the early 20th century, the nationalists

01:05:45.160 --> 01:05:48.000
[Guest]: and the princes were actually more or less on the same page.

01:05:48.000 --> 01:05:49.000
[Guest]: R.C.

01:05:49.000 --> 01:05:52.200
[Guest]: Dutt, he was a Congress president, also ended up becoming Diwan of Baroda.

01:05:52.200 --> 01:05:56.640
[Guest]: Madhav Rao was, in the early phase, he was part of the Congress process, he was at the

01:05:56.640 --> 01:05:59.440
[Guest]: reception committee in Madras, etc.

01:05:59.440 --> 01:06:02.520
[Guest]: You know, a number of overlaps existed in this form.

01:06:02.520 --> 01:06:03.520
[Guest]: The historian K.M.

01:06:03.520 --> 01:06:07.240
[Guest]: Panikkar has written about how it was in the princely states that a whole generation of

01:06:07.240 --> 01:06:11.480
[Guest]: talented Indians, they would all join as clerks into the British service, even if they lived

01:06:11.480 --> 01:06:12.480
[Guest]: in British India.

01:06:12.480 --> 01:06:15.800
[Guest]: And then after a few promotions, they would realize there was a glass ceiling, because

01:06:15.800 --> 01:06:20.360
[Guest]: of the color of their skin, they could never go beyond being a sort of glorified secretary.

01:06:20.360 --> 01:06:23.980
[Guest]: Your titles may change, but you are always a white man secretary.

01:06:23.980 --> 01:06:28.360
[Guest]: Those men who managed to rise above this usually moved to princely states, where they would

01:06:28.360 --> 01:06:33.840
[Guest]: become Diwans, where they would become ministers, and thus sort of create not just a career

01:06:33.840 --> 01:06:36.020
[Guest]: for themselves, but also a reputation.

01:06:36.020 --> 01:06:41.200
[Guest]: And a reputation as Indians governing Indians and doing it well, doing it sometimes at standards

01:06:41.200 --> 01:06:45.840
[Guest]: that exceeded those in British India, it gave a lot of Indians pride.

01:06:45.840 --> 01:06:48.940
[Guest]: These were heroes of that generation, especially in the 19th century.

01:06:48.940 --> 01:06:52.520
[Guest]: You mentioned T. Madhav Rao, he studied in Madras in a British school, he joined the

01:06:52.520 --> 01:06:57.120
[Guest]: clerical service of what was then the East India Company, still ruling in India.

01:06:57.120 --> 01:07:01.120
[Guest]: But then around 1850, he transfers to Travenco State as a tutor.

01:07:01.120 --> 01:07:05.880
[Guest]: Now the local Maharaj in Travenco wants an English tutor, because he knows that in this

01:07:05.880 --> 01:07:10.800
[Guest]: new world, in this new colonized sort of space that is India, the English language is extremely

01:07:10.800 --> 01:07:11.800
[Guest]: important.

01:07:11.800 --> 01:07:15.800
[Guest]: He already speaks English himself, but he wants his nephews also well-trained and well-tutored.

01:07:15.800 --> 01:07:19.280
[Guest]: He gets Madhav Rao to come and teach them and become their tutor.

01:07:19.280 --> 01:07:23.440
[Guest]: And that, Madhav Rao impresses the Maharaja that he's very soon after given a very high

01:07:23.440 --> 01:07:27.200
[Guest]: post in government, just two steps below that of the chief minister.

01:07:27.200 --> 01:07:31.200
[Guest]: A few years later, when it comes to finding a new chief minister, there's a local candidate

01:07:31.200 --> 01:07:33.000
[Guest]: who's senior, and then there's Madhav Rao.

01:07:33.000 --> 01:07:36.560
[Guest]: Madhav Rao wins because he speaks English, he's got lots of friends in Madras.

01:07:36.560 --> 01:07:37.680
[Guest]: So he becomes a bridge.

01:07:37.680 --> 01:07:41.760
[Guest]: On the one hand, the colonial state is happy with him because he's, you know, what Macaulay

01:07:41.760 --> 01:07:45.400
[Guest]: called on the face of it, you know, a man brown in color, but English in tastes and

01:07:45.400 --> 01:07:49.720
[Guest]: speaks English well, writes very well, has read everything that the English value as

01:07:49.720 --> 01:07:50.720
[Guest]: good literature.

01:07:50.720 --> 01:07:55.200
[Guest]: But the Maharaja values him because he can become a good spokesperson for the state.

01:07:55.200 --> 01:07:56.200
[Guest]: And that's what he becomes.

01:07:56.200 --> 01:07:59.480
[Guest]: He becomes Diwan of the state and starts actively developing the state.

01:07:59.480 --> 01:08:03.400
[Guest]: He knows that, how do I prevent British intervention in the state?

01:08:03.400 --> 01:08:07.040
[Guest]: They can intervene if revenues are bad, they can intervene if there are social injustices,

01:08:07.040 --> 01:08:10.720
[Guest]: they can intervene if there aren't enough roads, public works, schools, let me get all

01:08:10.720 --> 01:08:11.720
[Guest]: of these things done.

01:08:11.720 --> 01:08:15.280
[Guest]: So you have a huge budget for public works, you start diverting funds into schools, you've

01:08:15.280 --> 01:08:18.360
[Guest]: got hundreds of schools being set up in the vernacular languages.

01:08:18.360 --> 01:08:21.480
[Guest]: The Maharaja himself transforms the way he dresses.

01:08:21.480 --> 01:08:26.760
[Guest]: From your colorful Persianate robes, you start wearing these sober, almost dull and boring

01:08:26.760 --> 01:08:30.600
[Guest]: English type clothes because you want to show that you're also an active ruler.

01:08:30.600 --> 01:08:34.800
[Guest]: You're not like a puppet or you're not an exhibit who is meant to look exotic.

01:08:34.800 --> 01:08:39.480
[Guest]: There was an active effort to show that no, we can actually govern and we can do so far

01:08:39.480 --> 01:08:41.200
[Guest]: better than the British.

01:08:41.200 --> 01:08:44.600
[Guest]: And you see Madhavrao moving from Travancore, then he ends up in Indore for a while, then

01:08:44.600 --> 01:08:48.960
[Guest]: he ends up in Baroda, he lobbies, my friend Rahul Sagar is doing a biography, he told

01:08:48.960 --> 01:08:53.240
[Guest]: me, I found out in one of his essays, it's not in my book, where he says that Madhavrao

01:08:53.240 --> 01:08:58.240
[Guest]: even lobbied for the Diwanship of Mysore because these were the important big states.

01:08:58.240 --> 01:09:02.640
[Guest]: And for him, it was his life's mission to go and improve these states and make successes

01:09:02.640 --> 01:09:03.640
[Guest]: of these states.

01:09:03.640 --> 01:09:08.480
[Guest]: And for the Rajas, they needed suitably trained Indians, so they didn't need to get the colonial

01:09:08.480 --> 01:09:09.480
[Guest]: state involved.

01:09:09.480 --> 01:09:12.720
[Guest]: There was this wonderful sort of compact between these two people.

01:09:12.720 --> 01:09:16.360
[Guest]: The Indian National Congress, very hesitant for the longest time to discuss the princely

01:09:16.360 --> 01:09:18.280
[Guest]: states, partly because the Maharajas were funding them.

01:09:18.280 --> 01:09:21.760
[Guest]: You know, in 1887, Viceroy tells the Maharaja, stop funding them.

01:09:21.760 --> 01:09:23.480
[Guest]: He tells Mysore, Mysore stops.

01:09:23.480 --> 01:09:28.280
[Guest]: But as late as 1901, Sayajirao Gaikwad of Baroda still secretly giving money.

01:09:28.280 --> 01:09:33.080
[Guest]: One scholar has written about how even into the late 1920s and 30s, covertly, a lot of

01:09:33.080 --> 01:09:37.680
[Guest]: the Maharajas were paying the Congress because they wanted the British to be held to account.

01:09:37.680 --> 01:09:41.760
[Guest]: They had an incentive in keeping the British on their toes because they were not passive.

01:09:41.760 --> 01:09:45.380
[Guest]: They were not just, they didn't just pretend to be dead and allow the British to do everything

01:09:45.380 --> 01:09:46.380
[Guest]: they wanted to them.

01:09:46.380 --> 01:09:48.200
[Guest]: They actually did try to fight.

01:09:48.200 --> 01:09:52.960
[Guest]: It was not military means, obviously, as rulers of states, it was not satyagraha on the streets

01:09:52.960 --> 01:09:53.960
[Guest]: either.

01:09:53.960 --> 01:09:57.880
[Guest]: But it was the subtle and rather interesting ways by which they stood up to the British,

01:09:57.880 --> 01:09:59.360
[Guest]: sometimes by making statements.

01:09:59.360 --> 01:10:04.040
[Guest]: You know, Mysore, when the royal family was returned to the state after 50 years of British

01:10:04.040 --> 01:10:09.120
[Guest]: control, it became almost like this cult in Mysore to have industrialization and to sort

01:10:09.120 --> 01:10:12.360
[Guest]: of develop the state as an industrial headquarters for India.

01:10:12.360 --> 01:10:16.160
[Guest]: By the 1940s, the Maharaja didn't sanction it because he thought it would be a white

01:10:16.160 --> 01:10:17.160
[Guest]: elephant.

01:10:17.160 --> 01:10:21.240
[Guest]: But Mysore was actively considering setting up a car manufacturing unit because the sort

01:10:21.240 --> 01:10:26.120
[Guest]: of technocracy that controlled the state really wanted an Indian princely state in the subcontinent

01:10:26.120 --> 01:10:29.400
[Guest]: to become this huge hub of automobile manufacturing.

01:10:29.400 --> 01:10:32.560
[Guest]: Because everybody believed, no, no, backward country, poor, brown people, what are they

01:10:32.560 --> 01:10:33.560
[Guest]: going to do?

01:10:33.560 --> 01:10:35.960
[Guest]: They don't have the scientific and technical prowess.

01:10:35.960 --> 01:10:40.960
[Guest]: And Mysore invested a lot of its money, lost a lot of its money, pulling off these industrial

01:10:40.960 --> 01:10:44.080
[Guest]: experiments simply to make a political statement.

01:10:44.080 --> 01:10:45.760
[Guest]: Many of these ventures didn't turn profits.

01:10:45.760 --> 01:10:49.360
[Guest]: The Rajas knew they would never turn profits, you know, for decades they did not bring them

01:10:49.360 --> 01:10:52.320
[Guest]: a single penny in terms of, you know, returns.

01:10:52.320 --> 01:10:56.720
[Guest]: But they would still pour money into it more and more and more simply because it was important

01:10:56.720 --> 01:11:01.560
[Guest]: to the identity of the state as, you know, a very industrial and forward-looking place

01:11:01.560 --> 01:11:06.680
[Guest]: as a way of sort of taking the sting out of the British argument that natives were no

01:11:06.680 --> 01:11:09.880
[Guest]: good when it came to science and technology.

01:11:09.880 --> 01:11:13.800
[Guest]: Each of these states have these very interesting ways of countering the British, sometimes

01:11:13.800 --> 01:11:18.660
[Guest]: through ceremony, sometimes through ritual, you know, the way you treat your resident.

01:11:18.660 --> 01:11:22.440
[Guest]: And the British sometimes, you know, in their texts and writings, they make it seem as though

01:11:22.440 --> 01:11:26.640
[Guest]: these Rajas were too obsessed with ritual, etc. which is not true because the British

01:11:26.640 --> 01:11:27.920
[Guest]: were just as obsessed.

01:11:27.920 --> 01:11:31.360
[Guest]: So the British would come and fight with the Rajas saying, why have you put my agents,

01:11:31.360 --> 01:11:34.560
[Guest]: my representatives chair on the left side, the right has greater honor, it has to be

01:11:34.560 --> 01:11:35.560
[Guest]: on the right side.

01:11:35.560 --> 01:11:38.320
[Guest]: Then the Raja will fight back saying, no, no, no, the left is always where the chair

01:11:38.320 --> 01:11:39.320
[Guest]: has been.

01:11:39.320 --> 01:11:40.840
[Guest]: So you can't move to the right.

01:11:40.840 --> 01:11:42.520
[Guest]: It's actually a political negotiation.

01:11:42.520 --> 01:11:45.280
[Guest]: These are not eccentrics who are fighting over the place of a chair.

01:11:45.280 --> 01:11:47.380
[Guest]: The place of the chair has political meaning.

01:11:47.380 --> 01:11:51.280
[Guest]: So if the Raja allows this man to come and sit on the right side, he's essentially acknowledging

01:11:51.280 --> 01:11:55.840
[Guest]: that person's capacity to not only bully him, but also show publicly that this person has

01:11:55.840 --> 01:11:57.400
[Guest]: greater power over the Raja.

01:11:57.400 --> 01:12:00.520
[Guest]: So the Raja will insist as far as possible to keep him on the left.

01:12:00.520 --> 01:12:04.520
[Guest]: In Hyderabad, the Nizams would not allow the residents to wear shoes in Darbars and the

01:12:04.520 --> 01:12:08.320
[Guest]: English found this really insulting because, you know, for them, it was a mark of their

01:12:08.320 --> 01:12:13.880
[Guest]: privilege and status to walk into a Darbar with their feet covered, the Nizams wouldn't

01:12:13.880 --> 01:12:14.880
[Guest]: allow it.

01:12:14.880 --> 01:12:17.120
[Guest]: Two generations this dispute went on.

01:12:17.120 --> 01:12:20.800
[Guest]: Eventually they succeeded when there was a little boy on the throne and there was a regent

01:12:20.800 --> 01:12:21.940
[Guest]: who was actually ruling.

01:12:21.940 --> 01:12:25.720
[Guest]: The regent had some other negotiations with them, a return of territory, other issues.

01:12:25.720 --> 01:12:30.160
[Guest]: So he said, okay, fine, we'll let you win here so I can gain something bigger later.

01:12:30.160 --> 01:12:33.880
[Guest]: And that's when the British finally get the right to wear shoes in the Nizam's court.

01:12:33.880 --> 01:12:38.040
[Guest]: On the face of it, if you write a sort of sexified version of the princely states, haha,

01:12:38.040 --> 01:12:42.320
[Guest]: these frivolous people fighting over shoes, but no, it was really politics through ritual.

01:12:42.320 --> 01:12:44.960
[Guest]: These small details all had political meaning.

01:12:44.960 --> 01:12:50.000
[Guest]: You know, before Bahadur Shah Zafar was, was exiled in 1858, if a viceroy or a governor

01:12:50.000 --> 01:12:54.160
[Guest]: general passed Delhi, there was one, I think, forget his name, I think it was Lord Hastings

01:12:54.160 --> 01:12:57.520
[Guest]: who didn't, would not go to Delhi because he knew that if he went there, he would have

01:12:57.520 --> 01:13:01.920
[Guest]: to go and meet the emperor and he would have to take the supplicant position for formal

01:13:01.920 --> 01:13:02.920
[Guest]: purposes.

01:13:02.920 --> 01:13:05.680
[Guest]: And he said, no, the East India Company is now supreme, I will not do it.

01:13:05.680 --> 01:13:08.440
[Guest]: So he didn't go, but all the same, he didn't want to upset the Mughal emperor.

01:13:08.440 --> 01:13:11.120
[Guest]: So he sent him gifts, some carriage or something.

01:13:11.120 --> 01:13:14.940
[Guest]: So he was trying to sort of come to a compromise, but the Mughal emperor would insist that

01:13:14.940 --> 01:13:18.040
[Guest]: if the governor general came, he would have to take a supplicant position.

01:13:18.040 --> 01:13:22.560
[Guest]: The Mughal had no power, but that ritual allowed him that final sort of capacity to make a

01:13:22.560 --> 01:13:24.200
[Guest]: political statement.

01:13:24.200 --> 01:13:27.520
[Guest]: And so the British were also doing politics through ritual.

01:13:27.520 --> 01:13:30.080
[Guest]: They were also very much part of this game.

01:13:30.080 --> 01:13:31.080
[Guest]: And so were the nationalists.

01:13:31.080 --> 01:13:34.640
[Guest]: You know, when there was this boy, Maharaja of Kulapur, he's a footnote in the book, I

01:13:34.640 --> 01:13:36.200
[Guest]: couldn't keep him in the main text.

01:13:36.200 --> 01:13:38.800
[Guest]: He ended up being killed by his British warden.

01:13:38.800 --> 01:13:39.800
[Guest]: He was beaten to death.

01:13:39.800 --> 01:13:40.800
[Guest]: It was quite tragic.

01:13:40.800 --> 01:13:42.760
[Guest]: Young boy in his teens.

01:13:42.760 --> 01:13:46.560
[Guest]: He even tried to run away at one point because of how much they were trying to control him.

01:13:46.560 --> 01:13:50.960
[Guest]: It was a huge issue for the nationalist press, the Kesari, Tilak, you know, all the Maratha

01:13:50.960 --> 01:13:56.320
[Guest]: press of Pune, they were all up in arms protesting against his treatment and actively trying

01:13:56.320 --> 01:14:01.080
[Guest]: to support Kulapur state because they said that this is not just about a local Maharaja

01:14:01.080 --> 01:14:04.420
[Guest]: and him becoming trained by British people or whatever.

01:14:04.420 --> 01:14:06.760
[Guest]: It's an issue that matters to all Indians.

01:14:06.760 --> 01:14:11.600
[Guest]: When you treat an Indian of this kind of importance, Kulapur is basically Shivaji's descent.

01:14:11.600 --> 01:14:15.300
[Guest]: When you treat him poorly, it is a cause for Indians as a whole.

01:14:15.300 --> 01:14:17.760
[Guest]: It is not a cause just about one princely state.

01:14:17.760 --> 01:14:21.400
[Guest]: And the British were therefore very aware of this and they knew that princely states

01:14:21.400 --> 01:14:24.000
[Guest]: could also be used as platforms against them.

01:14:24.000 --> 01:14:28.080
[Guest]: So just as in later times, Maharajas would give funding and support to the Congress behind

01:14:28.080 --> 01:14:32.000
[Guest]: the scenes, at one point in Baroda, I think in the mid 19th century, you have a situation

01:14:32.000 --> 01:14:36.640
[Guest]: where dacoits and raiders would go out from Baroda, rob and sort of attack British territories

01:14:36.640 --> 01:14:37.640
[Guest]: in Gujarat.

01:14:37.640 --> 01:14:40.200
[Guest]: And as the police chased them, they would come back into Baroda.

01:14:40.200 --> 01:14:42.560
[Guest]: Problem being, the British police could not follow them into Baroda.

01:14:42.560 --> 01:14:45.140
[Guest]: And the Maharaja would look the other way, pretend he had no idea.

01:14:45.140 --> 01:14:47.840
[Guest]: Every now and then, he would catch one or two of the dacoits and hand them over to the

01:14:47.840 --> 01:14:48.840
[Guest]: British.

01:14:48.840 --> 01:14:52.200
[Guest]: But he actively let that happen because he enjoyed the fact that his people were going

01:14:52.200 --> 01:14:56.760
[Guest]: out and giving the British a little bit of a bloody nose every now and then.

01:14:56.760 --> 01:15:02.320
[Guest]: In Mysore, as late, you find in 1906 or 1907, a British official complaining that these

01:15:02.320 --> 01:15:05.840
[Guest]: papers in Mysore, the royal family, if you criticize the royal family, they will take

01:15:05.840 --> 01:15:07.800
[Guest]: you to the cleaners, the Mysore government.

01:15:07.800 --> 01:15:10.640
[Guest]: But if you criticize the British government, the Mysore government will pretend nothing

01:15:10.640 --> 01:15:11.640
[Guest]: has happened.

01:15:11.640 --> 01:15:15.080
[Guest]: They were allowing their local press to criticize the British actively because there the Mahasore

01:15:15.080 --> 01:15:19.000
[Guest]: Maharaja had no interest in protecting the British or their sentiments.

01:15:19.000 --> 01:15:23.360
[Guest]: Same complaint repeats in the 1920s, which means that for a 15 year period, Mysore Maharaja

01:15:23.360 --> 01:15:27.360
[Guest]: is looking the other way, letting his press call the British whatever the names they want.

01:15:27.360 --> 01:15:30.160
[Guest]: And there's this wonderful quote where the resident says that, you know, the British

01:15:30.160 --> 01:15:34.480
[Guest]: resident says that if these papers were in British India, they would have been long ago

01:15:34.480 --> 01:15:38.620
[Guest]: sort of prosecuted into oblivion, but because they're in a princely state, the British can

01:15:38.620 --> 01:15:40.860
[Guest]: only request and cajole and add pressure.

01:15:40.860 --> 01:15:43.800
[Guest]: But unless the Maharaja issues the orders, nothing can be done.

01:15:43.800 --> 01:15:45.440
[Guest]: So these Maharajas were not passive.

01:15:45.440 --> 01:15:48.400
[Guest]: The British called them allies, which is where the title of the book is false allies.

01:15:48.400 --> 01:15:52.560
[Guest]: You know, they were not necessarily allies in a meek, submissive sense.

01:15:52.560 --> 01:15:55.700
[Guest]: They were stuck in this strange political equation.

01:15:55.700 --> 01:15:59.360
[Guest]: But the moment the British eye turned in some other direction, they would try to shift.

01:15:59.360 --> 01:16:00.680
[Guest]: So these pillars were very shaky.

01:16:00.680 --> 01:16:05.100
[Guest]: You know, one moment the weight is on them, it will pretend that it's a very stable pillar.

01:16:05.100 --> 01:16:08.520
[Guest]: The moment the British attention moves to some other topic or some other state, these

01:16:08.520 --> 01:16:13.160
[Guest]: Rajas will try to see how much room they have to maneuver and try to amend the equation

01:16:13.160 --> 01:16:14.480
[Guest]: a little bit.

01:16:14.480 --> 01:16:16.240
[Guest]: So they were not passive by any stretch.

01:16:16.240 --> 01:16:19.040
[Guest]: They were not necessarily committed to the empire.

01:16:19.040 --> 01:16:23.640
[Guest]: The very fact of them funding revolutionaries and anti-British politicians shows that they

01:16:23.640 --> 01:16:27.360
[Guest]: were not, you know, they were capable of playing a political game.

01:16:27.360 --> 01:16:29.440
[Guest]: They didn't just lie down and take it.

01:16:29.440 --> 01:16:32.520
[Guest]: They had their own ways of fighting back as well.

01:16:32.520 --> 01:16:35.400
[Amit Varma]: And some did it more overtly than others, like one of the fascinating characters in

01:16:35.400 --> 01:16:39.440
[Amit Varma]: your book is Sairaji Rao Third of Baroda, where, you know, he's anti-caste.

01:16:39.440 --> 01:16:42.040
[Amit Varma]: He starts supporting the underprivileged with schools and all that.

01:16:42.040 --> 01:16:44.360
[Amit Varma]: He funds Ambedkar's education, right?

01:16:44.360 --> 01:16:48.480
[Amit Varma]: And you know, whenever he goes abroad, he meets revolutionaries like Taraknath Das,

01:16:48.480 --> 01:16:53.280
[Amit Varma]: Madam Kama, Shyamji Krishna Verma, no relative of either mine or Raja Ravi Verma, who founded

01:16:53.280 --> 01:16:58.480
[Amit Varma]: the famous India House in London from, you know, which Savarkar was a part of and pretty

01:16:58.480 --> 01:16:59.480
[Amit Varma]: radical bunch.

01:16:59.480 --> 01:17:01.920
[Amit Varma]: And Sri Aurobindo was his aide for a while.

01:17:01.920 --> 01:17:06.200
[Amit Varma]: The other thing that sort of strikes me is that fighting the British can happen both

01:17:06.200 --> 01:17:11.400
[Amit Varma]: in overt ways and more subversive ways, which are kind of under the surface, like you pointed

01:17:11.400 --> 01:17:15.480
[Amit Varma]: out when Dadaji Narubhai was for a very brief while, the Diwan in Baroda, where so much

01:17:15.480 --> 01:17:16.480
[Amit Varma]: was happening.

01:17:16.480 --> 01:17:21.440
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you know, the Maharaja didn't like him, the resident didn't like him and allegedly

01:17:21.440 --> 01:17:24.760
[Amit Varma]: the Maharaja tried to poison the resident and later got convicted for that.

01:17:24.760 --> 01:17:28.680
[Amit Varma]: And it was full on drama, which I think I discussed in my episode with Dinyar.

01:17:28.680 --> 01:17:32.760
[Amit Varma]: But he's very clear that this is for the cause, not for the man, as you've quoted him saying.

01:17:32.760 --> 01:17:37.600
[Amit Varma]: And he's very clear that if we show that Indians can govern themselves, then the biggest raison

01:17:37.600 --> 01:17:41.080
[Amit Varma]: d'etre for the British to be here, kind of goes away, punctured.

01:17:41.080 --> 01:17:45.040
[Amit Varma]: And there are other people like Madhava Rao who are not saying that, their rhetoric isn't

01:17:45.040 --> 01:17:48.260
[Amit Varma]: that, but clearly that is what they are doing.

01:17:48.260 --> 01:17:52.240
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, it's sort of a dilemma for the British also in a sense, right?

01:17:52.240 --> 01:17:56.440
[Amit Varma]: Like one, the British need the good administration for the revenues, because they're bleeding

01:17:56.440 --> 01:17:57.440
[Amit Varma]: the country dry.

01:17:57.440 --> 01:18:02.720
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, they also want a reason to sort of keep control and all of that.

01:18:02.720 --> 01:18:06.860
[Amit Varma]: How does this sort of rhetoric evolve over the years?

01:18:06.860 --> 01:18:12.680
[Amit Varma]: Because even right down to the 1930s and 1940s, if you look at sort of Churchill's utterances

01:18:12.680 --> 01:18:17.960
[Amit Varma]: on how, you know, Indians are effectively brutes who can't govern themselves, and this

01:18:17.960 --> 01:18:22.280
[Amit Varma]: will be a country riven by caste and torn apart and the British are required.

01:18:22.280 --> 01:18:24.760
[Amit Varma]: How is that narrative kind of shifting?

01:18:24.760 --> 01:18:29.680
[Amit Varma]: And is there a realisation that, hey, this is just BS, like within the company, as it

01:18:29.680 --> 01:18:33.400
[Amit Varma]: were, within the British Empire, I mean, there are multitudes there also, right?

01:18:33.400 --> 01:18:36.280
[Amit Varma]: Not everybody is your officer in Lagaan.

01:18:36.280 --> 01:18:38.280
[Guest]: So what sense did you get of that?

01:18:38.280 --> 01:18:39.280
[Guest]: That's the thing.

01:18:39.280 --> 01:18:43.120
[Guest]: You see, there are lots of British officers who actually celebrate these native statesmen

01:18:43.120 --> 01:18:44.120
[Guest]: as well.

01:18:44.120 --> 01:18:46.440
[Guest]: They're called native statesmen because, in quotes, because that's what they were called

01:18:46.440 --> 01:18:49.080
[Guest]: in the 19th century, statesmen could only be white.

01:18:49.080 --> 01:18:51.800
[Guest]: So if you were a brown statesman, you were called a native statesman.

01:18:51.800 --> 01:18:56.180
[Guest]: It's a loaded term, but I use it in the book because it belongs to that period.

01:18:56.180 --> 01:18:59.200
[Guest]: So you know, there were some of them, for example, there's this character I discussed

01:18:59.200 --> 01:19:03.920
[Guest]: called Shesha Yashastri, you know, on the one hand, trained in an English school, very

01:19:03.920 --> 01:19:08.160
[Guest]: good at sort of, you know, rising up the British bureaucracy, hits of ceiling himself, you

01:19:08.160 --> 01:19:12.280
[Guest]: know, is treated poorly, not given the same salary, has to fight certain battles.

01:19:12.280 --> 01:19:16.280
[Guest]: And till then, he's relatively obedient, you know, he will stand up for himself, but

01:19:16.280 --> 01:19:20.200
[Guest]: he's not really talking about the wider Indian sort of cause.

01:19:20.200 --> 01:19:24.360
[Guest]: But then he becomes Diwan of Travancore, and suddenly his tone towards the British changes.

01:19:24.360 --> 01:19:29.360
[Guest]: So when they send him to Travancore to become Diwan, they think they've got a loyal man

01:19:29.360 --> 01:19:33.040
[Guest]: who knows them, and therefore will be a wonderful bridge with the Raja there.

01:19:33.040 --> 01:19:36.040
[Guest]: The Raja, of course, has his interests, which is that I don't want you to be loyal to them.

01:19:36.040 --> 01:19:38.040
[Guest]: I want you to obey everything I will say.

01:19:38.040 --> 01:19:41.760
[Guest]: Shesha Yashastri has his own agenda, which is he wants the Raja to become a constitutional

01:19:41.760 --> 01:19:45.560
[Guest]: ruler and sort of develop the politics and the structure of the state.

01:19:45.560 --> 01:19:48.000
[Guest]: But all the same, he's also a Brahmin Hindu.

01:19:48.000 --> 01:19:50.600
[Guest]: So he's just as interested in the state's temple activities.

01:19:50.600 --> 01:19:54.040
[Guest]: So the British say, you know, these temples are costing too much, there is a drain on

01:19:54.040 --> 01:19:55.040
[Guest]: the exchequer.

01:19:55.040 --> 01:19:58.480
[Guest]: He says, no, this is a princely state, there is a Maharaja, there is a state temple, there

01:19:58.480 --> 01:20:00.520
[Guest]: are so many temples to take care of.

01:20:00.520 --> 01:20:03.720
[Guest]: As it's Diwan, I am going to do this because it is also part of my duty.

01:20:03.720 --> 01:20:07.720
[Guest]: And he sort of deploys statistics to show that actually the revenue from those temple

01:20:07.720 --> 01:20:11.720
[Guest]: lands, which the government takes is far higher than what they spend on maintaining those

01:20:11.720 --> 01:20:12.720
[Guest]: temples.

01:20:12.720 --> 01:20:14.800
[Guest]: So already there's a slight turn there.

01:20:14.800 --> 01:20:19.160
[Guest]: He starts, you know, writing on various British policies, he picks a fight with the British.

01:20:19.160 --> 01:20:22.360
[Guest]: They have this rule, which is not written in any of the treaties with the Rajas, but

01:20:22.360 --> 01:20:27.120
[Guest]: the British will simply not allow a royal judge to try a white man.

01:20:27.120 --> 01:20:30.480
[Guest]: And Shesha Yashastri tries to pick a fight on this count, saying that unless Travenco

01:20:30.480 --> 01:20:35.360
[Guest]: as a state gives away that right to the British by treaty, you cannot insist that Travenco

01:20:35.360 --> 01:20:37.160
[Guest]: judges cannot try a white man.

01:20:37.160 --> 01:20:40.840
[Guest]: They have to come to a compromise where eventually, you know, there's brown as well as white judges

01:20:40.840 --> 01:20:41.920
[Guest]: on the bench.

01:20:41.920 --> 01:20:46.440
[Guest]: But in the fight itself, you show that this man, even though he was trained in the British

01:20:46.440 --> 01:20:49.640
[Guest]: bureaucracy, even though a lot of British bureaucrats loved him and they thought he

01:20:49.640 --> 01:20:54.080
[Guest]: would be a very sort of, let's say, friendly figure, even when he moved to the princely

01:20:54.080 --> 01:20:55.080
[Guest]: state.

01:20:55.080 --> 01:20:59.320
[Guest]: No, once he moved to a home territory where it was brown people in control, brown people

01:20:59.320 --> 01:21:03.720
[Guest]: in power, brown people in their element, in their own country, completely in control of

01:21:03.720 --> 01:21:06.520
[Guest]: what was happening, his tone immediately shifted.

01:21:06.520 --> 01:21:09.440
[Guest]: And that essentially suggests that it was always there within.

01:21:09.440 --> 01:21:14.280
[Guest]: It just got an opportunity to manifest itself the moment it was released from British control

01:21:14.280 --> 01:21:16.840
[Guest]: into what was called native territory.

01:21:16.840 --> 01:21:21.600
[Guest]: You mentioned Sayajirao Gaikwad of Baroda, even more fascinating story, you know, and

01:21:21.600 --> 01:21:25.960
[Guest]: this is where you realize that even in princely politics, it's not just one group sometimes.

01:21:25.960 --> 01:21:30.720
[Guest]: You have at the beginning of the story, you have a Maharaja, Khanderao Gaikwad, he doesn't

01:21:30.720 --> 01:21:31.720
[Guest]: have children.

01:21:31.720 --> 01:21:35.960
[Guest]: He's got two wives, no children, picks up a 13 year old girl when he's in his late 30s,

01:21:35.960 --> 01:21:40.440
[Guest]: approaching 40, marries her, lives with her for four years, no children.

01:21:40.440 --> 01:21:44.560
[Guest]: The moment he dies, his brother, who's been locked up already for being a slightly textbook

01:21:44.560 --> 01:21:47.780
[Guest]: dubious character, Malhar Rao, he becomes the Maharaja.

01:21:47.780 --> 01:21:51.640
[Guest]: But the widow has a strange strategy and this is something the British note in 1884, there's

01:21:51.640 --> 01:21:55.960
[Guest]: a gentleman who writes about this, says that Indian Maharanis are very shrewd because any

01:21:55.960 --> 01:21:59.720
[Guest]: time there's a disputed succession or there's a ruler who dies without an heir, they will

01:21:59.720 --> 01:22:03.520
[Guest]: instantly declare themselves pregnant, by which for nine months at least you have to

01:22:03.520 --> 01:22:04.800
[Guest]: defer the succession.

01:22:04.800 --> 01:22:09.500
[Guest]: And that opens up a window for different factions in court to realign themselves, change the

01:22:09.500 --> 01:22:14.320
[Guest]: political landscape, come to terms and try and hammer out an agreement without the British

01:22:14.320 --> 01:22:16.640
[Guest]: gaining too much control over the situation.

01:22:16.640 --> 01:22:17.800
[Guest]: In Baroda, the same happens.

01:22:17.800 --> 01:22:21.960
[Guest]: The late Maharaja's wife, who's all of 17, suddenly claims she's pregnant.

01:22:21.960 --> 01:22:25.680
[Guest]: The brother who's been released hates it because he's like, you know, how can you suddenly

01:22:25.680 --> 01:22:26.680
[Guest]: come into this?

01:22:26.680 --> 01:22:29.180
[Guest]: I thought this was my party and you're now trying to snatch it from me.

01:22:29.180 --> 01:22:32.480
[Guest]: She unfortunately gives birth to a girl and it's fascinating because she moves to the

01:22:32.480 --> 01:22:35.920
[Guest]: British residency to give birth because the brother-in-law is trying to poison her.

01:22:35.920 --> 01:22:39.620
[Guest]: So she's also countering that by living under the British agent's nose.

01:22:39.620 --> 01:22:41.560
[Guest]: She forms an alliance with the British.

01:22:41.560 --> 01:22:43.360
[Guest]: So there are different interests at play.

01:22:43.360 --> 01:22:45.360
[Guest]: She and the British both dislike the brother.

01:22:45.360 --> 01:22:48.320
[Guest]: So in that context, she allies with the British, gets rid of the brother.

01:22:48.320 --> 01:22:49.920
[Guest]: I mean, he rules for five years.

01:22:49.920 --> 01:22:51.480
[Guest]: This is when Dadabhai Naoroji comes in.

01:22:51.480 --> 01:22:53.840
[Guest]: He proves to be a bad character.

01:22:53.840 --> 01:22:57.680
[Guest]: The whole story of him attempting to poison the resident is slightly questionable because

01:22:57.680 --> 01:22:59.840
[Guest]: he was never actually convicted of that.

01:22:59.840 --> 01:23:02.240
[Guest]: The jury was split as far as that was concerned.

01:23:02.240 --> 01:23:04.560
[Guest]: But the British have decided we're not going to let him rule anymore.

01:23:04.560 --> 01:23:06.440
[Guest]: So after five years, they get rid of him.

01:23:06.440 --> 01:23:07.680
[Guest]: Now the Maharani comes back.

01:23:07.680 --> 01:23:11.940
[Guest]: She, by the way, during these five years, the complaints that the British use as an

01:23:11.940 --> 01:23:16.720
[Guest]: excuse against Malhar Rao to depose him, many of those complaints were sponsored by her.

01:23:16.720 --> 01:23:20.800
[Guest]: She would sit in Pune where she had lots of her own money given to her by her late husband.

01:23:20.800 --> 01:23:24.640
[Guest]: She would use that money to fund complaints against her brother-in-law in Baroda.

01:23:24.640 --> 01:23:28.200
[Guest]: She would use that money to bribe the British resident's own officials.

01:23:28.200 --> 01:23:33.320
[Guest]: So even when you say there was a British resident in a state, he was also susceptible to lots

01:23:33.320 --> 01:23:34.400
[Guest]: of influences.

01:23:34.400 --> 01:23:37.840
[Guest]: That person could also be manipulated in a way where the British resident didn't even

01:23:37.840 --> 01:23:39.940
[Guest]: realize he was being manipulated.

01:23:39.940 --> 01:23:43.720
[Guest]: In her case, this Maharani Jamnabai was just paying his servants and assistants to keep

01:23:43.720 --> 01:23:45.960
[Guest]: fanning his animosity with the Maharaja.

01:23:45.960 --> 01:23:50.160
[Guest]: On the other hand, she's getting other people to complain to the resident about the Maharaja.

01:23:50.160 --> 01:23:53.600
[Guest]: Altogether she's putting so much pressure on the Maharaja that he ends up blundering

01:23:53.600 --> 01:23:55.240
[Guest]: and is eventually kicked off.

01:23:55.240 --> 01:23:59.040
[Guest]: Now she and the British ally, they come together and they decide we need to choose a new king

01:23:59.040 --> 01:24:00.040
[Guest]: for the throne.

01:24:00.040 --> 01:24:02.560
[Guest]: Both have, again, a common interest.

01:24:02.560 --> 01:24:07.060
[Guest]: The British want, what they say in one quote, a malleable boy whom they can shape and sort

01:24:07.060 --> 01:24:09.420
[Guest]: of make sure he's loyal as he grows up.

01:24:09.420 --> 01:24:13.240
[Guest]: She too wants a young boy because then she can retain her control over the boy and essentially

01:24:13.240 --> 01:24:15.760
[Guest]: be the person, the power behind the throne.

01:24:15.760 --> 01:24:19.660
[Guest]: So there's an older man in his 20s, they exile him, saying that no, no, your claims don't

01:24:19.660 --> 01:24:23.800
[Guest]: stand up, we're going to bring in a distant relative, a boy of 12, which is the future

01:24:23.800 --> 01:24:27.880
[Guest]: Sayajirao Gaikwad, and my god, this poor chap, Madhavrao also enters the scene.

01:24:27.880 --> 01:24:32.120
[Guest]: On the one hand, he's got the British resident on him, he's got a white tutor on him, he's

01:24:32.120 --> 01:24:36.040
[Guest]: got this wonderful administrator Madhavrao on him, and he's got the Maharani.

01:24:36.040 --> 01:24:40.800
[Guest]: All of them have their own incentives to tutor him and tailor him in a way that fits their

01:24:40.800 --> 01:24:41.800
[Guest]: respective purposes.

01:24:41.800 --> 01:24:46.120
[Guest]: Madhavrao wants a constitutional ruler, the British want a loyal ruler, Maharani wants

01:24:46.120 --> 01:24:50.100
[Guest]: a puppet, a rubber stamp, each of them is putting pressure on him.

01:24:50.100 --> 01:24:54.440
[Guest]: When he eventually comes to power in the year 1881, he very quickly shows that none of this

01:24:54.440 --> 01:24:55.440
[Guest]: has worked.

01:24:55.440 --> 01:24:57.240
[Guest]: He is essentially his own man.

01:24:57.240 --> 01:25:01.720
[Guest]: The British, for example, try to impose conditions on him, saying that because the previous Maharaja

01:25:01.720 --> 01:25:05.840
[Guest]: was such a bad egg, you're going to have some limitations on your power.

01:25:05.840 --> 01:25:09.960
[Guest]: Sayajirao says, fine, you're my overlords, I will accept the limitations, but with a

01:25:09.960 --> 01:25:10.960
[Guest]: time limit.

01:25:10.960 --> 01:25:13.360
[Guest]: They say, no, no, no, you can get rid of them whenever you want.

01:25:13.360 --> 01:25:17.840
[Guest]: He says, no, no, no, I want a clear time limit, two years at most, not beyond that.

01:25:17.840 --> 01:25:21.600
[Guest]: A wise decision because they do this in another princely state in Bikaner and the poor chayap

01:25:21.600 --> 01:25:24.440
[Guest]: was saddled for nearly a decade with these restrictions on his power.

01:25:24.440 --> 01:25:28.280
[Guest]: So Sayajirao managed to show that he would not take things lying down.

01:25:28.280 --> 01:25:30.680
[Guest]: Two years into, he picks a fight with the Maharani.

01:25:30.680 --> 01:25:33.840
[Guest]: The Maharani starts demanding large sums of money.

01:25:33.840 --> 01:25:35.000
[Guest]: He's not obeying her orders.

01:25:35.000 --> 01:25:38.560
[Guest]: He's not treating her as if she's the queen of the state or the ruler of the state.

01:25:38.560 --> 01:25:41.640
[Guest]: She actually writes to the British and this is a quote from her letter where she says,

01:25:41.640 --> 01:25:44.200
[Guest]: he has not till now been listening to you and your orders.

01:25:44.200 --> 01:25:46.540
[Guest]: We must put an end to his self-sufficiency.

01:25:46.540 --> 01:25:49.720
[Guest]: So she's trying to come back and ally with the British to get rid of this one, or at

01:25:49.720 --> 01:25:51.560
[Guest]: least tame him.

01:25:51.560 --> 01:25:54.200
[Guest]: This time, for some reason, the British don't support her.

01:25:54.200 --> 01:25:58.400
[Guest]: One of the reasons may be that this was a time when Lord Ripon, a very popular pro-Indian

01:25:58.400 --> 01:26:03.360
[Guest]: Viceroy was in power, which also tells you about how much individual British officials

01:26:03.360 --> 01:26:05.360
[Guest]: and officers could make a difference.

01:26:05.360 --> 01:26:06.880
[Guest]: And she's told, no, no, mind your business.

01:26:06.880 --> 01:26:08.240
[Guest]: He's going to rule.

01:26:08.240 --> 01:26:11.360
[Guest]: And he then becomes this slowly more and more confident.

01:26:11.360 --> 01:26:15.400
[Guest]: He's meeting the politicians of Pune, which is Ranade, Gokhale, Tilak.

01:26:15.400 --> 01:26:17.880
[Guest]: These are the people he's hanging out with, Jyoti Bafule.

01:26:17.880 --> 01:26:19.720
[Guest]: So he's picking up things from them.

01:26:19.720 --> 01:26:20.880
[Guest]: He's starting to go abroad.

01:26:20.880 --> 01:26:25.040
[Guest]: He's picking up ideas and, you know, forming a vision for his state abroad.

01:26:25.040 --> 01:26:28.280
[Guest]: And one thing he realizes very quickly is that the British, when they say an Indian

01:26:28.280 --> 01:26:33.460
[Guest]: state should modernize, they essentially want a bad copy of the British model.

01:26:33.460 --> 01:26:35.000
[Guest]: They don't want an innovative new copy.

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:38.760
[Guest]: They don't want a system or a version that is rooted in Indian ideas.

01:26:38.760 --> 01:26:41.080
[Guest]: They don't want a system that is better than the British.

01:26:41.080 --> 01:26:45.000
[Guest]: They want a bad copy that will allow them to say, oh, we're letting the state modernize.

01:26:45.000 --> 01:26:48.160
[Guest]: But look, it's not good enough, so we still have to control the state.

01:26:48.160 --> 01:26:50.520
[Guest]: They want to have their cake and eat it also.

01:26:50.520 --> 01:26:52.380
[Guest]: And he realizes this very quickly.

01:26:52.380 --> 01:26:56.080
[Guest]: On the one hand, he's got to deal with this imperial sort of pressure.

01:26:56.080 --> 01:26:59.640
[Guest]: But as I said earlier, Baroda also has a situation where you have a Maratha royal family over

01:26:59.640 --> 01:27:00.640
[Guest]: Gujaratis.

01:27:00.640 --> 01:27:01.640
[Guest]: So there's also that politics.

01:27:01.640 --> 01:27:05.400
[Guest]: So you have Gujarati, for example, his Gujarati minister, he appoints a Gujarati minister

01:27:05.400 --> 01:27:07.560
[Guest]: for the first time in the state's history.

01:27:07.560 --> 01:27:11.140
[Guest]: The minister ties up with the British resident and tries to cut the Maharaja out.

01:27:11.140 --> 01:27:14.720
[Guest]: So then he has to get rid of the Gujarati minister and slowly let Gujaratis in at lower

01:27:14.720 --> 01:27:17.800
[Guest]: levels so his own position can't be challenged.

01:27:17.800 --> 01:27:22.120
[Guest]: And then by the end of the 19th century, you start seeing him flirting much more seriously

01:27:22.120 --> 01:27:27.320
[Guest]: with the Congress party, with Congress politicians, funding Naoroji's election, funding other

01:27:27.320 --> 01:27:32.060
[Guest]: activities of the Congress, giving speeches that very quickly the British start getting

01:27:32.060 --> 01:27:36.100
[Guest]: very uncomfortable about and they think that this is bordering sedition, the kind of things

01:27:36.100 --> 01:27:37.360
[Guest]: that he says.

01:27:37.360 --> 01:27:40.960
[Guest]: Every speech he will talk about national ideas, he'll use the word national, he'll say we

01:27:40.960 --> 01:27:45.280
[Guest]: must have a national culture, a national art, a national government in future.

01:27:45.280 --> 01:27:49.960
[Guest]: He's saying things that Maharajas are usually allowed to feel but never allowed to say.

01:27:49.960 --> 01:27:52.560
[Guest]: But he's boldly going out and saying these things.

01:27:52.560 --> 01:27:55.540
[Guest]: Trying to stop him doesn't work because he's a major Maharaja.

01:27:55.540 --> 01:27:59.480
[Guest]: He's delivering good things to his government, his finances are wonderful, there's no debt

01:27:59.480 --> 01:28:03.520
[Guest]: in the state, the government's run efficiently, schools are being built, roads are being built.

01:28:03.520 --> 01:28:07.840
[Guest]: So you really can't find a corner into which you can force him and make him obey you.

01:28:07.840 --> 01:28:12.880
[Guest]: Of course, the straw that finally breaks the camel's back is a good 30 years into his reign,

01:28:12.880 --> 01:28:13.880
[Guest]: around 1910.

01:28:13.880 --> 01:28:17.960
[Guest]: This is when, in the pan-Indian context, bombs are being thrown, revolutionary activities

01:28:17.960 --> 01:28:19.500
[Guest]: are picking up in India.

01:28:19.500 --> 01:28:23.760
[Guest]: And there's this time where he's asked to give a speech and he says that, oh yeah, I

01:28:23.760 --> 01:28:25.800
[Guest]: don't agree with revolutionary methods.

01:28:25.800 --> 01:28:30.400
[Guest]: But he also adds that, you know, the core issue must be addressed, which is what?

01:28:30.400 --> 01:28:31.560
[Guest]: British rule, foreign rule.

01:28:31.560 --> 01:28:33.800
[Guest]: So he's not completely giving the British what they want.

01:28:33.800 --> 01:28:38.760
[Guest]: They try to get him to get his speeches pre-approved and he says, absolutely not.

01:28:38.760 --> 01:28:44.560
[Guest]: The future king of England, as air apparent, visits India and he's passing through Baroda

01:28:44.560 --> 01:28:47.720
[Guest]: and Maharaja says, no, no, I'm too busy, I have to go to Europe myself, so I'm not staying

01:28:47.720 --> 01:28:49.160
[Guest]: around to receive this prince.

01:28:49.160 --> 01:28:53.240
[Guest]: He can come, my government will take care of him, which the British don't like.

01:28:53.240 --> 01:28:57.040
[Guest]: Finally there's this Viceroy around 1909 or 1910, who's coming to Baroda.

01:28:57.040 --> 01:29:00.520
[Guest]: On the way, a bomb is flung at the Viceroy, the Viceroy survives.

01:29:00.520 --> 01:29:03.880
[Guest]: He comes to Baroda and he hears graffiti on the wall saying that, you may bring all your

01:29:03.880 --> 01:29:06.440
[Guest]: troops and armies here, we will not cease to resist.

01:29:06.440 --> 01:29:08.880
[Guest]: This is in a princely state in the Maharaja's capital.

01:29:08.880 --> 01:29:11.240
[Guest]: This is written while the Viceroy is present.

01:29:11.240 --> 01:29:14.680
[Guest]: And it's very difficult for the British to believe that these things could happen without

01:29:14.680 --> 01:29:19.800
[Guest]: the Maharaja, if not actively supporting it, definitely looking the other way.

01:29:19.800 --> 01:29:25.600
[Guest]: They have this time where they find that of about 167 seditious, revolutionary propaganda

01:29:25.600 --> 01:29:29.760
[Guest]: books that are published in India and which are banned by the British government, 17 have

01:29:29.760 --> 01:29:31.160
[Guest]: emerged from Baroda.

01:29:31.160 --> 01:29:34.640
[Guest]: And the Maharaja claims, oh, I have no idea, which the British simply don't believe.

01:29:34.640 --> 01:29:39.200
[Guest]: At one time, Bombay police raid Baroda, get to two presses and identify these books.

01:29:39.200 --> 01:29:43.040
[Guest]: They find a book called Vegetable Medicines, which is actually about bomb making.

01:29:43.040 --> 01:29:46.840
[Guest]: And they hold the Maharaja's government to account, but the Maharaja's officials turn

01:29:46.840 --> 01:29:50.960
[Guest]: around and say, okay, hold on, before we go into this whole revolutionary thing, on whose

01:29:50.960 --> 01:29:52.640
[Guest]: authority have you entered Baroda state?

01:29:52.640 --> 01:29:54.720
[Guest]: Who gave you the permission to raid our state?

01:29:54.720 --> 01:29:56.560
[Guest]: So your very action is not acceptable.

01:29:56.560 --> 01:29:58.360
[Guest]: So first you go back to Bombay.

01:29:58.360 --> 01:30:01.680
[Guest]: You had no authority entering and the British are very upset, saying, how can you talk jurisdiction

01:30:01.680 --> 01:30:04.040
[Guest]: when we found revolutionary material here?

01:30:04.040 --> 01:30:08.240
[Guest]: They say, Maharaja, you must sack these people, appoint a white man as head of your police,

01:30:08.240 --> 01:30:10.400
[Guest]: appoint white officials into your government.

01:30:10.400 --> 01:30:12.320
[Guest]: Maharaja doesn't sack them, he demotes them.

01:30:12.320 --> 01:30:15.960
[Guest]: One of them gets angry and he's not happy being demoted, so he resigns.

01:30:15.960 --> 01:30:18.400
[Guest]: Maharaja gives him 10,000 rupees as a gift.

01:30:18.400 --> 01:30:22.880
[Guest]: All of these are clear signals to the British, basically telling them to F off, saying that

01:30:22.880 --> 01:30:27.640
[Guest]: this is my state, you may be everything else outside, but in my state, I am sovereign and

01:30:27.640 --> 01:30:29.760
[Guest]: I will not take things lying down.

01:30:29.760 --> 01:30:34.080
[Guest]: Of course, then there's that famous episode of the 1911 Delhi Darbar, where Sairaj Rao

01:30:34.080 --> 01:30:39.320
[Guest]: goes to meet the British king, where by accident, it is construed that he insulted the king

01:30:39.320 --> 01:30:42.840
[Guest]: by turning his back and not properly bowing to the king.

01:30:42.840 --> 01:30:48.120
[Guest]: Some say the greater sin that he committed was that he came there in regular business

01:30:48.120 --> 01:30:52.360
[Guest]: attire, which is a usual white hachkan with just a string of pearls, none of his British

01:30:52.360 --> 01:30:55.560
[Guest]: titles and robes and medals and all of that.

01:30:55.560 --> 01:30:58.360
[Guest]: And they were very upset because when Maharajas came out in Darbar, they were supposed to

01:30:58.360 --> 01:31:02.560
[Guest]: look like bejeweled ostriches and peacocks, they were not supposed to look like ordinary

01:31:02.560 --> 01:31:05.880
[Guest]: people who could do business, they were supposed to look exotic.

01:31:05.880 --> 01:31:07.600
[Guest]: And he refused to play that game.

01:31:07.600 --> 01:31:12.760
[Guest]: So then they say, oh, he's not loyal, he must be toppled, either he must abdicate or he

01:31:12.760 --> 01:31:14.120
[Guest]: must be deposed.

01:31:14.120 --> 01:31:18.240
[Guest]: That pressure finally gets to him and he realises, okay, hold on, I've pushed the British to

01:31:18.240 --> 01:31:21.240
[Guest]: the brink so far, but getting deposed is not worth it.

01:31:21.240 --> 01:31:24.760
[Guest]: Because if you get deposed, who's going to be put on the throne, they're going to be

01:31:24.760 --> 01:31:27.000
[Guest]: beholden to the British for their power.

01:31:27.000 --> 01:31:29.560
[Guest]: So they're going to be easy for the British to manipulate.

01:31:29.560 --> 01:31:32.000
[Guest]: So he sort of pulls back a little bit.

01:31:32.000 --> 01:31:36.420
[Guest]: After that, all his statements which are anti-British are channelled through somebody else.

01:31:36.420 --> 01:31:38.760
[Guest]: Usually his Diwan, some official, somebody else.

01:31:38.760 --> 01:31:43.080
[Guest]: He will not directly pick a fight, but he will find other ways to get that message put

01:31:43.080 --> 01:31:44.080
[Guest]: out.

01:31:44.080 --> 01:31:45.560
[Guest]: And then he dies in 1939.

01:31:45.560 --> 01:31:48.220
[Guest]: And you know, it's a long reign, a very exciting reign.

01:31:48.220 --> 01:31:52.240
[Guest]: He was such an interesting man that at one point, his own Diwan was able to propose a

01:31:52.240 --> 01:31:55.760
[Guest]: constitutional form of monarchy to him, saying with full representative government, give

01:31:55.760 --> 01:31:59.640
[Guest]: Baroda a constitution and you will then become just a titular monarch.

01:31:59.640 --> 01:32:01.240
[Guest]: Sayajirao did not buy it.

01:32:01.240 --> 01:32:03.040
[Guest]: He said, no, that's too ambitious.

01:32:03.040 --> 01:32:06.720
[Guest]: But the very fact that that proposal could even be made to him is suggestive that he

01:32:06.720 --> 01:32:11.620
[Guest]: was a man willing to consider a different kind of future, even within the princely states.

01:32:11.620 --> 01:32:14.760
[Guest]: And there's this diary of the Aga Khan, where the Aga Khan recounts a conversation with

01:32:14.760 --> 01:32:18.880
[Guest]: Sayajirao, who says that if there's ever an Indian nation, all these princely states will

01:32:18.880 --> 01:32:19.880
[Guest]: have to go.

01:32:19.880 --> 01:32:22.220
[Guest]: And if you have to become a nation, they will have to go.

01:32:22.220 --> 01:32:26.960
[Guest]: So even though he's a prince, even though he's part of that universe, he's aware that

01:32:26.960 --> 01:32:31.600
[Guest]: there may be sacrifices coming up for a better future, for a different kind of future.

01:32:31.600 --> 01:32:32.920
[Guest]: And he's willing to acknowledge that.

01:32:32.920 --> 01:32:38.600
[Guest]: So overall, in this book, he's one of my favorite characters because such a textured, layered

01:32:38.600 --> 01:32:41.880
[Guest]: person, he was not much of an original thinker himself.

01:32:41.880 --> 01:32:45.800
[Guest]: But he had this knack for surrounding himself with talent, whether it came from the Congress,

01:32:45.800 --> 01:32:47.480
[Guest]: whether it came from British services.

01:32:47.480 --> 01:32:51.040
[Guest]: The British, for example, were very upset at one time that he was being guided by an

01:32:51.040 --> 01:32:53.400
[Guest]: Englishman called Elliot, who was his tutor.

01:32:53.400 --> 01:32:57.400
[Guest]: Now, the British liked white men governing and helping brown people, but they had to

01:32:57.400 --> 01:32:58.400
[Guest]: be officials.

01:32:58.400 --> 01:32:59.940
[Guest]: They had to be part of that official system.

01:32:59.940 --> 01:33:01.720
[Guest]: You couldn't get a white friend to come and do it.

01:33:01.720 --> 01:33:05.280
[Guest]: That was just as taboo as having brown people run their own affairs.

01:33:05.280 --> 01:33:10.560
[Guest]: So this man was fascinating and interesting in a remarkable degree, ruled over Baroda

01:33:10.560 --> 01:33:11.820
[Guest]: for a long time.

01:33:11.820 --> 01:33:16.200
[Guest]: And because he was so successful at government, it took the British a long time to find an

01:33:16.200 --> 01:33:19.880
[Guest]: excuse by which they could finally say that, look, we will depose you.

01:33:19.880 --> 01:33:24.320
[Guest]: Otherwise, for decades, he was able to get away with saying the most pointed things and

01:33:24.320 --> 01:33:29.520
[Guest]: criticizing them in the sharpest ways and boldly doing things such as supporting revolutionaries,

01:33:29.520 --> 01:33:33.080
[Guest]: which people would not dare to do if they were really afraid in those days.

01:33:33.080 --> 01:33:35.100
[Guest]: He could do it because he knew he was secure.

01:33:35.100 --> 01:33:38.760
[Guest]: But they finally found that one chink in his armor and managed to sort of get him to sober

01:33:38.760 --> 01:33:39.760
[Guest]: down a little bit.

01:33:39.760 --> 01:33:44.760
[Guest]: But yeah, overall, I think he was perhaps the, of all these princes of that generation,

01:33:44.760 --> 01:33:46.560
[Guest]: he was the boldest and the sharpest.

01:33:46.560 --> 01:33:52.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and for all those who think of the Indian princes as capricious or eccentric or whatever,

01:33:52.480 --> 01:33:56.560
[Amit Varma]: you know that King George, the fifth incident of the 1911 Darbar, is worth pointing out

01:33:56.560 --> 01:33:57.560
[Amit Varma]: what happened here.

01:33:57.560 --> 01:34:02.120
[Amit Varma]: The protocol was that each prince one at a time had to go up to the king, bow in a particular

01:34:02.120 --> 01:34:05.520
[Amit Varma]: way, then take seven step backwards and then move off.

01:34:05.520 --> 01:34:09.880
[Amit Varma]: And he apparently, without taking all seven step backwards, turned his back and that offended

01:34:09.880 --> 01:34:10.880
[Amit Varma]: them.

01:34:10.880 --> 01:34:16.400
[Amit Varma]: So that is not an Indian prince getting offended by the stupid ritual, it's a British king.

01:34:16.400 --> 01:34:21.760
[Guest]: But what's also interesting is, there's actually video footage of this, of that 1911 Darbar,

01:34:21.760 --> 01:34:23.760
[Guest]: and Sayajirao wasn't the only one to do it.

01:34:23.760 --> 01:34:27.880
[Guest]: Baroda, sorry, Mysore and a number of other Maharajas did the same thing, but only Baroda

01:34:27.880 --> 01:34:31.800
[Guest]: was targeted because the British had already decided that he was a bad egg and they wanted

01:34:31.800 --> 01:34:32.880
[Guest]: to put him in his place.

01:34:32.880 --> 01:34:37.120
[Guest]: The video footage shows clearly that nothing Sayajirao did was not done by others.

01:34:37.120 --> 01:34:41.080
[Guest]: The other senior princes also acted in similar ways, but they were not targeted because they

01:34:41.080 --> 01:34:44.440
[Guest]: didn't have that sort of, you know, the mark on their forehead already.

01:34:44.440 --> 01:34:47.960
[Guest]: The British had already decided that this one is somebody we need to put in place.

01:34:47.960 --> 01:34:52.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's like how the Americans got Al Capone for tax evasion, they couldn't get him for

01:34:52.080 --> 01:34:53.080
[Guest]: anything else.

01:34:53.080 --> 01:34:54.080
[Amit Varma]: So it's kind of like that.

01:34:54.080 --> 01:34:57.900
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, just reading that chapter of your book, it just feels like it would be such

01:34:57.900 --> 01:35:02.280
[Amit Varma]: a great web series and not just for Sayajirao, like even before him, like the craziness of

01:35:02.280 --> 01:35:06.720
[Amit Varma]: Malhar Rao Gaikwad, like, I don't want to give too many spoilers, but this is really

01:35:06.720 --> 01:35:12.080
[Amit Varma]: fascinating because Malhar Rao Gaikwad's brother Khanderao is on the throne, Malhar Rao is

01:35:12.080 --> 01:35:16.040
[Amit Varma]: locked up for trying to poison his brother, then his brother dies, so he automatically

01:35:16.040 --> 01:35:17.040
[Amit Varma]: becomes a king.

01:35:17.040 --> 01:35:21.040
[Amit Varma]: Now the minister who got him locked up, he sends him to jail, and that fellow dies.

01:35:21.040 --> 01:35:25.160
[Amit Varma]: And meanwhile, the things Malhar Rao does is things like just abduct women and take

01:35:25.160 --> 01:35:26.160
[Amit Varma]: them into the palace.

01:35:26.160 --> 01:35:32.100
[Amit Varma]: Like you use the phrases taken like pigeons and filthy violations being committed on them.

01:35:32.100 --> 01:35:34.280
[Amit Varma]: So it's all incredibly colourful.

01:35:34.280 --> 01:35:37.860
[Amit Varma]: But eventually, he also falls to this kind of Al Capone tax evasion thing where he has

01:35:37.860 --> 01:35:42.160
[Amit Varma]: actually poisoned people and killed people, but he's framed for something he probably

01:35:42.160 --> 01:35:43.160
[Guest]: didn't do.

01:35:43.160 --> 01:35:46.560
[Guest]: Yeah, which is quite, I mean, it's ironic that that's how it finally, they snatched

01:35:46.560 --> 01:35:47.560
[Guest]: the throne from him.

01:35:47.560 --> 01:35:48.560
[Amit Varma]: But yeah.

01:35:48.560 --> 01:35:52.920
[Amit Varma]: And in the middle of all this, Dadabahu Naoroji landed up for a couple of years and he's like,

01:35:52.920 --> 01:35:53.920
[Amit Varma]: what is this?

01:35:53.920 --> 01:35:54.920
[Amit Varma]: Where am I?

