01:37:22.440 --> 01:37:26.600
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Manu Pillay about his wonderful book, False Allies.

01:37:26.600 --> 01:37:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And let's start talking about the book now.

01:37:29.000 --> 01:37:35.240
[Amit Varma]: And you start with this very interesting portrait of Prince Aswathi Tirunal by Raja Ravi Verma.

01:37:35.240 --> 01:37:38.480
[Amit Varma]: And it is this kid, he was a teenager, he was 16 at the time.

01:37:38.480 --> 01:37:41.880
[Amit Varma]: And he's sitting on this tricycle with these really giant wheels.

01:37:41.880 --> 01:37:44.560
[Amit Varma]: But he's wearing European clothes.

01:37:44.560 --> 01:37:46.400
[Amit Varma]: And he's got this stern expression on his face.

01:37:46.400 --> 01:37:49.760
[Amit Varma]: And none of the kutru monstret you'll expect from royalty.

01:37:49.760 --> 01:37:54.280
[Amit Varma]: And there is sort of this sense that not just him, I think you talk about it as something

01:37:54.280 --> 01:37:58.400
[Amit Varma]: representative of what a lot of royals were doing at the time wanting to be seen as more

01:37:58.400 --> 01:38:04.880
[Amit Varma]: European and less of the sort of the oriental Indian sort of debauched Maharajas dressed

01:38:04.880 --> 01:38:06.640
[Amit Varma]: like peacocks and all of that.

01:38:06.640 --> 01:38:12.280
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about how that process was taking place, a point at which you kind

01:38:12.280 --> 01:38:17.560
[Amit Varma]: of aspire to being like the British like I remember I did an episode recently with Peggy

01:38:17.560 --> 01:38:20.180
[Amit Varma]: Mohan on the evolution of languages.

01:38:20.180 --> 01:38:27.360
[Amit Varma]: And there at one point, she talks about how, you know, some of Ghalib's poetry, for example,

01:38:27.360 --> 01:38:32.300
[Amit Varma]: is not at all intelligible to many people because it's so much more Persianized than

01:38:32.300 --> 01:38:35.840
[Amit Varma]: poets of an earlier age or than he was in his regular everyday writing.

01:38:35.840 --> 01:38:37.160
[Amit Varma]: And there is a reason for that.

01:38:37.160 --> 01:38:42.280
[Amit Varma]: And because he doesn't want it to come so much to the attention of the emperor and so

01:38:42.280 --> 01:38:43.280
[Amit Varma]: on.

01:38:43.280 --> 01:38:46.960
[Amit Varma]: So like language indicates which way the politics of the day is going.

01:38:46.960 --> 01:38:51.320
[Amit Varma]: And there is something happening in the 19th century, which, you know, I think persists

01:38:51.320 --> 01:38:56.280
[Amit Varma]: with us to this day, that this desire to learn English and to be like the English and all

01:38:56.280 --> 01:39:00.960
[Amit Varma]: of that, which, of course, has had a terrible deleterious effect on the way that we use

01:39:00.960 --> 01:39:04.920
[Amit Varma]: the English language with all its pomposities and so on, which even the British have thrown

01:39:04.920 --> 01:39:05.920
[Amit Varma]: away.

01:39:05.920 --> 01:39:09.920
[Amit Varma]: But tell me a little bit about what's going on inside royal heads at this time, that on

01:39:09.920 --> 01:39:12.900
[Amit Varma]: one hand, they must be resenting their rulers.

01:39:12.900 --> 01:39:15.200
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, they're trying to be more like them.

01:39:15.200 --> 01:39:16.200
[Guest]: So what's happening?

01:39:16.200 --> 01:39:20.160
[Guest]: There's this quote from, I think, a time, Lord Macaulay, I think, who visited one of

01:39:20.160 --> 01:39:25.040
[Guest]: the Maharajas of Mysore in the early part of the 19th century, somewhere in the 1830s.

01:39:25.040 --> 01:39:29.360
[Guest]: And he says, oh, you know, his house is like that of a vulgar cockney cheese monger.

01:39:29.360 --> 01:39:33.160
[Guest]: You know, it's got strange European paintings, random furniture from Europe.

01:39:33.160 --> 01:39:35.160
[Guest]: It's just filled with all kinds of things.

01:39:35.160 --> 01:39:39.000
[Guest]: And then in the 1850s, with the Travancore Maharaja called Uttaram Dhirnal also, you

01:39:39.000 --> 01:39:42.800
[Guest]: have a similar comment where a British official comes and sees his house is full of mirrors,

01:39:42.800 --> 01:39:46.720
[Guest]: these objects he's collected from Europe, completely random, no order, nothing.

01:39:46.720 --> 01:39:50.160
[Guest]: In another Maharaja's place, they see these, I think, these gas lamps, they used to put

01:39:50.160 --> 01:39:54.160
[Guest]: a street lamps or hang on carriages sitting inside his main audience hall as though it

01:39:54.160 --> 01:39:58.040
[Guest]: was some grand thing, whereas in England, it was used on carriages.

01:39:58.040 --> 01:40:02.560
[Guest]: Now, it would appear that these were comical things and these Rajas were just these idiots

01:40:02.560 --> 01:40:06.240
[Guest]: who saw these beautiful trinkets from abroad and their eyes just went wide and they said,

01:40:06.240 --> 01:40:07.520
[Guest]: oh, we must have it.

01:40:07.520 --> 01:40:12.840
[Guest]: But no, the thing is, for the Rajas also, as far as their subjects were concerned, having

01:40:12.840 --> 01:40:17.200
[Guest]: these strange and interesting possessions was a way of reflecting their international

01:40:17.200 --> 01:40:18.200
[Guest]: reach.

01:40:18.200 --> 01:40:21.080
[Guest]: Saying, look, I've got all these wonderful things, these mirrors and clocks and, you

01:40:21.080 --> 01:40:23.920
[Guest]: know, clocks were such a remarkable thing at that time.

01:40:23.920 --> 01:40:27.760
[Guest]: So I've got 20 clocks because, you know, I've got so much international reach.

01:40:27.760 --> 01:40:33.000
[Guest]: There's the story of a Raja who thinks he's, I think it's called bonbons or something.

01:40:33.000 --> 01:40:36.680
[Guest]: He thought he was importing a bunch of things he could eat.

01:40:36.680 --> 01:40:40.760
[Guest]: It turned out to be these idhas, you know, wigs that people used to wear in those days,

01:40:40.760 --> 01:40:44.560
[Guest]: those powdered wigs, or like this frame that women wore under their gowns.

01:40:44.560 --> 01:40:47.880
[Guest]: And he was just taken aback that this is what he had accidentally ordered.

01:40:47.880 --> 01:40:52.360
[Guest]: But the Rajas were essentially trying to communicate to their audience that, look, I have international

01:40:52.360 --> 01:40:53.360
[Guest]: reach.

01:40:53.360 --> 01:40:56.200
[Guest]: The British may look down on it, but the Rajas had their own purpose.

01:40:56.200 --> 01:40:59.520
[Guest]: That painting you refer to, it sits in a private house in Trivandrum.

01:40:59.520 --> 01:41:01.360
[Guest]: It's this very strange Ravi Orma painting.

01:41:01.360 --> 01:41:05.040
[Guest]: That tricycle is, it's one of those giant, it's a royal salvo, Queen Victoria had one

01:41:05.040 --> 01:41:06.040
[Guest]: as well.

01:41:06.040 --> 01:41:10.640
[Guest]: This was the rage in the 1870s and 80s, where, you know, bicycles were no longer fashionable.

01:41:10.640 --> 01:41:13.720
[Guest]: This is what you had to be on for a few years.

01:41:13.720 --> 01:41:18.560
[Guest]: And this guy, by posing on it at the age of 16, he's, frankly, he's passed his matriculation

01:41:18.560 --> 01:41:19.560
[Guest]: exam.

01:41:19.560 --> 01:41:21.560
[Guest]: Now, princes usually didn't go to college.

01:41:21.560 --> 01:41:23.480
[Guest]: He would end up getting a BA degree as well.

01:41:23.480 --> 01:41:26.720
[Guest]: And he was actually called the BA prince because he was the first prince in India to get a

01:41:26.720 --> 01:41:28.000
[Guest]: college degree.

01:41:28.000 --> 01:41:32.760
[Guest]: Now, in not wearing those Indian clothes, in not wearing those embroidered Persianate

01:41:32.760 --> 01:41:37.240
[Guest]: robes that the Travancore Maharajas used to wear earlier, he's not just trying to, he's

01:41:37.240 --> 01:41:41.160
[Guest]: not deracinated, he's not trying to anglicize himself in the sense that he's ashamed of

01:41:41.160 --> 01:41:42.160
[Guest]: what is at home.

01:41:42.160 --> 01:41:45.560
[Guest]: The Travancore Maharajas still fed 15,000 Brahmins on state events.

01:41:45.560 --> 01:41:49.800
[Guest]: They still had those great ceremonies where they would take a dip in water and come out

01:41:49.800 --> 01:41:54.440
[Guest]: out of this Padma Garbha with all kinds of, you know, new status ascribed to themselves.

01:41:54.440 --> 01:41:57.440
[Guest]: They would still go to their temple and they would still maintain a lot, spend a lot of

01:41:57.440 --> 01:41:59.440
[Guest]: money on temple rituals.

01:41:59.440 --> 01:42:04.560
[Guest]: But they would not allow themselves to be treated by the British as just these exotic

01:42:04.560 --> 01:42:05.560
[Guest]: exhibits.

01:42:05.560 --> 01:42:10.600
[Guest]: So dressing in a dull grey coat, wearing trousers and shoes and posing on a tricycle, which

01:42:10.600 --> 01:42:14.680
[Guest]: everybody's posing on in Europe and everybody owns in Europe, is a way of signaling that

01:42:14.680 --> 01:42:18.280
[Guest]: I am part of the same cosmopolitan global elite.

01:42:18.280 --> 01:42:19.520
[Guest]: I am part of that same thing.

01:42:19.520 --> 01:42:21.120
[Guest]: I'm an equal member of the same thing.

01:42:21.120 --> 01:42:26.080
[Guest]: I may be brown, but I can also lay claim to that particular, you know, world.

01:42:26.080 --> 01:42:31.760
[Guest]: And you cannot look down at me as though I'm just a sort of prop that's here to look pretty

01:42:31.760 --> 01:42:35.680
[Guest]: while real men who are white come and actually do the governing of my state.

01:42:35.680 --> 01:42:38.040
[Guest]: So he's actually trying to do multiple things all at once.

01:42:38.040 --> 01:42:40.840
[Guest]: He's trying to communicate a certain kind of self-image.

01:42:40.840 --> 01:42:45.900
[Guest]: There's another portrait I describe in the book but don't have a picture of, unfortunately.

01:42:45.900 --> 01:42:49.120
[Guest]: It's a picture with the same Ashwati Tirunel and his older brother.

01:42:49.120 --> 01:42:52.740
[Guest]: They're standing near a globe and the globe, you can see America on it.

01:42:52.740 --> 01:42:56.680
[Guest]: And there's a book in one of their hands and the book, you can see the text is also about

01:42:56.680 --> 01:42:57.680
[Guest]: America.

01:42:57.680 --> 01:43:01.760
[Guest]: Why are they posing like that with a book about America and a globe marking America?

01:43:01.760 --> 01:43:04.240
[Guest]: They're trying to signal that, look, oh, we're sitting here in India.

01:43:04.240 --> 01:43:07.320
[Guest]: We're supposed to be like these backward princes who don't know anything about the world.

01:43:07.320 --> 01:43:11.040
[Guest]: But no, through this book, we're actually exploring the world and here my older brother

01:43:11.040 --> 01:43:15.380
[Guest]: is showing me on the globe, you know, what I'm reading about America in my book.

01:43:15.380 --> 01:43:18.800
[Guest]: It's interesting because if you go back a few decades, there's a painting of Raja Ram Mohan

01:43:18.800 --> 01:43:23.160
[Guest]: Roy's son, where it's also a globe, but Ram Mohan Roy's son is actually showing where

01:43:23.160 --> 01:43:27.960
[Guest]: Bengal is on that map to a Western audience, like he's pointing out Bengal to a presumably

01:43:27.960 --> 01:43:29.040
[Guest]: white audience.

01:43:29.040 --> 01:43:30.640
[Guest]: Here the role is reversed.

01:43:30.640 --> 01:43:36.380
[Guest]: It is Indians laying claim to the larger world rather than pointing out their home to Europeans.

01:43:36.380 --> 01:43:41.880
[Guest]: So these are all forms of sort of defining yourself in a world that is racist, in a world

01:43:41.880 --> 01:43:46.880
[Guest]: that is unequal, and in a world that is competitive because you know the color of your skin and

01:43:46.880 --> 01:43:51.520
[Guest]: your religion, your language will all be held against you as a weakness.

01:43:51.520 --> 01:43:54.920
[Guest]: So on the one hand, celebrating all those things, but on the other hand, superficially

01:43:54.920 --> 01:43:58.880
[Guest]: giving yourself this garb, you're also trying to negotiate both those worlds.

01:43:58.880 --> 01:44:03.000
[Guest]: You're trying to sort of see how much of a balance you can strike between the two.

01:44:03.000 --> 01:44:06.520
[Guest]: And that is what this chap is trying to do and multiple Maharajas try to do.

01:44:06.520 --> 01:44:11.320
[Guest]: As I said, Sayajirao Gaikwad dressing in a simple white Ashkan with just a small necklace

01:44:11.320 --> 01:44:16.400
[Guest]: around his neck and not all the baubles and all the jewels that Baroda and its royal family

01:44:16.400 --> 01:44:17.520
[Guest]: were famous for.

01:44:17.520 --> 01:44:21.520
[Guest]: He wouldn't wear that because he also wanted to prove the point that I'm an active ruler.

01:44:21.520 --> 01:44:22.520
[Guest]: I am in control.

01:44:22.520 --> 01:44:23.520
[Guest]: I'm a working man.

01:44:23.520 --> 01:44:27.720
[Guest]: I'm not somebody who sits around on a throne while other people rule for me.

01:44:27.720 --> 01:44:31.640
[Guest]: There's this bit in Mysore, for example, I describe how in the early 1900s, when a new

01:44:31.640 --> 01:44:36.520
[Guest]: Maharaja grows up and comes to power, an official account with great pride says that the Maharaja

01:44:36.520 --> 01:44:39.280
[Guest]: handed 900 files in his first year.

01:44:39.280 --> 01:44:42.200
[Guest]: It's a form of saying that, you know, our Maharajas also work.

01:44:42.200 --> 01:44:46.120
[Guest]: They're not just sitting in grand palaces and riding elephants, they actually do work.

01:44:46.120 --> 01:44:49.200
[Guest]: And the question about whether he actually did work or not, whether the 900 figure is

01:44:49.200 --> 01:44:50.200
[Guest]: true or not.

01:44:50.200 --> 01:44:55.560
[Guest]: By making that claim, you're essentially signaling that these are active administrators, not

01:44:55.560 --> 01:44:59.900
[Guest]: just pretty boys who are sitting there to sort of titillate Westerners and give them

01:44:59.900 --> 01:45:02.720
[Guest]: an exotic glimpse of some kind of long lost India.

01:45:02.720 --> 01:45:04.080
[Guest]: They were not stuck in the past.

01:45:04.080 --> 01:45:07.520
[Guest]: These people were very much part of that late 19th century colonial universe.

01:45:07.520 --> 01:45:11.360
[Guest]: They were very much part of that change and they wanted to be on top of that change.

01:45:11.360 --> 01:45:14.000
[Guest]: You know, they didn't want to be swept away by change.

01:45:14.000 --> 01:45:17.000
[Guest]: This generation was very keen to be on top of that change.

01:45:17.000 --> 01:45:20.960
[Guest]: The Maharajas were swept away because of things that happened in the 30s and 40s, not in this

01:45:20.960 --> 01:45:21.960
[Guest]: early phase.

01:45:21.960 --> 01:45:25.720
[Guest]: And that's why, as I said, a lot of Indians also treated them with respect, a lot of nationalists

01:45:25.720 --> 01:45:30.920
[Guest]: treated them with respect precisely because they were also fighting a fight that nationalists

01:45:30.920 --> 01:45:34.360
[Guest]: in British India were trying to pull off.

01:45:34.360 --> 01:45:38.280
[Amit Varma]: I'm kind of struck by what you said about how some Maharajas like Ravancore would, you

01:45:38.280 --> 01:45:44.000
[Amit Varma]: know, feel the necessity to signal to their subjects, as it were, their global citizens

01:45:44.000 --> 01:45:47.320
[Amit Varma]: while not caring that the British are actually laughing at them.

01:45:47.320 --> 01:45:52.480
[Amit Varma]: So when I started my writing course last year in April, I got a Facebook request from another

01:45:52.480 --> 01:45:54.920
[Amit Varma]: guy whose description said writing coach.

01:45:54.920 --> 01:45:57.840
[Amit Varma]: So I said, one of my own tribe, let me check out what he does.

01:45:57.840 --> 01:46:02.120
[Amit Varma]: And I went on YouTube and he does all these videos where he's basically telling people

01:46:02.120 --> 01:46:07.400
[Amit Varma]: to do the exact opposite of what I say, where he is saying that never use a simple word.

01:46:07.400 --> 01:46:10.280
[Amit Varma]: For every word, use the most complicated word you can find.

01:46:10.280 --> 01:46:12.080
[Amit Varma]: And then he has demonstrations of it.

01:46:12.080 --> 01:46:17.360
[Amit Varma]: So instead of say, you should say articulate, opine, utter, all of that.

01:46:17.360 --> 01:46:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Basically write with the thesaurus.

01:46:19.000 --> 01:46:20.000
[Amit Varma]: Basically write with the thesaurus.

01:46:20.000 --> 01:46:23.220
[Amit Varma]: And I'll teach you all these kind of words.

01:46:23.220 --> 01:46:26.960
[Amit Varma]: And I realized that that's not irrational and he got millions of views and all that.

01:46:26.960 --> 01:46:27.960
[Amit Varma]: And that's not irrational.

01:46:27.960 --> 01:46:31.920
[Amit Varma]: Like as Snigdha Poonam writes in her book Dreamers, and she was also on my show, that

01:46:31.920 --> 01:46:36.760
[Amit Varma]: one of the rising industries in all these small towns of India is learning English.

01:46:36.760 --> 01:46:38.720
[Amit Varma]: These English coaching institutes.

01:46:38.720 --> 01:46:43.960
[Amit Varma]: And what these people are doing is that their aim isn't clear communication or impacting

01:46:43.960 --> 01:46:47.560
[Amit Varma]: other people with their writing, as the people who sign up for my course would be aiming

01:46:47.560 --> 01:46:48.560
[Amit Varma]: at.

01:46:48.560 --> 01:46:52.560
[Amit Varma]: Their aim is to signal to their peers that I'm so sophisticated, which goes back to that

01:46:52.560 --> 01:46:57.600
[Amit Varma]: English being that marker of class, that the better your English is, you're signaling to

01:46:57.600 --> 01:47:00.320
[Amit Varma]: others where you stand in the social hierarchy.

01:47:00.320 --> 01:47:06.360
[Amit Varma]: And it's kind of fascinating to think that by the mid 19th century, this was already

01:47:06.360 --> 01:47:07.360
[Guest]: in play.

01:47:07.360 --> 01:47:08.360
[Guest]: At the highest levels.

01:47:08.360 --> 01:47:12.600
[Guest]: The other big passion was this, Ashwadya Trinnal and his brother, both were into photography.

01:47:12.600 --> 01:47:15.840
[Guest]: And you actually see these Travenco official publications and official accounts where they

01:47:15.840 --> 01:47:16.840
[Guest]: say both were great photographers.

01:47:16.840 --> 01:47:19.040
[Guest]: They were not great photographers.

01:47:19.040 --> 01:47:24.040
[Guest]: It's just that them wielding the camera, wielding this technology from the West and owning it.

01:47:24.040 --> 01:47:27.800
[Guest]: You know, Ashwadya Trinnal, his claim to fame as far as photography goes is that he took

01:47:27.800 --> 01:47:30.240
[Guest]: a famous portrait of Swami Vivekananda.

01:47:30.240 --> 01:47:33.880
[Guest]: But that process of an Indian prince standing behind the camera and taking a photograph

01:47:33.880 --> 01:47:38.000
[Guest]: of an Indian icon, there's something, again, it's a signaling, it's a statement that is

01:47:38.000 --> 01:47:41.240
[Guest]: being made where Indians can pat each other on the back saying, oh, wow, you know, you've

01:47:41.240 --> 01:47:42.280
[Guest]: picked up the camera.

01:47:42.280 --> 01:47:43.680
[Guest]: You own a Western technology.

01:47:43.680 --> 01:47:48.580
[Guest]: Here you're picking up a Swamiji who's sort of, you know, reforming and sort of redefining

01:47:48.580 --> 01:47:50.760
[Guest]: what Hinduism means in this new age.

01:47:50.760 --> 01:47:54.560
[Guest]: They're all part of that generation that is trying to own that change and be part of it

01:47:54.560 --> 01:47:56.080
[Guest]: and make a political statement.

01:47:56.080 --> 01:48:00.360
[Guest]: Of course, these people had their eccentricities, you know, this Malharrao Gaikwad's brother,

01:48:00.360 --> 01:48:04.720
[Guest]: he saw a Scottish regiment once and immediately got the Baroda troops to start wearing kilts,

01:48:04.720 --> 01:48:07.920
[Guest]: except that he decided to add pink tights to it because they all had brown hairy legs

01:48:07.920 --> 01:48:12.120
[Guest]: and he decided, let me put pink tights, add pink tights to their uniform.

01:48:12.120 --> 01:48:13.620
[Guest]: So they had their quirks.

01:48:13.620 --> 01:48:18.560
[Guest]: But again, to assume that these quirks were just the Maharajas who had them, only they

01:48:18.560 --> 01:48:20.440
[Guest]: had these eccentricities is not true.

01:48:20.440 --> 01:48:24.720
[Guest]: Lord, I don't mention this in the book, but Lord Curzon, you know, this stiff upper lip,

01:48:24.720 --> 01:48:28.000
[Guest]: you know, erect back, very stuffy Viceroy.

01:48:28.000 --> 01:48:31.720
[Guest]: He had it in him to play, to go skinny dipping and play lawn tennis, naked ones.

01:48:31.720 --> 01:48:33.640
[Guest]: He had affairs with married women as well.

01:48:33.640 --> 01:48:36.160
[Guest]: We don't hold it against him because he's a white man.

01:48:36.160 --> 01:48:39.080
[Guest]: You know, that's not what they do is just their private life.

01:48:39.080 --> 01:48:40.080
[Guest]: That's interesting.

01:48:40.080 --> 01:48:44.360
[Guest]: But when an Indian in a position of influence also has, in quotes, an interesting private

01:48:44.360 --> 01:48:48.560
[Guest]: life, that becomes a stick by which to beat them and say, ha ha ha, look at these people.

01:48:48.560 --> 01:48:52.240
[Guest]: So frivolous, so useless, they're not good political figures, they just, they just care

01:48:52.240 --> 01:48:55.140
[Guest]: about their luxury and their, this thing.

01:48:55.140 --> 01:48:59.160
[Guest]: That is unfair because then you have to be fair in terms of dishing out criticism for

01:48:59.160 --> 01:49:01.000
[Guest]: eccentricities across the board.

01:49:01.000 --> 01:49:05.120
[Guest]: Here there's a sort of selectivization where you play on this, which is why, and because

01:49:05.120 --> 01:49:09.520
[Guest]: these people, the Maharajas were very aware of the cliches in which they were trapped,

01:49:09.520 --> 01:49:14.560
[Guest]: some of these people did make an active effort to try and break out of that, to try and,

01:49:14.560 --> 01:49:15.560
[Guest]: you know, look constitutional.

01:49:15.560 --> 01:49:20.240
[Guest]: You know, Mysore Maharaja, you know, very gentle figure, Krishnaraja Wadiyar IV, very

01:49:20.240 --> 01:49:24.720
[Guest]: gentle figure, did not intervene unnecessarily in politics, let his divans, his ministers

01:49:24.720 --> 01:49:25.760
[Guest]: govern for most part.

01:49:25.760 --> 01:49:29.760
[Guest]: He would be in control, he would issue policy directions, but he would not soil his hands

01:49:29.760 --> 01:49:31.340
[Guest]: with the actual running of the government.

01:49:31.340 --> 01:49:36.300
[Guest]: He did try to be this almost constitutional figurehead at the head of the state, uniting

01:49:36.300 --> 01:49:40.560
[Guest]: all the factions and trying to build the state and take it forward into some kind of bright

01:49:40.560 --> 01:49:41.760
[Guest]: industrial future.

01:49:41.760 --> 01:49:43.920
[Guest]: Again, he's also making a political statement.

01:49:43.920 --> 01:49:48.400
[Guest]: He may wear a nachkan, he may wear a turban, but he sees himself very much as a man of

01:49:48.400 --> 01:49:49.400
[Guest]: modernity.

01:49:49.400 --> 01:49:52.760
[Guest]: He doesn't see himself representing some kind of ancient dynasty.

01:49:52.760 --> 01:49:56.280
[Guest]: That's why the Mysore Maharajas, you know, they had the traditional Dasara, which is

01:49:56.280 --> 01:49:59.480
[Guest]: a kingly Dasara, is a tradition that comes all the way from Vijayanagara.

01:49:59.480 --> 01:50:04.040
[Guest]: It's a political symbol that's come down in a traditional way, quote traditional way to

01:50:04.040 --> 01:50:05.040
[Guest]: these Maharajas.

01:50:05.040 --> 01:50:08.180
[Guest]: But at the same Dasara, they also have an industrial exhibition because they're also

01:50:08.180 --> 01:50:10.520
[Guest]: signaling to the world that we are good at industry.

01:50:10.520 --> 01:50:13.400
[Guest]: So all the people of Mysore, they'll bring their crafts and their arts and whatever,

01:50:13.400 --> 01:50:15.000
[Guest]: they'll have a grand exhibition there.

01:50:15.000 --> 01:50:19.240
[Guest]: And the industrial event happening in parallel with Dasara is meant to signal exactly that.

01:50:19.240 --> 01:50:23.080
[Guest]: Dasara is the traditional state event, the industrial thing is the modern state event,

01:50:23.080 --> 01:50:25.240
[Guest]: and both manage to exist together.

01:50:25.240 --> 01:50:29.080
[Guest]: All of these people are therefore, if not successful at trying to sort of negotiate

01:50:29.080 --> 01:50:32.080
[Guest]: this, they're aware of it and they're grappling with that.

01:50:32.080 --> 01:50:36.720
[Guest]: And therefore, that process of grappling itself shows that they are active political figures.

01:50:36.720 --> 01:50:40.920
[Guest]: They're not passive people sitting in enclosed palaces, watching dancing girls and riding

01:50:40.920 --> 01:50:41.920
[Guest]: elephants.

01:50:41.920 --> 01:50:42.920
[Guest]: They had their elephants.

01:50:42.920 --> 01:50:46.280
[Guest]: Mysore had its elephant processions, but it also had its iron and steel works.

01:50:46.280 --> 01:50:50.360
[Guest]: It also had its sandalwood oil factory, and it also had dreams of an automobile factory,

01:50:50.360 --> 01:50:53.000
[Guest]: which is that both can be carried together into the future.

01:50:53.000 --> 01:50:57.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I think Ashwati Tirunal would probably be better remembered as a photographer if

01:50:57.640 --> 01:51:04.160
[Amit Varma]: he had one photograph showing Lord Curzon playing lawn tennis naked, which is so fascinating.

01:51:04.160 --> 01:51:08.420
[Amit Varma]: And you point out how the European view of the royals, at least the view that they're

01:51:08.420 --> 01:51:13.360
[Amit Varma]: putting out there in the narrative is so derogatory and so based on these stereotypes, like at

01:51:13.360 --> 01:51:18.440
[Amit Varma]: one point you quote the phrase, like a scorpion at the base of a beautiful lily, you know,

01:51:18.440 --> 01:51:22.640
[Amit Varma]: implying that's a quote, and you're implying that they don't deserve India.

01:51:22.640 --> 01:51:26.640
[Amit Varma]: And at another point, while talking about their view, you say, quote, for the British,

01:51:26.640 --> 01:51:31.280
[Amit Varma]: it conveniently infantilized Indian rulers and cemented the claim that natives were simply

01:51:31.280 --> 01:51:33.240
[Amit Varma]: capable of serious government.

01:51:33.240 --> 01:51:38.160
[Amit Varma]: India's traditional leaders were no good except for frivolous sex and fancy dress, thus justifying

01:51:38.160 --> 01:51:40.600
[Amit Varma]: stern manly imperial supervision.

01:51:40.600 --> 01:51:45.840
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, for a younger crop of nationalists animated by democratic ideals, silken autocracy

01:51:45.840 --> 01:51:47.960
[Amit Varma]: was a relic of feudal yesterdays.

01:51:47.960 --> 01:51:52.280
[Amit Varma]: India's destiny recovered after a long struggle, could not broke men who played no part in

01:51:52.280 --> 01:51:54.360
[Amit Varma]: the battles that mattered, stop quote.

01:51:54.360 --> 01:51:58.240
[Amit Varma]: And your book basically busts these kind of stereotypes.

01:51:58.240 --> 01:52:04.680
[Amit Varma]: Give me a sense of what is the landscape around this time of princely India, like one of the

01:52:04.680 --> 01:52:08.920
[Amit Varma]: sort of things that you've pointed out, which I think many listeners may not realize is

01:52:08.920 --> 01:52:12.520
[Amit Varma]: that there isn't British India, there is a British ruled India, and there is an India

01:52:12.520 --> 01:52:17.480
[Amit Varma]: ruled India, which is the princely states, which controls 40% of the territory with about

01:52:17.480 --> 01:52:21.360
[Amit Varma]: 25% of the population, you know, coming within his bounds.

01:52:21.360 --> 01:52:23.560
[Amit Varma]: So now, what is that like?

01:52:23.560 --> 01:52:27.120
[Amit Varma]: And what are the arrangements that the British have with them?

01:52:27.120 --> 01:52:31.760
[Amit Varma]: Like one very fundamental kind of meta question is, how does the British have so much say

01:52:31.760 --> 01:52:35.160
[Amit Varma]: that they are controlling all of these princely states?

01:52:35.160 --> 01:52:38.920
[Amit Varma]: Like do they have a powerful army out there, you know, is there a stick?

01:52:38.920 --> 01:52:39.920
[Amit Varma]: Is there a carrot?

01:52:39.920 --> 01:52:44.320
[Amit Varma]: How has that process kind of evolved that even someone like a Sayajee Rao, who's been

01:52:44.320 --> 01:52:48.600
[Amit Varma]: funding all these revolutionaries, you know, is worried about being deposed by them and

01:52:48.600 --> 01:52:50.640
[Amit Varma]: just completely chills after that.

01:52:50.640 --> 01:52:53.340
[Amit Varma]: So lay out a landscape for me.

01:52:53.340 --> 01:52:57.680
[Guest]: Each of these princely states, the way they came into contact with the British would vary.

01:52:57.680 --> 01:53:01.720
[Guest]: You know, for example, the state of Pudukottai, its rulers were a recent royal family.

01:53:01.720 --> 01:53:04.280
[Guest]: As I said, they came from a caste that was not a caste of kings.

01:53:04.280 --> 01:53:08.400
[Guest]: They were considered a robber caste, you know, but they became the system in that particular

01:53:08.400 --> 01:53:09.400
[Guest]: region.

01:53:09.400 --> 01:53:13.200
[Guest]: And the time when they were transitioning to kingship also happened to be the time when

01:53:13.200 --> 01:53:15.440
[Guest]: the East India Company was coming into power.

01:53:15.440 --> 01:53:19.120
[Guest]: And the Pudukottai royal family saw an advantage in allying with the East India Company because

01:53:19.120 --> 01:53:21.800
[Guest]: it would aid and augment their rise to kingship.

01:53:21.800 --> 01:53:22.960
[Guest]: And that is precisely what happened.

01:53:22.960 --> 01:53:26.800
[Guest]: With Pudukottai, in fact, Pudukottai did not pay tribute to the British, nothing, nor did

01:53:26.800 --> 01:53:28.240
[Guest]: they have a treaty with the British.

01:53:28.240 --> 01:53:32.880
[Guest]: There was no paper that was signed between the Raja and the East India Company, you know,

01:53:32.880 --> 01:53:34.560
[Guest]: defining what the relationship was.

01:53:34.560 --> 01:53:38.160
[Guest]: But because of their respective political, you know, influence and clout, the British

01:53:38.160 --> 01:53:41.200
[Guest]: were obviously the superior and the Pudukottai Raja was the inferior.

01:53:41.200 --> 01:53:42.200
[Guest]: Gwalior was different.

01:53:42.200 --> 01:53:45.560
[Guest]: You know, Gwalior, for example, the Marathas were defeated only in 1818.

01:53:45.560 --> 01:53:48.240
[Guest]: We often think that Battle of Plassey means British Empire begun.

01:53:48.240 --> 01:53:49.240
[Guest]: Not true.

01:53:49.240 --> 01:53:50.800
[Guest]: Battle of Plassey is in Bengal.

01:53:50.800 --> 01:53:55.300
[Guest]: By the time the Sikhs are defeated, it's 1849, a whole century passes before the British

01:53:55.300 --> 01:53:58.480
[Guest]: have full control of what we call the Indian subcontinent.

01:53:58.480 --> 01:54:02.600
[Guest]: It's in that century that a lot of these Maharajas fall into various alliances and

01:54:02.600 --> 01:54:04.360
[Guest]: sort of arrangements with the British.

01:54:04.360 --> 01:54:09.520
[Guest]: So with Gwalior, for example, they were defeated, they sort of come to terms in the early 19th

01:54:09.520 --> 01:54:10.520
[Guest]: century.

01:54:10.520 --> 01:54:14.400
[Guest]: But Gwalior, till the 1840s, has a very strong army of 40,000 soldiers.

01:54:14.400 --> 01:54:18.340
[Guest]: The British still can't sort of, you know, boss around Gwalior because it has armed troops.

01:54:18.340 --> 01:54:21.820
[Guest]: It has foreigners who are training these troops, not British, but people from other countries

01:54:21.820 --> 01:54:24.020
[Guest]: in Europe who are training these troops.

01:54:24.020 --> 01:54:27.200
[Guest]: Most importantly, Gwalior has a lot of profit coming in from opium sales.

01:54:27.200 --> 01:54:31.040
[Guest]: The British want to sort of control opium sales because they've got China and, you know,

01:54:31.040 --> 01:54:32.440
[Guest]: the wider history of that.

01:54:32.440 --> 01:54:33.800
[Guest]: And Gwalior tries to subvert it.

01:54:33.800 --> 01:54:37.240
[Guest]: It says we will find our own market, we will not come into the British system because its

01:54:37.240 --> 01:54:41.360
[Guest]: money depends on that and that money is important for maintaining the army and that army gives

01:54:41.360 --> 01:54:44.520
[Guest]: Gwalior the teeth to withstand further British encroachment.

01:54:44.520 --> 01:54:49.520
[Guest]: Finally, of course, the British, it's in a military action in 1843 that the British take

01:54:49.520 --> 01:54:50.600
[Guest]: over Gwalior.

01:54:50.600 --> 01:54:55.040
[Guest]: But because it was so late, unlike, for example, in Travancore where the resident was already

01:54:55.040 --> 01:54:59.640
[Guest]: bullying the Raja in 1810, because by then the British were in that much control and

01:54:59.640 --> 01:55:03.480
[Guest]: they were able to disband the Travancore army, which meant that the Raja had no teeth by

01:55:03.480 --> 01:55:05.040
[Guest]: which he could bite them.

01:55:05.040 --> 01:55:08.960
[Guest]: Gwalior, because it had teeth till the 1840s, Gwalior actually treated the East India Company

01:55:08.960 --> 01:55:10.680
[Guest]: with contempt for the longest time.

01:55:10.680 --> 01:55:14.140
[Guest]: You know, when there was this one resident who came in during the regency of this Rani

01:55:14.140 --> 01:55:18.380
[Guest]: called Baizabai and when he arrived, he found nobody had been sent out to receive him.

01:55:18.380 --> 01:55:21.720
[Guest]: He was treated like any other letter writer, you know, one of these reporters who used

01:55:21.720 --> 01:55:22.720
[Guest]: to come from other courts.

01:55:22.720 --> 01:55:25.720
[Guest]: He was treated just at that level, not given any importance.

01:55:25.720 --> 01:55:29.680
[Guest]: He couldn't even find firewood to light in his kitchen the day he arrived because no

01:55:29.680 --> 01:55:30.800
[Guest]: arrangements had been made.

01:55:30.800 --> 01:55:34.640
[Guest]: She consciously treated him as a non-entity because she had the power to do it.

01:55:34.640 --> 01:55:38.760
[Guest]: Of course, after 1843, when the army is gone and the army is completely smashed, Gwalior

01:55:38.760 --> 01:55:40.740
[Guest]: also has to fall into line.

01:55:40.740 --> 01:55:43.560
[Guest]: This is not the same, for example, with the Kathiawar states.

01:55:43.560 --> 01:55:47.360
[Guest]: The Kathiawar states were those, the 300 odd, hundreds of states spread over a very small

01:55:47.360 --> 01:55:48.640
[Guest]: territory.

01:55:48.640 --> 01:55:50.160
[Guest]: Many of them the British had no treaties with.

01:55:50.160 --> 01:55:52.560
[Guest]: They were paying tribute to one ruler before that.

01:55:52.560 --> 01:55:55.080
[Guest]: The British became the next overlord, so the British took the place.

01:55:55.080 --> 01:55:58.960
[Guest]: So for them, it was just the overlord changing, not a big deal.

01:55:58.960 --> 01:56:02.840
[Guest]: With Rajputana, very complicated because in the early 19th century, you have the British

01:56:02.840 --> 01:56:03.840
[Guest]: coming.

01:56:03.840 --> 01:56:08.360
[Guest]: They will sign, they all sign their treaties with the British, becoming allies.

01:56:08.360 --> 01:56:09.360
[Guest]: Then there's a shift.

01:56:09.360 --> 01:56:12.680
[Guest]: Lord Wellesley is replaced by another viceroy, another governor general, who's not interested

01:56:12.680 --> 01:56:13.680
[Guest]: in this.

01:56:13.680 --> 01:56:16.920
[Guest]: He wants to pull back the East India Company from being mired in too much Indian politics

01:56:16.920 --> 01:56:18.920
[Guest]: and all these treaties are abrogated.

01:56:18.920 --> 01:56:23.000
[Guest]: Then it's only after 1818 when the Marathas are defeated that the British walk into the

01:56:23.000 --> 01:56:28.040
[Guest]: vacuum that the Marathas have left and claim control of the Rajput states.

01:56:28.040 --> 01:56:31.000
[Guest]: But here again, the internal Rajput structure is very different.

01:56:31.000 --> 01:56:34.880
[Guest]: The British find that because the Rajput states in the Maratha period have been weakened or

01:56:34.880 --> 01:56:39.680
[Guest]: the Raja has been weakened, the Raja's subordinate vassals have become very powerful.

01:56:39.680 --> 01:56:42.840
[Guest]: So the Rajas have an incentive in allying with the East India Company because the East

01:56:42.840 --> 01:56:48.200
[Guest]: India Company soldiers will help the Raja reclaim his power, push back the vassals,

01:56:48.200 --> 01:56:50.960
[Guest]: put them back in their place and the Raja can reclaim power.

01:56:50.960 --> 01:56:56.880
[Guest]: So it's not as though these Rajas sort of all fell down and sort of prostrated before

01:56:56.880 --> 01:56:57.880
[Guest]: the British.

01:56:57.880 --> 01:57:00.680
[Guest]: They had various incentives for allying with the British.

01:57:00.680 --> 01:57:03.340
[Guest]: Some cases it was forced, Gwalior in 1843.

01:57:03.340 --> 01:57:07.240
[Guest]: Some cases the Rajas wanted the British to come because they needed to rescue themselves

01:57:07.240 --> 01:57:10.200
[Guest]: from their own subordinates and their own nobles because they were being cornered in

01:57:10.200 --> 01:57:12.640
[Guest]: their local political structures.

01:57:12.640 --> 01:57:16.120
[Guest]: In some cases like Travancore, Travancore had no option because they needed East India

01:57:16.120 --> 01:57:20.000
[Guest]: Company support in the 1790s fighting Tipu Sultan.

01:57:20.000 --> 01:57:23.680
[Guest]: That is where they had to sort of get into bed with the British.

01:57:23.680 --> 01:57:26.520
[Guest]: Each state therefore has a different reason for allying with the British.

01:57:26.520 --> 01:57:28.120
[Guest]: Some may pay tribute, some may not.

01:57:28.120 --> 01:57:29.760
[Guest]: Some may have a treaty, some may not.

01:57:29.760 --> 01:57:32.460
[Guest]: There's actually no structure to the way the British did this.

01:57:32.460 --> 01:57:37.360
[Guest]: Even when they classed, for example, Pudukottai was a princely state, but its original overlord,

01:57:37.360 --> 01:57:41.640
[Guest]: the kingdom of Ramnath, was classed as a Zamindari, which is lower than Pudukottai, but even though

01:57:41.640 --> 01:57:46.120
[Guest]: the histories of the states are different, where Ramnath is superior, Pudukottai is inferior,

01:57:46.120 --> 01:57:50.720
[Guest]: the British sort of topple it and invert it because of various historical contingencies.

01:57:50.720 --> 01:57:56.480
[Guest]: So there's lots of things happening in different places and we sort of assume that India as

01:57:56.480 --> 01:58:02.520
[Guest]: a political entity was a given, which it was not, which was also why during the 1857 rebellion,

01:58:02.520 --> 01:58:06.400
[Guest]: Travancore loudly supported the British and said, we stand loyally with the British.

01:58:06.400 --> 01:58:10.440
[Guest]: Not because he cared for the British, the Raja had been facing pressures of annexation

01:58:10.440 --> 01:58:11.440
[Guest]: at that time.

01:58:11.440 --> 01:58:13.520
[Guest]: He was afraid the British were going to annex his state.

01:58:13.520 --> 01:58:19.560
[Guest]: So when they were in a crisis, by loudly proclaiming loyalty, he was basically trying to put them

01:58:19.560 --> 01:58:22.340
[Guest]: in a moral position to not annex his state.

01:58:22.340 --> 01:58:25.440
[Guest]: Because he had shown that when they were at their lowest and their weakest, he stood with

01:58:25.440 --> 01:58:26.440
[Guest]: them.

01:58:26.440 --> 01:58:29.520
[Guest]: It's a footnote in this book, but Priya Atwal in her book on the Sikhs, she talks about

01:58:29.520 --> 01:58:34.100
[Guest]: those few Punjab states that survived, Kapurthala, Patiala, etc.

01:58:34.100 --> 01:58:38.000
[Guest]: They signed with the East India Company because they knew Ranjit Singh was becoming too big.

01:58:38.000 --> 01:58:41.840
[Guest]: So there's this wonderful quote she says, where one of the Rajas basically says that

01:58:41.840 --> 01:58:46.120
[Guest]: my options are, it's a quick death with Ranjit Singh or slow death with the British.

01:58:46.120 --> 01:58:47.120
[Guest]: I choose slow death.

01:58:47.120 --> 01:58:51.120
[Guest]: So at least I have some more years in power and my state will continue for some more time

01:58:51.120 --> 01:58:56.240
[Guest]: in a truncated form, as opposed to being completely wiped out by the Sikh empire of Ranjit Singh.

01:58:56.240 --> 01:58:58.560
[Guest]: All of these are calculated decisions.

01:58:58.560 --> 01:59:01.760
[Guest]: Each of them has their local, individual reason for allying.

01:59:01.760 --> 01:59:04.800
[Guest]: They did not see themselves as part of one unified nation.

01:59:04.800 --> 01:59:06.400
[Guest]: That frankly did not exist.

01:59:06.400 --> 01:59:08.400
[Guest]: Nationalism was constructed in India.

01:59:08.400 --> 01:59:11.300
[Guest]: Perhaps we had what people call a civilizational identity and all that.

01:59:11.300 --> 01:59:13.160
[Guest]: But that was not nationalism.

01:59:13.160 --> 01:59:18.000
[Guest]: Nationalism was consciously, painfully, painstakingly constructed in the late 19th century.

01:59:18.000 --> 01:59:21.440
[Guest]: Before that, all of these people saw themselves as belonging to different regions.

01:59:21.440 --> 01:59:25.360
[Guest]: A Travancore Maharaja had no incentive in joining an anti-British rebellion with the

01:59:25.360 --> 01:59:27.080
[Guest]: Raja of Banaras, for example.

01:59:27.080 --> 01:59:31.040
[Guest]: A Nizam of Hyderabad didn't see why he had to join forces with a Maharaja of Kashmir,

01:59:31.040 --> 01:59:32.040
[Guest]: for example.

01:59:32.040 --> 01:59:37.280
[Guest]: They saw themselves as legitimate rulers of legitimate, independent political spaces.

01:59:37.280 --> 01:59:40.720
[Guest]: Their priority was not fighting for a larger India because that concept of a larger did

01:59:40.720 --> 01:59:42.520
[Guest]: not, India did not exist.

01:59:42.520 --> 01:59:45.240
[Guest]: Their concept was simply, I will fight to protect my turf.

01:59:45.240 --> 01:59:49.280
[Guest]: I will fight to protect my kingdom because I am the legitimate king of this kingdom.

01:59:49.280 --> 01:59:53.240
[Guest]: So the terms itself are different and the landscape therefore is this patchy landscape

01:59:53.240 --> 01:59:56.960
[Guest]: where you have British territories and then intervening it, you've got lots of princely

01:59:56.960 --> 01:59:57.960
[Guest]: territories.

01:59:57.960 --> 01:59:59.960
[Guest]: A lot of princely states were not compact.

01:59:59.960 --> 02:00:04.120
[Guest]: Baroda, for example, was spread over four or five different parcels of land.

02:00:04.120 --> 02:00:07.440
[Guest]: So there was one set of territories around the capital.

02:00:07.440 --> 02:00:11.320
[Guest]: Then disconnected from that, there are three other territories because that's how its exchange

02:00:11.320 --> 02:00:12.640
[Guest]: with the British took place.

02:00:12.640 --> 02:00:15.960
[Guest]: A lot of states in Kathiawad used to pay tribute to Baroda.

02:00:15.960 --> 02:00:18.720
[Guest]: The British eventually came in and said, we will collect that tribute for you.

02:00:18.720 --> 02:00:22.160
[Guest]: So there was a weird sort of political arrangement there also.

02:00:22.160 --> 02:00:27.160
[Guest]: In Rajputana, the Rajput Maharajas paid, many of them paid tribute to the British only based

02:00:27.160 --> 02:00:31.200
[Guest]: on the revenue of what was called their core sort of crown territory.

02:00:31.200 --> 02:00:34.520
[Guest]: Their vassals territories were not included because the vassals had their own autonomous

02:00:34.520 --> 02:00:35.520
[Guest]: rights.

02:00:35.520 --> 02:00:38.840
[Guest]: And most importantly, these vassals would often lobby the British for independent recognition

02:00:38.840 --> 02:00:39.840
[Guest]: as princely states.

02:00:39.840 --> 02:00:43.520
[Guest]: So the Rajas had to also quickly sit with the, if the British resident was sitting with

02:00:43.520 --> 02:00:47.000
[Guest]: a danda over the Raja's head, the Raja was sitting with a danda over his vassal's heads

02:00:47.000 --> 02:00:49.240
[Guest]: to prevent the vassals from becoming too big.

02:00:49.240 --> 02:00:52.560
[Guest]: So there's, you know, each of these states is balancing different things and thinking

02:00:52.560 --> 02:00:56.680
[Guest]: very much from a, let's say, I wouldn't say myopic because that assumes that they were

02:00:56.680 --> 02:00:58.760
[Guest]: somehow supposed to have a grand vision.

02:00:58.760 --> 02:01:03.000
[Guest]: But they were thinking from their respective individual positions which to them were very

02:01:03.000 --> 02:01:06.880
[Guest]: legitimate and the people in those days also recognized it as legitimate.

02:01:06.880 --> 02:01:11.680
[Amit Varma]: So I have three follow up questions from this, at least three, more might occur.

02:01:11.680 --> 02:01:15.840
[Amit Varma]: But the first of them is this, that when you speak of civilizational identity, that there's

02:01:15.840 --> 02:01:19.360
[Amit Varma]: a possibility that there might have been a civilizational identity.

02:01:19.360 --> 02:01:20.360
[Amit Varma]: Was there one?

02:01:20.360 --> 02:01:21.360
[Amit Varma]: What is your sense?

02:01:21.360 --> 02:01:23.900
[Amit Varma]: And if so, how would it have been constructed?

02:01:23.900 --> 02:01:26.320
[Amit Varma]: Because this is not the age of mass media.

02:01:26.320 --> 02:01:28.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, all these states are very different things.

02:01:28.240 --> 02:01:30.360
[Amit Varma]: There's not much communication going on.

02:01:30.360 --> 02:01:32.100
[Amit Varma]: All these are separate languages.

02:01:32.100 --> 02:01:36.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, I assume that there is hardly any interaction or common culture between the

02:01:36.600 --> 02:01:39.880
[Amit Varma]: people of Patiala and the people of Travancore, for example.

02:01:39.880 --> 02:01:43.440
[Amit Varma]: So do you find a sense of that civilizational identity?

02:01:43.440 --> 02:01:47.400
[Amit Varma]: Like one thing that we discussed in the middle episode we did, the second out of the three

02:01:47.400 --> 02:01:53.560
[Amit Varma]: episodes we've done so far, is where you spoke about how a lot of modern Hinduism might actually

02:01:53.560 --> 02:01:58.080
[Amit Varma]: have ended up being a colonial construct in the sense that the British come to India who

02:01:58.080 --> 02:02:00.240
[Amit Varma]: are their early intellectual tutors.

02:02:00.240 --> 02:02:04.720
[Amit Varma]: It sees elite Brahmins who sell them on this vision of Brahmanism with the caste system

02:02:04.720 --> 02:02:05.840
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

02:02:05.840 --> 02:02:10.320
[Amit Varma]: And then that becomes a way the British look at India, and they control all the mass media,

02:02:10.320 --> 02:02:11.880
[Amit Varma]: and they control the narratives.

02:02:11.880 --> 02:02:14.080
[Amit Varma]: And today that becomes a way we look at ourselves.

02:02:14.080 --> 02:02:16.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's not necessarily the case.

02:02:16.120 --> 02:02:20.720
[Amit Varma]: So that is sort of one civilizational view which is playing out among, you know, elite

02:02:20.720 --> 02:02:23.700
[Amit Varma]: Brahmins and elite colonial forces.

02:02:23.700 --> 02:02:29.720
[Amit Varma]: But is there a broader civilizational identity you feel that is there, or is it all dissipated

02:02:29.720 --> 02:02:34.640
[Amit Varma]: and dispersed and different things everywhere and multitudes that eventually move towards

02:02:34.640 --> 02:02:36.940
[Amit Varma]: homogeneity but at that time, they don't?

02:02:36.940 --> 02:02:39.560
[Amit Varma]: As a historian, how does one even get a sense of this?

02:02:39.560 --> 02:02:44.320
[Amit Varma]: Because if someone writes a history of 2021, you have plenty of sources, you know what

02:02:44.320 --> 02:02:46.440
[Amit Varma]: everybody thinks because of social media.

02:02:46.440 --> 02:02:48.240
[Amit Varma]: How do you get a sense of what it was like then?

02:02:48.240 --> 02:02:49.240
[Amit Varma]: And what is your sense?

02:02:49.240 --> 02:02:53.440
[Guest]: See, one of the issues with this is also conceptual, which is that some people say Hinduism was

02:02:53.440 --> 02:02:55.000
[Guest]: invented by the British.

02:02:55.000 --> 02:02:59.040
[Guest]: I wouldn't say the Hindu religion was invented by the British, to say that Hinduism as a

02:02:59.040 --> 02:03:03.000
[Guest]: religion was invented by the British basically means, oh, it was only in this time that we

02:03:03.000 --> 02:03:06.280
[Guest]: decided we must have a core set of books and a core set of beliefs, etc.

02:03:06.280 --> 02:03:11.560
[Guest]: That much is true, that we absorbed the Western definition of what a religion must be, which

02:03:11.560 --> 02:03:14.960
[Guest]: means books to chahiye because Christians and Jews, everybody has books, so we must

02:03:14.960 --> 02:03:16.120
[Guest]: also find books.

02:03:16.120 --> 02:03:20.820
[Guest]: So we've perhaps taken that conceptual bracket, but all the same, that religious identity

02:03:20.820 --> 02:03:23.120
[Guest]: sort of existed before that as well.

02:03:23.120 --> 02:03:25.200
[Guest]: It was not invented by the British.

02:03:25.200 --> 02:03:30.320
[Guest]: The current shape we've given to it was the conceptual bracket came from that particular

02:03:30.320 --> 02:03:31.320
[Guest]: period.

02:03:31.320 --> 02:03:35.840
[Guest]: But prior to that also, for example, because of the Puranic tradition, for example, a villager

02:03:35.840 --> 02:03:38.760
[Guest]: in Patiala and a villager in Travancore may not know much about each other.

02:03:38.760 --> 02:03:42.400
[Guest]: Their practice of Hinduism may also be different, but both would have heard the Ramayana, both

02:03:42.400 --> 02:03:45.920
[Guest]: would have heard the Mahabharata, and both would not have gone to Kashi, but they would

02:03:45.920 --> 02:03:48.200
[Guest]: know that there is such a place as Kashi.

02:03:48.200 --> 02:03:52.240
[Guest]: That place exists somewhere in that spiritual landscape, somewhere in that mental map.

02:03:52.240 --> 02:03:54.800
[Guest]: You don't even have an idea of what the Indian subcontinent looks like.

02:03:54.800 --> 02:03:56.060
[Guest]: Nobody's seen a map.

02:03:56.060 --> 02:03:57.760
[Guest]: But you know there is a place called Kashi.

02:03:57.760 --> 02:04:00.040
[Guest]: This is broadly the direction in which Kashi lies.

02:04:00.040 --> 02:04:02.840
[Guest]: The Patiala guy will also know there is a place called Rameshwaram because he knows

02:04:02.840 --> 02:04:05.040
[Guest]: vaguely that there is something there.

02:04:05.040 --> 02:04:10.280
[Guest]: So that spiritual landscape is perhaps a common thread that you find, and that is constructed

02:04:10.280 --> 02:04:14.280
[Guest]: not through the Vedas, not through some kind of esoteric ideas, but through these wonderful

02:04:14.280 --> 02:04:16.320
[Guest]: narratives that is the Puranic tradition.

02:04:16.320 --> 02:04:20.960
[Guest]: These stories are basically weaving together different things and sort of giving them a

02:04:20.960 --> 02:04:22.360
[Guest]: sort of overarching umbrella.

02:04:22.360 --> 02:04:25.760
[Guest]: You know, you're basically saying that all this is true, that's why some of the stories

02:04:25.760 --> 02:04:26.960
[Guest]: are sometimes contradictory.

02:04:26.960 --> 02:04:30.920
[Guest]: The British read these Puranic texts and they say, there is no consistency, there's no chronology,

02:04:30.920 --> 02:04:32.360
[Guest]: why are these stories so chaotic?

02:04:32.360 --> 02:04:35.240
[Guest]: You start a story and then you digress into five different stories, then you come back

02:04:35.240 --> 02:04:37.320
[Guest]: and again digress into something else.

02:04:37.320 --> 02:04:40.540
[Guest]: It's not because it was chaotic or people didn't have structure.

02:04:40.540 --> 02:04:43.840
[Guest]: It was because at different times, different elements, different parts of the country were

02:04:43.840 --> 02:04:49.440
[Guest]: being woven together into one messy, but one unified narrative fabric.

02:04:49.440 --> 02:04:53.080
[Guest]: That fabric still has different threads of different colors, but it is one fabric.

02:04:53.080 --> 02:04:58.200
[Guest]: To that extent, yes, I think there was some awareness that there is this broader thing.

02:04:58.200 --> 02:05:03.520
[Guest]: And you see that as technology gets better, access to these places becomes stronger.

02:05:03.520 --> 02:05:08.440
[Guest]: The biggest set of Brahmins in Banaras, which is in northern India, was from Maharashtra.

02:05:08.440 --> 02:05:12.080
[Guest]: Because the Marathas, as they picked up, as they sort of spread out, their armies would

02:05:12.080 --> 02:05:15.960
[Guest]: also be accompanied by Brahmins, their armies would also be accompanied by pilgrims.

02:05:15.960 --> 02:05:20.080
[Guest]: And it became a way for the Maratha state to flaunt its piety because everybody knew

02:05:20.080 --> 02:05:21.880
[Guest]: that Kashi was an important state.

02:05:21.880 --> 02:05:24.120
[Guest]: Nobody had seen Kashi, but it was an important city.

02:05:24.120 --> 02:05:28.000
[Guest]: So when the Maratha kings and nobles built ghats over there, the current form of Kashi

02:05:28.000 --> 02:05:30.840
[Guest]: was largely built in the Maratha period.

02:05:30.840 --> 02:05:34.640
[Guest]: When they do that, and they go, even if they say, they go to some place in Tamil Nadu and

02:05:34.640 --> 02:05:38.720
[Guest]: say, we renovated Kashi, we built 20 ghats in Kashi, people will understand the importance

02:05:38.720 --> 02:05:39.720
[Guest]: of it.

02:05:39.720 --> 02:05:43.160
[Guest]: You know, they may not have been to Kashi, they may not know where Kashi is, but they

02:05:43.160 --> 02:05:47.160
[Guest]: know doing this in Kashi is a pious, important thing and therefore they will connect on that

02:05:47.160 --> 02:05:48.760
[Guest]: particular plane.

02:05:48.760 --> 02:05:51.840
[Guest]: Even so, it's not like the Maratha version of, or Maratha's practice of Hinduism was

02:05:51.840 --> 02:05:55.200
[Guest]: what a Bengali would practice, nor that a Maratha invasion, suddenly Bengalis would

02:05:55.200 --> 02:05:57.240
[Guest]: all clap saying, welcome your fellow Hindus.

02:05:57.240 --> 02:06:01.600
[Guest]: No, on the contrary, when the Marathas invaded Bengal, you have the Maharashtra Puran which

02:06:01.600 --> 02:06:03.640
[Guest]: is rather scathing of the Marathas.

02:06:03.640 --> 02:06:05.920
[Guest]: They don't see a common element there.

02:06:05.920 --> 02:06:10.400
[Guest]: When Puri is taken from the Marathas by the British, the Puri priests actually write a

02:06:10.400 --> 02:06:14.080
[Guest]: letter to the East India Company Governor General Lord Wellesley, praising him to the

02:06:14.080 --> 02:06:17.640
[Guest]: sky saying, you are the best of all monarchs we've had so far.

02:06:17.640 --> 02:06:21.320
[Guest]: So far we couldn't breathe in peace, but you've come, therefore we are, you know, finally

02:06:21.320 --> 02:06:22.320
[Guest]: at ease, etc.

02:06:22.320 --> 02:06:25.960
[Guest]: Super, you know, superlative language they use for an Englishman.

02:06:25.960 --> 02:06:30.240
[Guest]: But there is an awareness, there is knowledge, you know, that these places and these sacred

02:06:30.240 --> 02:06:31.680
[Guest]: sites matter.

02:06:31.680 --> 02:06:34.920
[Guest]: It's something, that's why even the Marathas, when they come into Orissa for the first time,

02:06:34.920 --> 02:06:39.920
[Guest]: they want control of Puri, because controlling Puri not only marks status, it sends a message

02:06:39.920 --> 02:06:41.280
[Guest]: out to lots of people.

02:06:41.280 --> 02:06:46.520
[Guest]: You know, kings ally themselves with important temples because it has a larger resonance

02:06:46.520 --> 02:06:48.480
[Guest]: than his very localized power.

02:06:48.480 --> 02:06:52.760
[Guest]: His power may be localized, but by weaving himself to an important site mentioned in

02:06:52.760 --> 02:06:57.240
[Guest]: the Puranas, mentioned in traditional accounts, he's also connecting himself to that larger

02:06:57.240 --> 02:06:58.240
[Guest]: fabric.

02:06:58.240 --> 02:07:01.240
[Guest]: So there is a fabric, but it's not like somebody's given it a shape.

02:07:01.240 --> 02:07:04.800
[Guest]: You can't say it's a rectangular fabric or a square fabric with perfect borders.

02:07:04.800 --> 02:07:09.480
[Guest]: It's a constantly knitted, constantly being, someone's constantly weaving and adding more

02:07:09.480 --> 02:07:10.480
[Guest]: things to it.

02:07:10.480 --> 02:07:14.600
[Guest]: In different directions, the fabric is going, growing in different ways, but something exists

02:07:14.600 --> 02:07:16.520
[Guest]: and people are aware of that something.

02:07:16.520 --> 02:07:20.680
[Guest]: When they say, as I said, when they say that, you know, I've gone to Kashi, that has meaning

02:07:20.680 --> 02:07:24.440
[Guest]: no matter where you are in India, that word Kashi represents something.

02:07:24.440 --> 02:07:28.960
[Guest]: And if you understand it and the other person also understands it, you're part of that particular

02:07:28.960 --> 02:07:29.960
[Guest]: fabric.

02:07:29.960 --> 02:07:32.280
[Guest]: So, you know, that is how I would, I would define it.

02:07:32.280 --> 02:07:36.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you made the fabric expanding in all directions, no shapes sound like H.P Lovecraft's

02:07:36.440 --> 02:07:37.440
[Amit Varma]: Thulu.

02:07:37.440 --> 02:07:41.400
[Amit Varma]: Another good reason to control poori, of course, is that if you control poori, sooner or later,

02:07:41.400 --> 02:07:42.400
[Amit Varma]: you control aloo.

02:07:42.400 --> 02:07:46.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I had to get my one dad joke out of the way.

02:07:46.640 --> 02:07:49.680
[Amit Varma]: I would, of course, never argue with you because zero knowledge, but the only part of what

02:07:49.680 --> 02:07:53.640
[Amit Varma]: you said that I feel a little skeptical towards is when you said a person in Patiala would

02:07:53.640 --> 02:07:54.640
[Amit Varma]: know where Rameshwaram is.

02:07:54.640 --> 02:07:58.880
[Amit Varma]: Dude, a person in Patiala today doesn't know where Rameshwaram is.

02:07:58.880 --> 02:08:01.880
[Amit Varma]: And if you're listening to this from Patiala, you're obviously an outlier because you're

02:08:01.880 --> 02:08:02.880
[Guest]: listening to this.

02:08:02.880 --> 02:08:06.800
[Guest]: No, they wouldn't call it Rameshwaram, they would call it Dakshinakashi, which is, you

02:08:06.800 --> 02:08:07.800
[Guest]: know, the southern Kashi.

02:08:07.800 --> 02:08:08.800
[Amit Varma]: That's how it's been called.

02:08:08.800 --> 02:08:09.800
[Amit Varma]: I don't think so.

02:08:09.800 --> 02:08:14.480
[Guest]: If you generally go to, let's say, a person who's, you know, vaguely well versed in these

02:08:14.480 --> 02:08:15.480
[Guest]: Puranic things.

02:08:15.480 --> 02:08:19.200
[Guest]: Frankly, I shouldn't have said Patiala because Punjab is slightly an outlier in these things,

02:08:19.200 --> 02:08:22.680
[Guest]: which is why even the old Brahmins used to include that in what was called Mleccha Desha,

02:08:22.680 --> 02:08:25.280
[Guest]: you know, barbarian country, don't even go there.

02:08:25.280 --> 02:08:27.680
[Guest]: And caste wasn't as strong as it was in the Gangetic belt.

02:08:27.680 --> 02:08:29.920
[Guest]: So maybe that was the wrong example to give.

02:08:29.920 --> 02:08:34.240
[Guest]: But still, if you found somebody who would broadly belong to that Hindu tradition, was

02:08:34.240 --> 02:08:38.200
[Guest]: not a Sikh, for example, and you said Dakshinakashi, they would understand broadly what you are

02:08:38.200 --> 02:08:39.200
[Guest]: referring to.

02:08:39.200 --> 02:08:40.200
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough.

02:08:40.200 --> 02:08:44.520
[Amit Varma]: The second of my three questions is that maybe there was a sense of a civilizational identity

02:08:44.520 --> 02:08:48.440
[Amit Varma]: which was undefined, nebulous, always changing.

02:08:48.440 --> 02:08:51.500
[Amit Varma]: When did a sense of a national identity come about?

02:08:51.500 --> 02:08:55.080
[Amit Varma]: Because my sense of the princely states, you know, from your writing and those of others

02:08:55.080 --> 02:08:59.040
[Amit Varma]: would be that there is no sense of an India per se as we know it now.

02:08:59.040 --> 02:09:03.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, it's just that I would imagine that a ruler in that time would have his princely

02:09:03.120 --> 02:09:04.120
[Amit Varma]: state.

02:09:04.120 --> 02:09:07.040
[Amit Varma]: And this is a foreign land, including other princely states.

02:09:07.040 --> 02:09:11.720
[Amit Varma]: And then there is this foreign lands, which has suddenly come and the British and that's

02:09:11.720 --> 02:09:12.720
[Amit Varma]: what there is.

02:09:12.720 --> 02:09:19.200
[Amit Varma]: So when does a national identity start taking shape, where princely states can also think

02:09:19.200 --> 02:09:22.960
[Amit Varma]: of the possibility of something called India when they can start using the word national,

02:09:22.960 --> 02:09:23.960
[Guest]: for example?

02:09:23.960 --> 02:09:26.440
[Guest]: I think it's having the British as a common enemy.

02:09:26.440 --> 02:09:29.920
[Guest]: Why is it that the early nationalists who had the toughest task of firstly articulating

02:09:29.920 --> 02:09:34.640
[Guest]: what nationalism is, how do you explain or construct nationalism, them and the princes,

02:09:34.640 --> 02:09:38.440
[Guest]: the reason they were on the same page in the early decades, the first 50 odd years of that

02:09:38.440 --> 02:09:41.200
[Guest]: process was partly because they had a common enemy.

02:09:41.200 --> 02:09:46.200
[Guest]: When you have a common enemy, it becomes easier to define what you have in common as brown

02:09:46.200 --> 02:09:47.200
[Guest]: people.

02:09:47.200 --> 02:09:48.880
[Guest]: And I think that helped a great deal.

02:09:48.880 --> 02:09:52.920
[Guest]: That's why the early Congress also stayed away from touchy areas that would emphasize

02:09:52.920 --> 02:09:53.920
[Guest]: difference.

02:09:53.920 --> 02:09:56.960
[Guest]: They didn't want to get into social reform and anything where people would end up quarrelling

02:09:56.960 --> 02:09:57.960
[Guest]: with each other.

02:09:57.960 --> 02:10:01.840
[Guest]: They just focused strictly on political things they required, for example, the English language,

02:10:01.840 --> 02:10:04.400
[Guest]: because otherwise they would all get lost in each other's languages.

02:10:04.400 --> 02:10:09.200
[Guest]: So they needed people who were brown, spoke English, had gone to the new schools, agreed

02:10:09.200 --> 02:10:14.280
[Guest]: on a core agenda of things to discuss, and together they would then construct nationalism.

02:10:14.280 --> 02:10:17.280
[Guest]: The princes joined the party because they said, great, you know, you're also fighting

02:10:17.280 --> 02:10:18.280
[Guest]: against the British.

02:10:18.280 --> 02:10:21.560
[Guest]: We're also not very happy with the British, so let's sort of come together.

02:10:21.560 --> 02:10:26.180
[Guest]: So nationalism occurs, I would say, you know, there's this, some people would put it down

02:10:26.180 --> 02:10:31.560
[Guest]: to the 1860s, Dadabhai Naoroji, that generation, but frankly already, if I'm not wrong, was

02:10:31.560 --> 02:10:36.760
[Guest]: it the 1840s or the 50s, there's this mysterious, not mysterious, we know the identity now,

02:10:36.760 --> 02:10:38.360
[Guest]: but I don't remember the name now.

02:10:38.360 --> 02:10:42.200
[Guest]: There was this gentleman who was writing letters to the editor of the Bombay Gazette, this

02:10:42.200 --> 02:10:47.100
[Guest]: newspaper in Bombay, and it was fascinating that those, I think it's six or seven letters

02:10:47.100 --> 02:10:52.000
[Guest]: that he wrote, but a very strong critique of colonial rule, economic, political, everything.

02:10:52.000 --> 02:10:57.080
[Guest]: So I would say somewhere by mid-19th century, there was, you know, the initial sort of shoots

02:10:57.080 --> 02:10:58.960
[Guest]: of this were emerging.

02:10:58.960 --> 02:11:02.760
[Guest]: Awareness that the British are bad for India, you know, and the thing is this awareness

02:11:02.760 --> 02:11:07.780
[Guest]: was also linked to a great extent to English education, not because English education suddenly

02:11:07.780 --> 02:11:13.280
[Guest]: enlightened people, but because English education gave us a language and a vocabulary and words

02:11:13.280 --> 02:11:19.020
[Guest]: like democracy, nationalism, which we could use to express ideas that were already there.

02:11:19.020 --> 02:11:20.240
[Guest]: Those feelings were there.

02:11:20.240 --> 02:11:24.000
[Guest]: The English language allowed people to express it in a form that even the colonizer would

02:11:24.000 --> 02:11:28.240
[Guest]: understand and people in Britain would understand, and therefore it could become some kind of

02:11:28.240 --> 02:11:29.240
[Guest]: a movement.

02:11:29.240 --> 02:11:33.120
[Guest]: So the second half of the 19th century really is when people start thinking of India as

02:11:33.120 --> 02:11:38.280
[Guest]: a whole, as one unit, and where people need to come together and manage to achieve something.

02:11:38.280 --> 02:11:39.280
[Guest]: It was not easy.

02:11:39.280 --> 02:11:42.080
[Guest]: The early Congress used to meet once a year, end of the year in December, they would give

02:11:42.080 --> 02:11:45.080
[Guest]: speeches and they would go, and the British would laugh at them saying, you know, they're

02:11:45.080 --> 02:11:48.800
[Guest]: like a suburban debating club, you know, people come, they give long speeches and everybody

02:11:48.800 --> 02:11:49.920
[Guest]: goes home.

02:11:49.920 --> 02:11:54.840
[Guest]: But that itself was the beginning of that process, beginning of saying, no, we are all

02:11:54.840 --> 02:11:55.840
[Guest]: part of one thing.

02:11:55.840 --> 02:11:59.040
[Guest]: We may only meet once a year, but we are part of one political landscape.

02:11:59.040 --> 02:12:02.840
[Guest]: So it's really in the late 19th century that this happens, which is why at that time these

02:12:02.840 --> 02:12:06.320
[Guest]: people were allies with each other and the British were the common enemy.

02:12:06.320 --> 02:12:10.440
[Guest]: Having a common enemy always helps because I think it, even now politicians make this

02:12:10.440 --> 02:12:14.760
[Guest]: huge bogey out of Pakistan because it helps sort of rally people together behind them

02:12:14.760 --> 02:12:19.440
[Guest]: in India and then sort of takes attention away from problems within by focusing on an

02:12:19.440 --> 02:12:20.440
[Guest]: external enemy.

02:12:20.440 --> 02:12:24.680
[Guest]: It's not the perfect analogy, but essentially the same principle is in play.

02:12:24.680 --> 02:12:27.600
[Guest]: You highlight a foreigner and say that at least we all belong here.

02:12:27.600 --> 02:12:32.040
[Guest]: We may not have defined exactly what our places are in this landscape, but we definitely were

02:12:32.040 --> 02:12:33.040
[Guest]: born here.

02:12:33.040 --> 02:12:37.440
[Guest]: Whereas this person has not only come from outside, he also comes from an alien culture

02:12:37.440 --> 02:12:38.920
[Guest]: and is dominating us.

02:12:38.920 --> 02:12:41.840
[Guest]: And we know one thing, we may disagree on everything else, but we know one thing, which

02:12:41.840 --> 02:12:44.080
[Guest]: is that we want to push back that domination.

02:12:44.080 --> 02:12:49.760
[Guest]: So that common cause becomes a medium by which to then think about nationalism, think about

02:12:49.760 --> 02:12:53.920
[Guest]: how you have things in common, think about that civilizational element, think about the

02:12:53.920 --> 02:12:58.000
[Guest]: religious traditions that bind you together, think about and sort of intellectualize the

02:12:58.000 --> 02:12:59.000
[Guest]: argument.

02:12:59.000 --> 02:13:01.120
[Guest]: But I think it begins essentially with having a common enemy.

02:13:01.120 --> 02:13:05.880
[Amit Varma]: And as a German theorist, Carl Schmitt once said that for politics, you always need an

02:13:05.880 --> 02:13:06.880
[Amit Varma]: other.

02:13:06.880 --> 02:13:08.360
[Amit Varma]: So I guess this is a convenient other.

02:13:08.360 --> 02:13:11.560
[Amit Varma]: Now you speak of that one nation actually coming together and when it actually does

02:13:11.560 --> 02:13:16.440
[Amit Varma]: come together after 47, after the British leave, it comes together in a lot of violence.

02:13:16.440 --> 02:13:21.280
[Amit Varma]: Like I did an episode with Narayanini Basu on her excellent book on VP Menon.

02:13:21.280 --> 02:13:25.480
[Amit Varma]: And the thing that strikes me is that what Sardar Patel and VP Menon do for what we would

02:13:25.480 --> 02:13:29.960
[Amit Varma]: consider a good cause today, because it's all over and we are beneficiaries, is an act

02:13:29.960 --> 02:13:34.520
[Amit Varma]: of colonialism that is actually harsher and more brutal than the original British act

02:13:34.520 --> 02:13:38.160
[Amit Varma]: of colonialism, because they take over control of the princely state.

02:13:38.160 --> 02:13:42.800
[Amit Varma]: So they derive their influence in the princely states over a long period of time, whereas

02:13:42.800 --> 02:13:48.560
[Amit Varma]: what Patel and Menon do is over a short period of time with a lot of violence, like some,

02:13:48.560 --> 02:13:52.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, you've written about how between 27,000 to 40,000 people died in Hyderabad

02:13:52.640 --> 02:13:53.640
[Guest]: while that was happening.

02:13:53.640 --> 02:13:57.760
[Guest]: Yeah, that so-called police operation actually, I mean, your police operation involved bombs

02:13:57.760 --> 02:13:58.760
[Guest]: from aircraft.

02:13:58.760 --> 02:13:59.760
[Guest]: I'm sorry, it was not a police operation.

02:13:59.760 --> 02:14:00.760
[Unknown]: It was an invasion.

02:14:00.760 --> 02:14:01.760
[Unknown]: It was a conquest.

02:14:01.760 --> 02:14:05.520
[Guest]: It was a military takeover of the state, which I'm not saying is good or bad, but we should

02:14:05.520 --> 02:14:06.600
[Guest]: call it what it was.

02:14:06.600 --> 02:14:10.160
[Guest]: Police operation even then was used to play down what exactly it was.

02:14:10.160 --> 02:14:13.760
[Amit Varma]: And subsequent broken promises in terms of what, you know, you promise them something,

02:14:13.760 --> 02:14:16.480
[Amit Varma]: they sign up on that basis, and then you kind of break that.

02:14:16.480 --> 02:14:21.120
[Amit Varma]: So is that something that we should also consider, like when we think of colonialism, we think

02:14:21.120 --> 02:14:25.160
[Amit Varma]: of the colonialism of the British, and that's a great evil in the subcontinent.

02:14:25.160 --> 02:14:28.480
[Amit Varma]: But what happened in 47 to get the princely states in?

02:14:28.480 --> 02:14:33.320
[Amit Varma]: And I am of course glad it happened now that it's over, because I'm glad to be here in,

02:14:33.320 --> 02:14:37.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, in an independent India where we can travel freely, I can go to Rameshwaram

02:14:37.080 --> 02:14:42.760
[Amit Varma]: or Patiala anytime I feel like, but the manner in which it happened is something that I find

02:14:42.760 --> 02:14:47.140
[Amit Varma]: it hard to look at and say that no, that was as evil as colonialism.

02:14:47.140 --> 02:14:48.140
[Guest]: What are your thoughts on that?

02:14:48.140 --> 02:14:53.160
[Guest]: The thing is, the Maharajas in some way lost sympathy in that final decade before independence.

02:14:53.160 --> 02:14:56.440
[Guest]: Till the mid 30s, they were relatively strong.

02:14:56.440 --> 02:14:59.960
[Guest]: Nobody could envision an India without them, only perhaps a few socialists in the Congress,

02:14:59.960 --> 02:15:02.120
[Guest]: but generally, Gandhi was circumspect.

02:15:02.120 --> 02:15:05.480
[Guest]: Patiala, you know, the same Patiala who got them to integrate their states with the Indian

02:15:05.480 --> 02:15:10.040
[Guest]: Union in 1929 or so in a speech in Mysore, you know, some of the local politicians complained

02:15:10.040 --> 02:15:13.640
[Guest]: about the Mysore government, and Sardar Patiala basically said, this is a great government,

02:15:13.640 --> 02:15:17.200
[Guest]: if there's Maharajas, wonderful, if you've got issues with them, the people of Mysore

02:15:17.200 --> 02:15:20.760
[Guest]: have a problem, not the ruler, it's your problem, not the ruler's fault, you must have some

02:15:20.760 --> 02:15:24.400
[Guest]: issue with you, he's telling the people, the local congressmen in Mysore.

02:15:24.400 --> 02:15:27.920
[Guest]: The same Patiala gets them to eventually give up their rights in the states.

02:15:27.920 --> 02:15:31.200
[Guest]: Several things of course are at play, one, from their perspective, from the perspective

02:15:31.200 --> 02:15:35.360
[Guest]: of the Congress, partitions happened, India can't be allowed to secede, you can't have

02:15:35.360 --> 02:15:39.360
[Guest]: these semi-autonomous units in the state, Nehru has an allergy when it comes to these

02:15:39.360 --> 02:15:41.920
[Guest]: hereditary rulers, and each of them has their reasons.

02:15:41.920 --> 02:15:46.600
[Guest]: So there is an incentive in trying to sort of get a strong state together, for which

02:15:46.600 --> 02:15:50.200
[Guest]: all of these little barriers in these states, these islands cannot be allowed.

02:15:50.200 --> 02:15:55.680
[Guest]: For the same reason, it's also a sort of implicit recognition that just as the British found

02:15:55.680 --> 02:16:00.680
[Guest]: that a princely territory could be used to harbour anti-British dacoits, to harbour seditionists,

02:16:00.680 --> 02:16:06.400
[Guest]: to support revolutionaries, I mean it could also easily become a footing for anti-India

02:16:06.400 --> 02:16:10.320
[Guest]: forces for example, to use these princely states against the new Congress government

02:16:10.320 --> 02:16:14.200
[Guest]: or whatever, or the British to continue to manipulate Indian politics.

02:16:14.200 --> 02:16:18.360
[Guest]: They might find ways to sort of control the rajas and thus destabilise India or try to

02:16:18.360 --> 02:16:19.800
[Guest]: retain control in India.

02:16:19.800 --> 02:16:23.480
[Guest]: The British certainly had a brief moment of flirtation with Travancore because Travancore

02:16:23.480 --> 02:16:28.800
[Guest]: had thorium, which they were very interested in, so they were like, should we try and perhaps

02:16:28.800 --> 02:16:30.800
[Guest]: give Travancore special treatment?

02:16:30.800 --> 02:16:35.880
[Guest]: But there were lots of fears, 1947 is a time of great chaos, nobody is really sure about

02:16:35.880 --> 02:16:39.760
[Guest]: where all these pieces are going to land, so you really are going in and you have to

02:16:39.760 --> 02:16:42.280
[Guest]: do your best, it's almost on a war footing.

02:16:42.280 --> 02:16:46.320
[Guest]: But what really causes the maharajas trouble is the fact that they were increasingly losing

02:16:46.320 --> 02:16:48.480
[Guest]: sympathy from their own subjects.

02:16:48.480 --> 02:16:53.400
[Guest]: Even the best of them, in states like Mysore, Travancore etc, maharajas lost sympathy ultimately

02:16:53.400 --> 02:16:55.280
[Guest]: because of their own success.

02:16:55.280 --> 02:16:58.880
[Guest]: On the one hand you build schools etc, but you're stuck in a colonial framework which

02:16:58.880 --> 02:17:02.840
[Guest]: puts certain limitations on how many jobs you can give etc etc.

02:17:02.840 --> 02:17:07.320
[Guest]: People start getting political, you're on the one hand equipping them to think of democracy

02:17:07.320 --> 02:17:11.160
[Guest]: and modern rights and speak that democratic language, but you're a hereditary ruler.

02:17:11.160 --> 02:17:15.360
[Guest]: So there's already a slight sort of disjointedness over there.

02:17:15.360 --> 02:17:19.800
[Guest]: By the 1930s and 40s, it's becoming very clear that the British are slowly going to have

02:17:19.800 --> 02:17:20.800
[Guest]: to leave.

02:17:20.800 --> 02:17:24.380
[Guest]: The maharajas are now lost because they're like, which way should we sway?

02:17:24.380 --> 02:17:25.560
[Guest]: And they fail to unite.

02:17:25.560 --> 02:17:28.720
[Guest]: This is where their quirks come in, in the sense that Hyderabad is too grand to sit with

02:17:28.720 --> 02:17:31.320
[Guest]: say a Patiala, which it sees as a minor state.

02:17:31.320 --> 02:17:35.720
[Guest]: Travancore will not sit with a Jaipur for example because it thinks its status is higher.

02:17:35.720 --> 02:17:38.400
[Guest]: The maharajas do not come together and lobby as a group.

02:17:38.400 --> 02:17:41.400
[Guest]: And efforts to get them to lobby as a group fail.

02:17:41.400 --> 02:17:44.960
[Guest]: From their perspective too, they are legitimate rulers of these states, they are still stuck

02:17:44.960 --> 02:17:47.840
[Guest]: in a place where they do not see India as a nation state.

02:17:47.840 --> 02:17:48.840
[Guest]: So C.P.

02:17:48.840 --> 02:17:52.480
[Guest]: Ramaswamy, Iyer of Travancore-Diwan goes to Lord Mountbatten and says, this is not going

02:17:52.480 --> 02:17:55.880
[Guest]: to last and tells the Maharaja of Travancore, within six months of the British departure

02:17:55.880 --> 02:17:59.680
[Guest]: there is going to be civil war in India and after the massacre of the Congress leaders,

02:17:59.680 --> 02:18:02.840
[Guest]: you have to decide how you want to behave and what your future will be.

02:18:02.840 --> 02:18:06.100
[Guest]: He was convinced there was going to be a massacre of Congress leaders because this was not going

02:18:06.100 --> 02:18:07.100
[Guest]: to happen.

02:18:07.100 --> 02:18:08.960
[Guest]: The Indian state would not survive.

02:18:08.960 --> 02:18:14.340
[Guest]: So many of them were really genuinely caught up in the idea that there could not be some

02:18:14.340 --> 02:18:18.640
[Guest]: kind of unified Indian nation and because they saw themselves as legitimate, why should

02:18:18.640 --> 02:18:22.560
[Guest]: they sort of give up their powers and sacrifice something for a larger, better together or

02:18:22.560 --> 02:18:23.560
[Guest]: even lobby together.

02:18:23.560 --> 02:18:28.860
[Guest]: Why should I sit with another Maharaja when in my own right I have that capacity, etc.

02:18:28.860 --> 02:18:29.860
[Guest]: So that's one thing.

02:18:29.860 --> 02:18:30.860
[Guest]: The other thing is repression.

02:18:30.860 --> 02:18:35.980
[Guest]: And this is interesting because we assume that all Indians when they stood up and fought

02:18:35.980 --> 02:18:37.840
[Guest]: it was anti-colonial, which is not true.

02:18:37.840 --> 02:18:42.960
[Guest]: As I said, in Travancore, Mysore, in Baroda it was anti-Gujarati-Marathi.

02:18:42.960 --> 02:18:47.220
[Guest]: In Travancore, it was Nayas versus Irawas versus Syrian Christians.

02:18:47.220 --> 02:18:49.400
[Guest]: These were internal politics.

02:18:49.400 --> 02:18:53.960
[Guest]: In the 30s, whether you look at Baroda, Mysore, Travancore, any of the big states, there was

02:18:53.960 --> 02:18:57.480
[Guest]: an overlap between nationalism and this internal politics.

02:18:57.480 --> 02:19:02.800
[Guest]: What happened is the local politicians realized having links with the Congress allowed them

02:19:02.800 --> 02:19:07.020
[Guest]: to punch above their weight because the Rajas were sensitive to Congress criticism.

02:19:07.020 --> 02:19:11.040
[Guest]: So having a Congress tag was a good way to negotiate with the Raja.

02:19:11.040 --> 02:19:15.000
[Guest]: The Congress, especially for example, the local Congress stood for election in Mysore

02:19:15.000 --> 02:19:16.000
[Guest]: and they lost.

02:19:16.000 --> 02:19:19.320
[Guest]: There was no interest in the Congress's message at that time.

02:19:19.320 --> 02:19:23.240
[Guest]: So they realized they need local allies to create a footprint in the states.

02:19:23.240 --> 02:19:25.880
[Guest]: So there was a sort of politics of convenience there.

02:19:25.880 --> 02:19:31.360
[Guest]: There was a convenient marriage between local politicians and the Congress party.

02:19:31.360 --> 02:19:35.300
[Guest]: Local politicians said, let's forget our factionalism and our communalism for now.

02:19:35.300 --> 02:19:38.680
[Guest]: Get together under the Congress party and negotiate with the Maharaja for better rights,

02:19:38.680 --> 02:19:41.240
[Guest]: for more democratic representation.

02:19:41.240 --> 02:19:45.440
[Guest]: So Maharajas were suddenly in a position where outside British India, their overlords whom

02:19:45.440 --> 02:19:48.840
[Guest]: they could otherwise manipulate or play some game with, they're being pushed out.

02:19:48.840 --> 02:19:50.440
[Guest]: Congress is rising to power.

02:19:50.440 --> 02:19:54.560
[Guest]: Local politicians who they so far have been playing are now actually using the Congress's

02:19:54.560 --> 02:19:56.400
[Guest]: language and becoming anti-Maharaja.

02:19:56.400 --> 02:19:59.880
[Guest]: Till yesterday, the Maharajas are being celebrated by the Congress.

02:19:59.880 --> 02:20:01.800
[Guest]: Now however, they've become the villains.

02:20:01.800 --> 02:20:05.880
[Guest]: And instinctively, almost all of them, whether it's in Mysore, whether it's in Travancore,

02:20:05.880 --> 02:20:10.720
[Guest]: they start having very, very repressive strategies in play, physically sort of attacking people,

02:20:10.720 --> 02:20:11.720
[Guest]: guns being fired.

02:20:11.720 --> 02:20:16.320
[Guest]: In Viduraswatha, in Mysore, there is what is called the Southern Jallianwala Bagh.

02:20:16.320 --> 02:20:20.900
[Guest]: In Travancore, Punnapravaila, after 1810, for the first time in the state, troops being

02:20:20.900 --> 02:20:24.500
[Guest]: brought out to attack its own people, bloodshed in the streets.

02:20:24.500 --> 02:20:28.000
[Guest]: That kind of thing starts happening in the states and the Maharajas lose sympathy.

02:20:28.000 --> 02:20:32.840
[Guest]: And finally, with World War II coming in, the complete global landscape changes.

02:20:32.840 --> 02:20:34.240
[Guest]: Now the Maharajas are really small fry.

02:20:34.240 --> 02:20:37.600
[Guest]: The British really want to leave and they want to leave relatively quickly.

02:20:37.600 --> 02:20:40.800
[Guest]: The Maharajas become an inconvenience in certain ways.

02:20:40.800 --> 02:20:41.800
[Guest]: It makes sense.

02:20:41.800 --> 02:20:42.800
[Guest]: Logically speaking, it makes sense.

02:20:42.800 --> 02:20:45.520
[Guest]: The British are going to hand over power to the Congress government.

02:20:45.520 --> 02:20:47.240
[Guest]: They're not really going to look after the Rajas.

02:20:47.240 --> 02:20:51.320
[Guest]: The best they can do is claim that the Rajas are now freed from all obligations to the

02:20:51.320 --> 02:20:52.320
[Guest]: British.

02:20:52.320 --> 02:20:55.080
[Guest]: They have to negotiate independent treaties with the Indian government.

02:20:55.080 --> 02:20:57.840
[Guest]: But you know, the Rajas, ultimately their armies aren't that strong.

02:20:57.840 --> 02:21:02.480
[Guest]: They can't withstand the Indian army and the kind of resources the Congress party is going

02:21:02.480 --> 02:21:03.740
[Guest]: to inherit.

02:21:03.740 --> 02:21:06.640
[Guest]: And using that, Sardar Patel goes with carrot and stick both.

02:21:06.640 --> 02:21:08.580
[Guest]: Where the stick is needed, he uses it.

02:21:08.580 --> 02:21:11.200
[Guest]: In most cases, the carrot works.

02:21:11.200 --> 02:21:12.360
[Guest]: Negotiations are held.

02:21:12.360 --> 02:21:14.560
[Guest]: People think in 1947, the Rajas stopped ruling.

02:21:14.560 --> 02:21:15.560
[Guest]: Not true.

02:21:15.560 --> 02:21:16.560
[Guest]: Rajas ruled till 1949.

02:21:16.560 --> 02:21:21.640
[Guest]: It was only when the integration took place in 1949 that they finally took a political

02:21:21.640 --> 02:21:22.640
[Guest]: backseat.

02:21:22.640 --> 02:21:24.320
[Guest]: They became these figurehead rulers.

02:21:24.320 --> 02:21:28.200
[Guest]: They were given their privy purses and that was it.

02:21:28.200 --> 02:21:32.320
[Guest]: Now here again, people assume, oh, you know, poor country, why should we pay these people

02:21:32.320 --> 02:21:33.320
[Guest]: so much money, etc.

02:21:33.320 --> 02:21:38.600
[Guest]: But the frank truth is they actually gave up legitimate political power they had.

02:21:38.600 --> 02:21:41.520
[Guest]: Territories, Travancore had a revenue of 9 crores, which was one of India's richest provinces

02:21:41.520 --> 02:21:42.520
[Guest]: at that time.

02:21:42.520 --> 02:21:45.560
[Guest]: 9 crores doesn't sound like a lot today, but in those days, it was a heap of money for

02:21:45.560 --> 02:21:48.320
[Guest]: such a small state of 8000 square miles.

02:21:48.320 --> 02:21:51.600
[Guest]: One of the reasons the Maharaja was hesitant to merge with the Indian Union was because

02:21:51.600 --> 02:21:55.840
[Guest]: Malabar, which was the part of Kerala that was under British control, was far more backward.

02:21:55.840 --> 02:21:59.480
[Guest]: And he said, what will happen is you'll form some kind of a state between all three Malayalam

02:21:59.480 --> 02:22:04.560
[Guest]: speaking elements and my richer subjects will end up subsidizing this place in North Kerala,

02:22:04.560 --> 02:22:05.560
[Guest]: which is backward.

02:22:05.560 --> 02:22:06.560
[Guest]: And what about our progress?

02:22:06.560 --> 02:22:11.040
[Guest]: We've come so far, we will end up going backwards if we merge with other parts of Kerala, which

02:22:11.040 --> 02:22:13.800
[Guest]: are, you know, which are going to pull us down or drag us down.

02:22:13.800 --> 02:22:17.600
[Guest]: They had some logical economic considerations and fears as well.

02:22:17.600 --> 02:22:21.080
[Guest]: But you know, the larger current of history was in a certain direction.

02:22:21.080 --> 02:22:23.400
[Guest]: The British abandoned the Maharajas finally.

02:22:23.400 --> 02:22:27.320
[Guest]: And the Maharajas had fallen out with the Congress in those final 15 odd years.

02:22:27.320 --> 02:22:30.040
[Guest]: Even Gandhiji, who otherwise respected the Rajas, had turned around.

02:22:30.040 --> 02:22:35.280
[Guest]: By 1940, even he was a bit anti-Maharaja after several events.

02:22:35.280 --> 02:22:39.680
[Guest]: So you know, they became the casualties of that larger shift in history.

02:22:39.680 --> 02:22:40.680
[Guest]: And perhaps rightly so.

02:22:40.680 --> 02:22:45.360
[Guest]: You know, the Rajputana chapter in the book, which is chapter 7, that talks about how several

02:22:45.360 --> 02:22:47.820
[Guest]: states would have faced trouble anyway.

02:22:47.820 --> 02:22:50.460
[Guest]: Because in Rajputana, it was not really Congress or nationalists.

02:22:50.460 --> 02:22:55.400
[Guest]: It was tribal unrest because the local Rajput system of governance had already started failing.

02:22:55.400 --> 02:22:56.400
[Guest]: The world had changed.

02:22:56.400 --> 02:22:59.400
[Guest]: So, you know, your feudal levies in Rajputana was pretty feudal.

02:22:59.400 --> 02:23:04.680
[Guest]: It was not a place that progressed very far, unlike the southern states, for example.

02:23:04.680 --> 02:23:07.320
[Guest]: So tribal unrest is there, peasant unrest is there.

02:23:07.320 --> 02:23:12.520
[Guest]: It was going, in the mid 1910s and 20s, people really thought Rajputana would go Bolshevik

02:23:12.520 --> 02:23:15.960
[Guest]: because it was getting to a stage that was pretty bad.

02:23:15.960 --> 02:23:18.400
[Guest]: And perhaps that way the Rajas would have been toppled.

02:23:18.400 --> 02:23:24.000
[Guest]: So the Rajas, they adapted to colonialism, but by doing so, they also limited their shelf

02:23:24.000 --> 02:23:25.000
[Guest]: life.

02:23:25.000 --> 02:23:27.040
[Guest]: So they became part of that structure to survive.

02:23:27.040 --> 02:23:31.200
[Guest]: They adapted in certain ways so that when the structure collapsed, they were left flailing

02:23:31.200 --> 02:23:36.680
[Guest]: with no place in a future India, which, you know, was perhaps how it would inevitably

02:23:36.680 --> 02:23:38.840
[Guest]: be in the end.

02:23:38.840 --> 02:23:44.080
[Guest]: All the book argues is that the argument that they did nothing till then is not true.

02:23:44.080 --> 02:23:45.720
[Guest]: Many of them did great things, in fact.

02:23:45.720 --> 02:23:49.360
[Guest]: Many of them contributed to the process of what we would today call a nation building

02:23:49.360 --> 02:23:53.360
[Guest]: or part of India's national story and narrative.

02:23:53.360 --> 02:23:56.240
[Guest]: All of that is, it's important that we acknowledge that.

02:23:56.240 --> 02:23:58.640
[Guest]: Just to understand modern Indian history better.

02:23:58.640 --> 02:24:02.600
[Guest]: But indeed in the final stage, they in many ways let themselves down.

02:24:02.600 --> 02:24:06.000
[Guest]: Of course, their final obituary by Indira Gandhi was perhaps a bit unfair.

02:24:06.000 --> 02:24:09.160
[Guest]: Her argument was, we are paying these people lots of money, it was actually not that much

02:24:09.160 --> 02:24:10.160
[Guest]: money.

02:24:10.160 --> 02:24:14.680
[Guest]: You know, very few Rajas had grand, as I said, of the 562, most got really trivial sums.

02:24:14.680 --> 02:24:16.000
[Guest]: Very few had large sums.

02:24:16.000 --> 02:24:20.480
[Guest]: And in most states, it was agreed that with each generation, the amount would be reduced,

02:24:20.480 --> 02:24:24.400
[Guest]: reduced further, till finally it was just a nominal kind of figure.

02:24:24.400 --> 02:24:28.840
[Guest]: The reason Indira Gandhi finally, you know, sort of ended the Privy Purses is simply because

02:24:28.840 --> 02:24:31.160
[Guest]: the Maharajas were not happy with her socialist turn.

02:24:31.160 --> 02:24:33.200
[Guest]: They were funding opposition parties.

02:24:33.200 --> 02:24:36.680
[Guest]: The Rajmata Vijayanagar was a key funder of the Janasang, for example.

02:24:36.680 --> 02:24:39.960
[Guest]: The Swatantra Party used to get funding from the Maharajas.

02:24:39.960 --> 02:24:43.480
[Guest]: She basically wanted a little bit like today's government, you know, doesn't allow other

02:24:43.480 --> 02:24:46.400
[Guest]: parties to get funding from industrial houses.

02:24:46.400 --> 02:24:47.400
[Guest]: Same logic.

02:24:47.400 --> 02:24:49.160
[Guest]: If you pay them, I will come and attack you.

02:24:49.160 --> 02:24:52.600
[Guest]: Since the Maharajas are paying them, you're essentially taking government of India money.

02:24:52.600 --> 02:24:55.640
[Guest]: Indira Gandhi sees herself as the government of India, and you're using it to attack the

02:24:55.640 --> 02:24:56.640
[Guest]: government of India.

02:24:56.640 --> 02:24:57.640
[Guest]: I'm not going to allow it.

02:24:57.640 --> 02:24:59.480
[Guest]: She puts an end to the Privy Purses.

02:24:59.480 --> 02:25:03.080
[Guest]: Of course, she gives it socialist justification and all that, but it wasn't such a big deal.

02:25:03.080 --> 02:25:04.440
[Guest]: It wasn't such a big amount.

02:25:04.440 --> 02:25:06.400
[Guest]: It was not a big drain on the Indian exchequer.

02:25:06.400 --> 02:25:11.560
[Guest]: It was simply, I think, for political reasons, that that promise was broken.

02:25:11.560 --> 02:25:13.000
[Guest]: And you know, that was that.

02:25:13.000 --> 02:25:17.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's unfortunate how much Narendra Modi has learned from Indira Gandhi, though one

02:25:17.480 --> 02:25:21.120
[Amit Varma]: could argue they're both creatures of their perverse incentives.

02:25:21.120 --> 02:25:25.080
[Amit Varma]: And I was amused by the phrase that you just used that Nehru was allergic to hereditary

02:25:25.080 --> 02:25:26.080
[Amit Varma]: rulers.

02:25:26.080 --> 02:25:28.920
[Amit Varma]: I wonder how he would have kind of felt today.

02:25:28.920 --> 02:25:34.160
[Amit Varma]: So you mentioned the possibility that was held out by many that the Indian state would

02:25:34.160 --> 02:25:36.680
[Amit Varma]: not hold, the center would not hold, it would collapse.

02:25:36.680 --> 02:25:40.000
[Amit Varma]: You pointed out the prediction that the Congress leaders would be slaughtered.

02:25:40.000 --> 02:25:42.160
[Amit Varma]: Now the thing is, history happened.

02:25:42.160 --> 02:25:43.440
[Amit Varma]: And we know that none of that happened.

02:25:43.440 --> 02:25:47.680
[Amit Varma]: The center held, the Congress leaders were not slaughtered, and we are here today.

02:25:47.680 --> 02:25:52.800
[Amit Varma]: But you know, history always makes seem everything that has already happened inevitable, like

02:25:52.800 --> 02:25:54.720
[Amit Varma]: it's 100% going to happen this way.

02:25:54.720 --> 02:25:57.560
[Amit Varma]: But there was a nonzero chance that the center would not hold.

02:25:57.560 --> 02:25:59.800
[Amit Varma]: There was a nonzero chance that it would all fall apart.

02:25:59.800 --> 02:26:05.520
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it's precisely because of that, that our constitution was designed to be so centralizing

02:26:05.520 --> 02:26:11.200
[Amit Varma]: that we kept so much of the oppressive colonial apparatus because we needed it for stability

02:26:11.200 --> 02:26:13.300
[Amit Varma]: and for circumstances like that.

02:26:13.300 --> 02:26:17.560
[Amit Varma]: So even though your book isn't about that and doesn't touch on that, but you are a historian

02:26:17.560 --> 02:26:21.880
[Amit Varma]: and you've read a lot, how big would you say that nonzero chance really was?

02:26:21.880 --> 02:26:26.680
[Guest]: I mean, again, this is, you know, it's speculative to say what might have happened.

02:26:26.680 --> 02:26:30.880
[Guest]: But I think because we made a wise choice to retain, for example, the administrative

02:26:30.880 --> 02:26:34.840
[Guest]: services, that administrative apparatus, the same officials who are serving the British

02:26:34.840 --> 02:26:38.880
[Guest]: government of India, one fine morning woke up and started serving the Nehruvian government

02:26:38.880 --> 02:26:39.880
[Guest]: of India.

02:26:39.880 --> 02:26:42.120
[Guest]: There was no ego clash there.

02:26:42.120 --> 02:26:46.040
[Guest]: You know, it's not like, oh, you supported previous people, therefore I won't play with

02:26:46.040 --> 02:26:47.040
[Guest]: you.

02:26:47.040 --> 02:26:48.360
[Guest]: Sardar Patel, for example, had an important role.

02:26:48.360 --> 02:26:50.480
[Guest]: I don't think Nehru liked VP Menon a lot.

02:26:50.480 --> 02:26:54.000
[Guest]: But Sardar Patel had no issues with the fact that VP Menon came out of the British bureaucracy

02:26:54.000 --> 02:26:58.280
[Guest]: and had served the British state for so long because he was able to arrange for a smooth

02:26:58.280 --> 02:27:03.720
[Guest]: transition and make sure that although the people in power at the top have changed, overall

02:27:03.720 --> 02:27:07.600
[Guest]: the structure remains more or less the same because otherwise if you sort of tamper with

02:27:07.600 --> 02:27:10.200
[Guest]: everything all at once, the whole thing will fall apart.

02:27:10.200 --> 02:27:14.120
[Guest]: So holding it together required sort of, you know, as you said, holding on to colonial

02:27:14.120 --> 02:27:17.040
[Guest]: rules, etc., colonial laws and the apparatus.

02:27:17.040 --> 02:27:20.040
[Guest]: I think that's the only reason we didn't sort of break apart.

02:27:20.040 --> 02:27:24.360
[Guest]: I think that was a wise decision, whether it was taken consciously or subconsciously,

02:27:24.360 --> 02:27:28.320
[Guest]: because you weren't sort of lighting too many fires all at once.

02:27:28.320 --> 02:27:30.400
[Guest]: You didn't have to firefight all at once either.

02:27:30.400 --> 02:27:35.000
[Guest]: You were able to go one after the other because overall there was a degree of stability.

02:27:35.000 --> 02:27:38.220
[Guest]: Then the other big thing is one big issue was, of course, partition.

02:27:38.220 --> 02:27:41.640
[Guest]: So there was a lot of energy and attention sort of diverted into that, but the rest of

02:27:41.640 --> 02:27:45.000
[Guest]: the country, to great measure, was stable.

02:27:45.000 --> 02:27:48.360
[Guest]: Just because the British left, it was not as though everything collapsed and people

02:27:48.360 --> 02:27:50.320
[Guest]: started fighting with each other and all of that.

02:27:50.320 --> 02:27:52.040
[Guest]: It was all controlled very quickly.

02:27:52.040 --> 02:27:55.000
[Guest]: The Indian Army, you know, it was an army that fought in the name of the British King

02:27:55.000 --> 02:27:57.000
[Guest]: in World War II, but we retained it.

02:27:57.000 --> 02:28:01.800
[Guest]: We retained the same officers, the same leadership, and we were able to sort of do that without

02:28:01.800 --> 02:28:06.800
[Guest]: getting personal, without letting egos get in the way, which unfortunately is not true

02:28:06.800 --> 02:28:07.800
[Guest]: today anymore.

02:28:07.800 --> 02:28:10.680
[Guest]: If you have served a previous government, then you can be sacked by the next government.

02:28:10.680 --> 02:28:15.280
[Guest]: It's a very dangerous game because the whole point of having a bureaucracy that is not

02:28:15.280 --> 02:28:19.920
[Guest]: part of that political sort of shifting of sands is precisely for stability, whereas

02:28:19.920 --> 02:28:24.440
[Guest]: if bureaucracy also becomes political very quickly, then everything is political.

02:28:24.440 --> 02:28:25.960
[Guest]: Everything then can start shifting.

02:28:25.960 --> 02:28:26.960
[Guest]: That's a bit dangerous.

02:28:26.960 --> 02:28:32.320
[Guest]: In 1947, we didn't make that mistake as much, but that mistake can be made in the future

02:28:32.320 --> 02:28:33.320
[Guest]: also.

02:28:33.320 --> 02:28:36.960
[Guest]: And then we'll perhaps have an answer to your question as to where it will take us.

02:28:36.960 --> 02:28:42.800
[Guest]: In 1947, we missed that terrible possibility, but, you know, you can never take it for granted

02:28:42.800 --> 02:28:47.120
[Guest]: in India that, you know, now this is set and now the landscape will never change.

02:28:47.120 --> 02:28:49.200
[Guest]: I don't think you can say that with any guarantee.

02:28:49.200 --> 02:28:54.160
[Guest]: It depends entirely on who's in control and how much they're willing to play by the rules

02:28:54.160 --> 02:28:57.640
[Guest]: of the game, because everything ultimately boils down to the rules of the game.

02:28:57.640 --> 02:28:59.400
[Amit Varma]: Rules are what hold it together.

02:28:59.400 --> 02:29:02.640
[Amit Varma]: Speaking of an independent bureaucracy, I had an episode a couple of weeks back with

02:29:02.640 --> 02:29:07.080
[Amit Varma]: Josie Joseph, and one of the big themes that comes out from his book is that the reason

02:29:07.080 --> 02:29:12.280
[Amit Varma]: India's security state is such a menace to our citizens, but the way it has been designed

02:29:12.280 --> 02:29:14.280
[Amit Varma]: is that it is under political control.

02:29:14.280 --> 02:29:19.640
[Amit Varma]: So everyone who, you know, comes to power is going to use it to oppress his enemies,

02:29:19.640 --> 02:29:20.640
[Amit Varma]: you know.

02:29:20.640 --> 02:29:24.440
[Amit Varma]: And it's kind of one of the ironic things that I think, like Modi was an RSS pracharak

02:29:24.440 --> 02:29:26.880
[Amit Varma]: in the mid 70s when emergency happened.

02:29:26.880 --> 02:29:31.200
[Amit Varma]: You know, there is this famous story about him going to the railway station in Ahmedabad

02:29:31.200 --> 02:29:35.320
[Amit Varma]: to meet either George Fernandes or Subramanian Swamy, whatever dressed as a Sardar.

02:29:35.320 --> 02:29:39.160
[Amit Varma]: George Fernandes, I think it was in receiving him and taking him to a guest house and all.

02:29:39.160 --> 02:29:42.400
[Amit Varma]: And you would imagine that the lesson which Modi and Jaitley and all of those people who

02:29:42.400 --> 02:29:46.000
[Amit Varma]: were jailed would take from that is that we should not be this oppressive, that we should

02:29:46.000 --> 02:29:47.800
[Amit Varma]: make the state less oppressive.

02:29:47.800 --> 02:29:52.280
[Amit Varma]: But the lesson they seem to have taken instead is that when we come to power, we will be

02:29:52.280 --> 02:29:55.000
[Amit Varma]: in charge of this state and we will use it as we want.

02:29:55.000 --> 02:29:56.000
[Guest]: That is usually the case.

02:29:56.000 --> 02:29:58.640
[Guest]: I mean, ultimately, it all boils down to power, right?

02:29:58.640 --> 02:29:59.880
[Guest]: You know, I have power now.

02:29:59.880 --> 02:30:00.880
[Guest]: So why should I give up?

02:30:00.880 --> 02:30:01.880
[Guest]: Why will I?

02:30:01.880 --> 02:30:02.880
[Guest]: I've worked very hard to gain power.

02:30:02.880 --> 02:30:07.080
[Guest]: Now, why will I sit and dilute the things that, you know, that matter for power?

02:30:07.080 --> 02:30:08.080
[Unknown]: Exactly.

02:30:08.080 --> 02:30:12.440
[Guest]: I'm happy being, you know, just as oppressive, except that it really is a question of who's

02:30:12.440 --> 02:30:13.440
[Guest]: in power.

02:30:13.440 --> 02:30:14.440
[Amit Varma]: That's all.

02:30:14.440 --> 02:30:17.240
[Amit Varma]: And again, it struck me in the context of why we didn't break up in 47.

02:30:17.240 --> 02:30:21.640
[Amit Varma]: And here's a question of how big a role does inertia play in history?

02:30:21.640 --> 02:30:26.440
[Amit Varma]: Like looking through history, one would imagine that every moment in some way or the other

02:30:26.440 --> 02:30:31.320
[Amit Varma]: because of the conflicts or the turmoil or the injustices that are happening, every moment

02:30:31.320 --> 02:30:33.120
[Amit Varma]: holds a seat for evolution.

02:30:33.120 --> 02:30:36.320
[Amit Varma]: But what you have instead, most of the time is a slow evolution.

02:30:36.320 --> 02:30:41.320
[Amit Varma]: So looking at the currents of history in the time that you have, how big a role does inertia

02:30:41.320 --> 02:30:42.320
[Amit Varma]: play?

02:30:42.320 --> 02:30:46.040
[Amit Varma]: How much of history is shaped not by what people do, but by what they don't do?

02:30:46.040 --> 02:30:47.040
[Guest]: Good deal.

02:30:47.040 --> 02:30:48.720
[Guest]: I think 1857 is a good example.

02:30:48.720 --> 02:30:52.760
[Guest]: As I said, a lot of the Rajas actually supported the British because they saw advantage in

02:30:52.760 --> 02:30:54.560
[Guest]: supporting the British at that time.

02:30:54.560 --> 02:30:58.480
[Guest]: You could easily say that if they decided to jump on the revolutionary bandwagon or

02:30:58.480 --> 02:31:01.920
[Guest]: the rebellion or joined it, the British would have been kicked out.

02:31:01.920 --> 02:31:05.960
[Guest]: Punjab Maharajas who were enabling supplies to the Delhi army, for example, if the Maharajas

02:31:05.960 --> 02:31:08.920
[Guest]: had cut off supplies, the Delhi army would have struggled.

02:31:08.920 --> 02:31:09.920
[Guest]: So it's a bit complicated.

02:31:09.920 --> 02:31:13.000
[Guest]: I don't know if inertia is the word I would choose.

02:31:13.000 --> 02:31:16.240
[Guest]: They all had their incentives to behave the way they did at that time.

02:31:16.240 --> 02:31:19.720
[Guest]: It was not like they lay back and said, oh, let me just watch what is happening.

02:31:19.720 --> 02:31:25.360
[Guest]: No, they actively made certain choices, which in hindsight may look like the bad choice,

02:31:25.360 --> 02:31:26.560
[Guest]: look like inertia or whatever.

02:31:26.560 --> 02:31:29.280
[Guest]: But at that time to them, it made sense.

02:31:29.280 --> 02:31:32.240
[Guest]: Some cases, however, are just, I suppose, accidents of history.

02:31:32.240 --> 02:31:34.080
[Guest]: You know, I was reading this book by Amarpal Singh.

02:31:34.080 --> 02:31:39.000
[Guest]: It's coming out with Harper Collins on the 1857 rebellion, and he focuses just on Delhi.

02:31:39.000 --> 02:31:43.080
[Guest]: And it's fascinating that the rebels have a huge advantage over the British.

02:31:43.080 --> 02:31:45.800
[Guest]: The British have the only advantage that they have a strategic location where they've come

02:31:45.800 --> 02:31:48.960
[Guest]: and the rebels didn't even bother to block them off from that location.

02:31:48.960 --> 02:31:52.040
[Guest]: That location was sitting there, the rebels could have just taken control of it.

02:31:52.040 --> 02:31:55.480
[Guest]: But by the time they did, the British had come in and they had taken control of it.

02:31:55.480 --> 02:31:58.960
[Guest]: The second thing is the rebels had a huge advantage in terms of numbers.

02:31:58.960 --> 02:32:03.080
[Guest]: Each faction in it, it was not a regimented army where everybody listened to one commander.

02:32:03.080 --> 02:32:04.360
[Guest]: There was no single commander.

02:32:04.360 --> 02:32:07.600
[Guest]: There were different kinds of commanders with different backgrounds who had their own internal

02:32:07.600 --> 02:32:09.780
[Guest]: politics, their own internal incentives.

02:32:09.780 --> 02:32:11.840
[Guest]: Some groups are going around plundering Delhi itself.

02:32:11.840 --> 02:32:13.960
[Guest]: Some are going to the emperor and blackmailing the emperor.

02:32:13.960 --> 02:32:16.160
[Guest]: Others are going and telling the emperor, no, no, no, we'll rein them in.

02:32:16.160 --> 02:32:18.400
[Guest]: You are protected and your people will be protected.

02:32:18.400 --> 02:32:21.120
[Guest]: Lots of chaos is happening in the same process.

02:32:21.120 --> 02:32:25.080
[Guest]: What was most fascinating is outside Delhi, there are these tribes or these communities

02:32:25.080 --> 02:32:26.400
[Guest]: of Gurjars.

02:32:26.400 --> 02:32:31.320
[Guest]: And it's so interesting that if, let's say, an Englishman is riding to say Meerut or Mathura,

02:32:31.320 --> 02:32:35.280
[Guest]: one of those places, these people will catch hold of him, strip him of all his valuables

02:32:35.280 --> 02:32:36.680
[Guest]: and then send him off.

02:32:36.680 --> 02:32:39.560
[Guest]: But if it's a rebel going, they'll do the same thing to the rebel leader as well.

02:32:39.560 --> 02:32:43.080
[Guest]: Because for them, it makes no difference if it's a white person or if it's a brown Indian

02:32:43.080 --> 02:32:46.400
[Guest]: fighting against the British, both are equally targets for plunder.

02:32:46.400 --> 02:32:49.000
[Guest]: That is what is happening in the countryside.

02:32:49.000 --> 02:32:51.520
[Guest]: Now again, there's a logic for this.

02:32:51.520 --> 02:32:53.600
[Guest]: They don't see themselves as part of one nation.

02:32:53.600 --> 02:32:56.760
[Guest]: They don't see themselves as part of one common grand cause.

02:32:56.760 --> 02:32:58.760
[Guest]: It did not work.

02:32:58.760 --> 02:32:59.760
[Guest]: Is that inertia?

02:32:59.760 --> 02:33:00.760
[Guest]: No.

02:33:00.760 --> 02:33:04.880
[Guest]: It's just that at that time, in that logic, in their context, this is what they saw.

02:33:04.880 --> 02:33:05.880
[Guest]: My self-interest.

02:33:05.880 --> 02:33:09.800
[Guest]: Why should I bother about what is happening in Delhi or what the rebels are wanting to

02:33:09.800 --> 02:33:10.800
[Guest]: do?

02:33:10.800 --> 02:33:13.520
[Guest]: As far as I'm concerned, I've got an opportunity to make a lot of money through plunder.

02:33:13.520 --> 02:33:15.080
[Guest]: Let me just focus on that.

02:33:15.080 --> 02:33:18.520
[Guest]: Whatever happens in Delhi, kings come, kings go, rulers come, rulers go.

02:33:18.520 --> 02:33:21.480
[Guest]: We will just take care of our self-interest.

02:33:21.480 --> 02:33:24.800
[Guest]: And that at different political levels, you see that playing out in different ways.

02:33:24.800 --> 02:33:28.480
[Guest]: That's why I'm not a bit hesitant to say inertia plays a role.

02:33:28.480 --> 02:33:32.320
[Guest]: But I think not everybody perhaps subscribes to a grand vision.

02:33:32.320 --> 02:33:37.160
[Guest]: Not everybody is part of some kind of grand movement of history.

02:33:37.160 --> 02:33:39.560
[Guest]: It's not really the case as far as I can see.

02:33:39.560 --> 02:33:42.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, this is really everything you've described, I agree.

02:33:42.360 --> 02:33:47.320
[Amit Varma]: Inertia doesn't fit it because these are just people responding to their immediate incentives.

02:33:47.320 --> 02:33:51.680
[Amit Varma]: And you know, game theory could explain why most of the princes said they supported the

02:33:51.680 --> 02:33:53.400
[Amit Varma]: British during 1857.

02:33:53.400 --> 02:33:56.640
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, if you give them an ideal situation where there is a guarantee that

02:33:56.640 --> 02:33:59.480
[Amit Varma]: everybody will be on the same side, they'll choose that side.

02:33:59.480 --> 02:34:02.280
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, you just go for the status quo and play safe.

02:34:02.280 --> 02:34:06.640
[Amit Varma]: I think by inertia, I meant something that is outside of incentives, more a bias towards

02:34:06.640 --> 02:34:13.640
[Amit Varma]: inaction as it were, which I think plays a part in all our lives as individuals, certainly.

02:34:13.640 --> 02:34:15.120
[Amit Varma]: I don't know how it comes together.

02:34:15.120 --> 02:34:17.880
[Amit Varma]: But let's get back to your book now.

02:34:17.880 --> 02:34:21.280
[Amit Varma]: And your first chapter is titled Raja in a Suit.

02:34:21.280 --> 02:34:25.400
[Amit Varma]: And it's about Travancore about which you've already written so much.

02:34:25.400 --> 02:34:28.400
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about what's happening here.

02:34:28.400 --> 02:34:35.440
[Amit Varma]: How is the relationship between the Travancore kings like Uttaram Tirunal and his successors?

02:34:35.440 --> 02:34:40.880
[Amit Varma]: How is that evolving that relationship with the British Empire and so on?

02:34:40.880 --> 02:34:45.400
[Guest]: So you know, this Uttaram Tirunal was at this interesting juncture where he's inherited

02:34:45.400 --> 02:34:50.560
[Guest]: a system where kingship is defined very much through temple service, Hindu religious institutions.

02:34:50.560 --> 02:34:54.880
[Guest]: In fact, there's a report written by one of his divans, which is all about and it's fascinating.

02:34:54.880 --> 02:34:58.660
[Guest]: It's an administrative report, but it's about the quality of priests and temples, how many

02:34:58.660 --> 02:35:00.440
[Guest]: meals are being dispensed to Brahmins.

02:35:00.440 --> 02:35:04.600
[Guest]: Those are the kind of incentives that those are the things that define what a good Hindu

02:35:04.600 --> 02:35:06.420
[Guest]: state is at that time.

02:35:06.420 --> 02:35:10.200
[Guest]: But he's also facing pressures that come from the presence of Christian missionaries who

02:35:10.200 --> 02:35:12.920
[Guest]: are talking about caste and saying that this is unjust.

02:35:12.920 --> 02:35:18.060
[Guest]: Missionaries, of course, they were not altruistic or completely sort of impartial parties.

02:35:18.060 --> 02:35:20.960
[Guest]: They had their own agendas and intentions as well.

02:35:20.960 --> 02:35:24.480
[Guest]: But they were highlighting an important truth that the king, is he just the king of the

02:35:24.480 --> 02:35:27.200
[Guest]: elites and the existing system?

02:35:27.200 --> 02:35:32.600
[Guest]: Or is it his job also to ameliorate the conditions of poorer people who are not privileged and

02:35:32.600 --> 02:35:33.920
[Guest]: who are marginalized?

02:35:33.920 --> 02:35:35.320
[Guest]: That's a question that comes up.

02:35:35.320 --> 02:35:41.120
[Guest]: The British come up and they're like, a king's job is not just to preside over this partially

02:35:41.120 --> 02:35:46.320
[Guest]: religious, partially political order, but to actively promote progress, which is what?

02:35:46.320 --> 02:35:49.680
[Guest]: Roads, dams, schools, irrigation, that kind of thing.

02:35:49.680 --> 02:35:53.480
[Guest]: So he realizes that I'm at this juncture and he's not always successful at it.

02:35:53.480 --> 02:35:57.520
[Guest]: He's very good socially with the British because he speaks English, wears English suits and

02:35:57.520 --> 02:35:59.940
[Guest]: likes to be painted in English suits and all that.

02:35:59.940 --> 02:36:03.800
[Guest]: But he realizes that I need to be able to negotiate this other language as well.

02:36:03.800 --> 02:36:06.160
[Guest]: That is where Travancore's modernization begins.

02:36:06.160 --> 02:36:10.840
[Guest]: It doesn't come from the kings deciding one fine morning that, oh, we will now be modernizers

02:36:10.840 --> 02:36:12.320
[Guest]: and we will set new standards.

02:36:12.320 --> 02:36:17.120
[Guest]: No, it comes from real political pressures and their desire to preserve the sanctity

02:36:17.120 --> 02:36:18.960
[Guest]: and the power of the throne.

02:36:18.960 --> 02:36:21.000
[Guest]: To preserve that power, they have to adapt.

02:36:21.000 --> 02:36:23.560
[Guest]: So their game with the British is constantly adapting.

02:36:23.560 --> 02:36:26.040
[Guest]: That's where that Madhav Rao, who we mentioned at the start, he comes in.

02:36:26.040 --> 02:36:29.800
[Guest]: They find him as a good candidate who's in good books with the British, speaks English,

02:36:29.800 --> 02:36:33.880
[Guest]: but is also a Hindu Brahmin and therefore meets all the criteria that you require.

02:36:33.880 --> 02:36:36.480
[Guest]: As a Brahmin, he has social authority over Hindus.

02:36:36.480 --> 02:36:41.240
[Guest]: As an English speaker from an English school in Madras, he's got contacts with the British.

02:36:41.240 --> 02:36:46.800
[Guest]: He becomes the person who starts, the word is reform, they start reforming the state,

02:36:46.800 --> 02:36:51.080
[Guest]: cutting down certain taxes, antiquated taxes are thrown out of the window, roads are being

02:36:51.080 --> 02:36:55.240
[Guest]: built, agriculture is being widened, coffee cultivation instead of forests.

02:36:55.240 --> 02:36:57.880
[Guest]: The forests are being cut down and you've got plantations coming in.

02:36:57.880 --> 02:37:00.560
[Guest]: Lots of innovative things that are coming in.

02:37:00.560 --> 02:37:03.520
[Guest]: Things that are sometimes just fashionable, because the British think it's fashionable.

02:37:03.520 --> 02:37:04.520
[Guest]: Not all of it is true.

02:37:04.520 --> 02:37:07.600
[Guest]: The Maharajas also knew that there were different ways of manipulating the British.

02:37:07.600 --> 02:37:11.040
[Guest]: For example, a lot of things, every year they would have a progress report that they would

02:37:11.040 --> 02:37:16.000
[Guest]: publish in the English language, talking about how many miles of roads they'd built, etc.

02:37:16.000 --> 02:37:19.080
[Guest]: But what's interesting is a lot of the social reform stayed just on paper.

02:37:19.080 --> 02:37:22.000
[Guest]: The British came and said, why is it that lower castes are not allowed on your roads?

02:37:22.000 --> 02:37:25.160
[Guest]: Maharaja will issue a proclamation saying, all lower castes are now allowed on the roads.

02:37:25.160 --> 02:37:27.320
[Guest]: In reality, it changes nothing.

02:37:27.320 --> 02:37:31.240
[Guest]: In my grandmother's village, as late as the 1950s, nobody would dare walk on the temple

02:37:31.240 --> 02:37:35.840
[Guest]: road, even though officially in the 1920s itself, the rules had been changed and all

02:37:35.840 --> 02:37:37.560
[Guest]: roads had been thrown open.

02:37:37.560 --> 02:37:41.880
[Guest]: So there was a conversation going on with the British and they also knew exact ways

02:37:41.880 --> 02:37:43.360
[Guest]: in which to impress the British.

02:37:43.360 --> 02:37:47.720
[Guest]: English language, write reports, have statistics and keep the British resident at bay.

02:37:47.720 --> 02:37:52.400
[Guest]: And then, if you're building schools, you can also justify spending money on your temple

02:37:52.400 --> 02:37:53.400
[Guest]: rituals.

02:37:53.400 --> 02:37:56.040
[Guest]: If you're only doing temple rituals, then the British will come and nag you.

02:37:56.040 --> 02:37:58.480
[Guest]: So this becomes a form of adapting.

02:37:58.480 --> 02:38:03.800
[Guest]: So good governance itself becomes a form of keeping the imperial power at bay.

02:38:03.800 --> 02:38:08.640
[Guest]: Because that's the only way you can give the resident and the British no cause for complaint.

02:38:08.640 --> 02:38:11.700
[Guest]: Once you've taken care of what is called good government, you can do what you want.

02:38:11.700 --> 02:38:15.720
[Guest]: You have the freedom and the room to maneuver and continue your Brahminical Hindu riots,

02:38:15.720 --> 02:38:16.720
[Guest]: etc, etc.

02:38:16.720 --> 02:38:19.560
[Guest]: And Uttaram Tirunelveli is the man who starts it in the 1850s.

02:38:19.560 --> 02:38:24.640
[Guest]: But it's taken forward by his nephews, Ailyam and Vishakam, of whom Ailyam is in power for

02:38:24.640 --> 02:38:25.640
[Guest]: 20 years.

02:38:25.640 --> 02:38:27.480
[Guest]: So he's bursting with energy.

02:38:27.480 --> 02:38:30.680
[Guest]: He's an heir apparent, so poor man can't sit on the throne till his brother dies.

02:38:30.680 --> 02:38:32.720
[Guest]: So he's setting up a cigar factory.

02:38:32.720 --> 02:38:33.720
[Guest]: He's a botanist.

02:38:33.720 --> 02:38:34.800
[Guest]: He's collecting plants.

02:38:34.800 --> 02:38:37.080
[Guest]: He's writing commentaries on Sanskrit texts.

02:38:37.080 --> 02:38:39.440
[Guest]: He's writing articles in newspapers.

02:38:39.440 --> 02:38:42.480
[Guest]: He's writing anonymous articles criticizing British policy.

02:38:42.480 --> 02:38:44.960
[Guest]: He's writing open articles criticizing British policy.

02:38:44.960 --> 02:38:45.960
[Guest]: Fascinating.

02:38:45.960 --> 02:38:50.640
[Guest]: Some of the writings he's put down, it's almost the same language as a Gokhale, as a Ranade,

02:38:50.640 --> 02:38:52.920
[Guest]: because he's speaking that same general language.

02:38:52.920 --> 02:38:58.320
[Guest]: He talks openly as a Maharaja about how the British, if the empire has to have a moral

02:38:58.320 --> 02:39:02.040
[Guest]: purpose, it is ultimately of handing India back to Indians.

02:39:02.040 --> 02:39:06.200
[Guest]: He's also able to, as a Maharaja, he's able to articulate a future where Indians will

02:39:06.200 --> 02:39:08.080
[Guest]: be in charge of India.

02:39:08.080 --> 02:39:09.080
[Guest]: And that's fascinating.

02:39:09.080 --> 02:39:11.200
[Guest]: You don't think of Maharajas thinking about these things.

02:39:11.200 --> 02:39:13.640
[Guest]: But he is thinking about larger issues.

02:39:13.640 --> 02:39:15.840
[Guest]: He rules only for five years.

02:39:15.840 --> 02:39:18.680
[Guest]: But both Maharajas are extremely hands-on.

02:39:18.680 --> 02:39:22.440
[Guest]: They realize that to beat the British and to keep the British at bay, to preserve our

02:39:22.440 --> 02:39:24.400
[Guest]: own power, we've got to work for it.

02:39:24.400 --> 02:39:28.040
[Guest]: Whether it's changing our costume, whether it's changing the language we speak, whether

02:39:28.040 --> 02:39:32.480
[Guest]: it's focusing on political reform, we have to do it to survive.

02:39:32.480 --> 02:39:36.720
[Guest]: Their nephew sort of drops the ball a little bit and it creates room for the British to

02:39:36.720 --> 02:39:39.400
[Guest]: once again come and poke their nose in Travancore.

02:39:39.400 --> 02:39:45.920
[Guest]: But for a good 20-30 years, these two Maharajas managed to hold their own and just play the

02:39:45.920 --> 02:39:46.920
[Guest]: British.

02:39:46.920 --> 02:39:50.360
[Guest]: They played within rules set by the British, but they aced that game.

02:39:50.360 --> 02:39:54.560
[Guest]: They said the rules are unfair, the ground is not a level playing field, it's tilted

02:39:54.560 --> 02:39:58.040
[Guest]: in favor of the British, but we will still play and we will still succeed.

02:39:58.040 --> 02:39:59.600
[Amit Varma]: And in great measure, they did.

02:39:59.600 --> 02:40:03.800
[Amit Varma]: And what I kind of find fascinating about this beyond the larger currents that you talk

02:40:03.800 --> 02:40:06.920
[Amit Varma]: about is also the intimate personal portraits that emerge.

02:40:06.920 --> 02:40:11.360
[Amit Varma]: For example, Uttarantirunal is so fascinating in the sense that, you know, you've described

02:40:11.360 --> 02:40:12.720
[Amit Varma]: him as what a charming kid he is.

02:40:12.720 --> 02:40:17.200
[Amit Varma]: I think when he's a little infant, he climbs on the knee of a British Singh and asks, how

02:40:17.200 --> 02:40:18.960
[Amit Varma]: are your people doing?

02:40:18.960 --> 02:40:23.920
[Amit Varma]: And then he takes an interest in medicine and does an apprenticeship under a proper

02:40:23.920 --> 02:40:26.840
[Amit Varma]: doctor and starts a dispensary.

02:40:26.840 --> 02:40:31.040
[Amit Varma]: And before he comes to the throne and people come there just because they want to interact

02:40:31.040 --> 02:40:32.040
[Amit Varma]: with him.

02:40:32.040 --> 02:40:35.960
[Guest]: They come with fake illnesses because, you know, a prince is treating you, it's the most

02:40:35.960 --> 02:40:36.960
[Amit Varma]: fascinating thing.

02:40:36.960 --> 02:40:37.960
[Amit Varma]: A prince is treating you.

02:40:37.960 --> 02:40:43.080
[Amit Varma]: And then this obsession with Kathakali, where, you know, he is obsessed with it, but he cannot

02:40:43.080 --> 02:40:44.520
[Amit Varma]: perform it because he's a royal.

02:40:44.520 --> 02:40:47.960
[Amit Varma]: So he performs in front of a mirror in his palace and all of that.

02:40:47.960 --> 02:40:53.240
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, he loves European company, wears European dress, collects all kinds of

02:40:53.240 --> 02:40:56.640
[Amit Varma]: nonsense.

02:40:56.640 --> 02:41:00.640
[Amit Varma]: And that itself is something that should make us sit back and think that there was a time

02:41:00.640 --> 02:41:03.560
[Amit Varma]: that a clock was a thing of wonder.

02:41:03.560 --> 02:41:05.800
[Amit Varma]: And there was a time that a map was a thing of wonder.

02:41:05.800 --> 02:41:09.260
[Amit Varma]: There are people who never saw a map in their lives.

02:41:09.260 --> 02:41:10.260
[Amit Varma]: Can you imagine?

02:41:10.260 --> 02:41:14.960
[Amit Varma]: You know, it's just absolutely fascinating.

02:41:14.960 --> 02:41:18.880
[Guest]: And map making, that's actually a fascinating process in its own right in the late 18th

02:41:18.880 --> 02:41:22.640
[Guest]: and early 19th century, when these surveyors would go out, a lot of people would think

02:41:22.640 --> 02:41:25.500
[Guest]: this was an invading army because they would have flags and they would have like people

02:41:25.500 --> 02:41:27.640
[Guest]: accompanying them with strange instruments.

02:41:27.640 --> 02:41:29.880
[Guest]: And local people would see them with great suspicion.

02:41:29.880 --> 02:41:34.040
[Guest]: And a lot of Indian Rajas were against these these mapping processes, because what it does

02:41:34.040 --> 02:41:37.600
[Guest]: is it gives data to the British, it gives data to the British exactly where you have

02:41:37.600 --> 02:41:41.560
[Guest]: a fort exactly where your boundaries are, whereas your interest lies in not having that

02:41:41.560 --> 02:41:43.880
[Guest]: kind of precise data given to the British.

02:41:43.880 --> 02:41:46.520
[Guest]: So each of these processes itself is political.

02:41:46.520 --> 02:41:49.360
[Guest]: Map making itself is a political process.

02:41:49.360 --> 02:41:52.440
[Guest]: An imperial power needs a map to know what on earth is governing.

02:41:52.440 --> 02:41:55.640
[Guest]: The people on the ground who are doing the governing, especially the Indian Rajas, they

02:41:55.640 --> 02:41:57.800
[Guest]: don't want the imperial power to know these things.

02:41:57.800 --> 02:42:01.680
[Guest]: You know, there's an example, I think it's a footnote in this book, not in the main text

02:42:01.680 --> 02:42:07.080
[Guest]: about how Kashmir, you know, they had Kashmir under their control, but the Kashmir Maharaja

02:42:07.080 --> 02:42:11.080
[Guest]: had a habit of secreting a good part of his revenue in various forts in forms of like

02:42:11.080 --> 02:42:13.660
[Guest]: jewel and jewels and gold, whatever.

02:42:13.660 --> 02:42:17.920
[Guest]: At one point, the British invade, and they sort of started going to these forts and just

02:42:17.920 --> 02:42:21.360
[Guest]: figuring out what is in these, and they discover large quantities of treasure, which they didn't

02:42:21.360 --> 02:42:24.960
[Guest]: even know existed, because the Maharaja had hidden them away in different places.

02:42:24.960 --> 02:42:30.000
[Guest]: One Jaipur Maharaja, he would fudge his accounts royally, you know, he modernized his government

02:42:30.000 --> 02:42:32.840
[Guest]: in certain areas, roads, railways, fine.

02:42:32.840 --> 02:42:36.440
[Guest]: But his revenue management, he refused to modernize, because modernization means what's

02:42:36.440 --> 02:42:40.080
[Guest]: reports and statistics, which means what the British resident can read them and understand

02:42:40.080 --> 02:42:42.160
[Guest]: them as easily as the Raja, nahi chahiye.

02:42:42.160 --> 02:42:46.360
[Guest]: I will do it in a way where only I have control over the data, only I understand what this

02:42:46.360 --> 02:42:51.200
[Guest]: data means, and through that he was able to cut off as much as 20 lakhs of his revenue

02:42:51.200 --> 02:42:53.640
[Guest]: and avoid paying the British a higher tribute.

02:42:53.640 --> 02:42:55.320
[Guest]: They are counter manipulating the British.

02:42:55.320 --> 02:42:57.680
[Guest]: As late as 1906, the British are even aware of this.

02:42:57.680 --> 02:43:02.080
[Guest]: Jaipur Maharaja makes a series of donations to British charities, and the British officials

02:43:02.080 --> 02:43:05.800
[Guest]: say we know exactly why he's doing this, because he wants us to not pay attention to his books

02:43:05.800 --> 02:43:06.800
[Guest]: of account.

02:43:06.800 --> 02:43:08.080
[Guest]: So this is a form of bribery.

02:43:08.080 --> 02:43:12.000
[Guest]: He's paying them off in some other charitable situation, so they don't poke their nose into

02:43:12.000 --> 02:43:16.080
[Guest]: his actual serious accounts and figure out how much money he's concealing from the eyes

02:43:16.080 --> 02:43:20.280
[Guest]: of the British, and thereby paying a lower tribute.

02:43:20.280 --> 02:43:23.520
[Guest]: Constant wonderful like fascinating strategies in play in all these states.

02:43:23.520 --> 02:43:28.680
[Guest]: So that reference to mapmaking just sent me down this route of thinking of how even something

02:43:28.680 --> 02:43:33.440
[Guest]: so basic that we today take for granted was actually a political negotiation with very

02:43:33.440 --> 02:43:35.600
[Guest]: serious political consequences.

02:43:35.600 --> 02:43:40.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it's another web series right there, you can call it the mapmaker and the accountant

02:43:40.360 --> 02:43:45.240
[Amit Varma]: about how information, you know, brings power with it and how it's so important.

02:43:45.240 --> 02:43:50.480
[Amit Varma]: And the two nephews, you know, there's Ahilyam Tirunella, I hope I pronounced that right.

02:43:50.480 --> 02:43:55.480
[Amit Varma]: Who is on the one hand, you know, he's a polyglot, he's, he's described by the British as conservative

02:43:55.480 --> 02:43:58.160
[Amit Varma]: by temperament, but liberal by intellect.

02:43:58.160 --> 02:44:04.520
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, he's also described as a, quote, moral wreck and sexual pervert,

02:44:04.520 --> 02:44:05.520
[Amit Varma]: stop quote.

02:44:05.520 --> 02:44:09.760
[Amit Varma]: And you describe this wonderful dying ritual, which royals apparently had almost a Dorian

02:44:09.760 --> 02:44:14.800
[Amit Varma]: grayish kind of thing where when a royal is dying, he'll, you know, a random outside stranger

02:44:14.800 --> 02:44:19.120
[Amit Varma]: will be paid money, a Brahmin will be paid money to come and take on all the sins of

02:44:19.120 --> 02:44:20.240
[Amit Varma]: the royal.

02:44:20.240 --> 02:44:22.560
[Guest]: And you basically embrace the royal who's dying.

02:44:22.560 --> 02:44:27.120
[Guest]: And by that you sort of, you become the scapegoat, you, you, you absorb all his sins.

02:44:27.120 --> 02:44:28.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah.

02:44:28.120 --> 02:44:31.720
[Amit Varma]: And then the royal dies happy that he's not committed any sins and the Brahmin is escorted

02:44:31.720 --> 02:44:35.160
[Amit Varma]: outside the kingdom and said, Okay, get, get lost and don't come back here.

02:44:35.160 --> 02:44:38.440
[Amit Varma]: And here's your money, presumably.

02:44:38.440 --> 02:44:42.560
[Guest]: I don't know what's interesting in the Travancore Rajas is that the Raja embraces the Brahmin,

02:44:42.560 --> 02:44:45.120
[Guest]: the Brahmin takes the sins, but where do they send the Brahmin?

02:44:45.120 --> 02:44:46.120
[Guest]: Into British India.

02:44:46.120 --> 02:44:49.520
[Guest]: Tell him you take my sins and get lost into British India.

02:44:49.520 --> 02:44:51.320
[Guest]: Just don't come back to Travancore with my sins.

02:44:51.320 --> 02:44:52.320
[Guest]: Lovely.

02:44:52.320 --> 02:44:55.840
[Amit Varma]: There's a story in that also, maybe, you know, maybe there's a Brahmin who goes to all the

02:44:55.840 --> 02:44:58.080
[Amit Varma]: different kingdoms and does this.

02:44:58.080 --> 02:45:02.840
[Amit Varma]: And Visakhan Tirunal is also so fascinating that one, there is that poignant frustration

02:45:02.840 --> 02:45:06.000
[Amit Varma]: that he's next in line for the throne for 20 years.

02:45:06.000 --> 02:45:11.560
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is that because of the matrilineal structure, you know, it's the earlier Kings

02:45:11.560 --> 02:45:14.920
[Amit Varma]: Uttram's sister's kids who are the next in line.

02:45:14.920 --> 02:45:15.920
[Amit Varma]: So his brother is the king.

02:45:15.920 --> 02:45:18.800
[Amit Varma]: It's not like his father is a king and eventually the father will die.

02:45:18.800 --> 02:45:19.800
[Amit Varma]: His brother is the king.

02:45:19.800 --> 02:45:20.800
[Amit Varma]: He has to wait.

02:45:20.800 --> 02:45:22.000
[Amit Varma]: He has to outlive his brother.

02:45:22.000 --> 02:45:23.400
[Amit Varma]: God knows how long he will get.

02:45:23.400 --> 02:45:25.600
[Amit Varma]: There is that whole poignant thing.

02:45:25.600 --> 02:45:29.840
[Amit Varma]: And what comes naturally out of this is that he hates his brother's courtiers and one of

02:45:29.840 --> 02:45:31.500
[Amit Varma]: them is Raja Ravi Varma.

02:45:31.500 --> 02:45:33.360
[Amit Varma]: So he kicks Raja Ravi Varma out of the throne.

02:45:33.360 --> 02:45:37.320
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the one painting that you have of Visakhan in your book is by Ramaswamy Naidu,

02:45:37.320 --> 02:45:39.760
[Amit Varma]: who's Raja Ravi Varma's big rival.

02:45:39.760 --> 02:45:40.760
[Guest]: What do you think of his work?

02:45:40.760 --> 02:45:41.760
[Guest]: Equally interesting.

02:45:41.760 --> 02:45:44.000
[Guest]: In fact, Ramaswamy Naidu is not as famous.

02:45:44.000 --> 02:45:46.920
[Guest]: Ravi Varma sort of became more famous and his name we all know now.

02:45:46.920 --> 02:45:50.920
[Guest]: But in the late 19th century, Ramaswamy Naidu was also a very famous artist.

02:45:50.920 --> 02:45:54.480
[Guest]: And in fact, before Ravi Varma, Madhav Rao, who was Diwan of Travancore and then became

02:45:54.480 --> 02:45:57.880
[Guest]: Diwan of Baroda, he actually invited Ramaswamy Naidu to come.

02:45:57.880 --> 02:45:59.960
[Guest]: And this is again, I should credit Rahul Sagar for this.

02:45:59.960 --> 02:46:01.520
[Guest]: He recently told me about this.

02:46:01.520 --> 02:46:07.600
[Guest]: In 1876, Madhav Rao invites Ramaswamy Naidu to come and visit Baroda and work there.

02:46:07.600 --> 02:46:10.680
[Guest]: But Raja Ravi Varma comes only around 1880, 1880, 1881.

02:46:10.680 --> 02:46:11.680
[Guest]: That is when Ravi Varma comes.

02:46:11.680 --> 02:46:12.680
[Guest]: He's second.

02:46:12.680 --> 02:46:18.200
[Guest]: So that essentially shows that Ramaswamy Naidu, even as late as the early 1880s, was sort

02:46:18.200 --> 02:46:21.520
[Guest]: of considered one notch perhaps higher than Ravi Varma.

02:46:21.520 --> 02:46:23.680
[Guest]: Although eventually Ravi Varma sort of picked up.

02:46:23.680 --> 02:46:25.600
[Guest]: One of the reasons being Ravi Varma's pedigree.

02:46:25.600 --> 02:46:27.560
[Guest]: He came from an aristocratic family.

02:46:27.560 --> 02:46:30.680
[Guest]: In many ways, he was a social equal with many of the Rajas he met.

02:46:30.680 --> 02:46:36.840
[Guest]: So he visits Udaipur, for example, and Udaipur has a local painter from a local artist and

02:46:36.840 --> 02:46:41.240
[Guest]: cast who's actually gone to London and studied at the Slade School of Art on a scholarship

02:46:41.240 --> 02:46:42.240
[Guest]: from the Maharana.

02:46:42.240 --> 02:46:43.800
[Guest]: But he's still treated as a craftsman.

02:46:43.800 --> 02:46:47.520
[Guest]: Whereas Ravi Varma, when he comes, he's treated as a nobleman.

02:46:47.520 --> 02:46:48.760
[Guest]: He's given robes of honor.

02:46:48.760 --> 02:46:50.000
[Guest]: He's given a necklace.

02:46:50.000 --> 02:46:51.160
[Guest]: He's not just given a fee.

02:46:51.160 --> 02:46:56.120
[Guest]: He's treated as an equal through these symbolic gifts as well, which I think plays a big role

02:46:56.120 --> 02:46:57.120
[Guest]: in Ravi Varma's reputation.

02:46:57.120 --> 02:46:59.640
[Guest]: Ravi Varma's reputation wasn't purely talent.

02:46:59.640 --> 02:47:00.720
[Guest]: It was also privilege.

02:47:00.720 --> 02:47:05.720
[Guest]: It was also the fact that he could move around with great ease among the crowd that he was

02:47:05.720 --> 02:47:06.720
[Guest]: painting.

02:47:06.720 --> 02:47:08.120
[Guest]: He was never in a supplicant position.

02:47:08.120 --> 02:47:12.080
[Guest]: He was like this fashionable man who came from an aristocratic family with tens of thousands

02:47:12.080 --> 02:47:15.360
[Guest]: of acres of land, sisters-in-law, Aranis of Travancore.

02:47:15.360 --> 02:47:17.680
[Guest]: He was in some ways exotic to the British for that reason.

02:47:17.680 --> 02:47:19.400
[Guest]: That's why they called him the painter prince.

02:47:19.400 --> 02:47:25.200
[Guest]: He wasn't a prince, but that tag sort of caught on because of his background.

02:47:25.200 --> 02:47:29.120
[Amit Varma]: So you know, speaking of Raja Ravi Varma, to take a quick digression, I just realized

02:47:29.120 --> 02:47:33.520
[Amit Varma]: that it is very much sanskari for me to take digressions because hey, our epics did.

02:47:33.520 --> 02:47:38.720
[Amit Varma]: But to take that digression, from the time you first saw Raja Ravi Varma's paintings,

02:47:38.720 --> 02:47:43.480
[Amit Varma]: what is the effect of your appreciation of his work due to context?

02:47:43.480 --> 02:47:49.080
[Amit Varma]: Like one, you get the kind of context of the different influences that he's getting, like

02:47:49.080 --> 02:47:53.640
[Amit Varma]: those early influences in the Travancore kingdom are obviously the Kerala murals and all that.

02:47:53.640 --> 02:47:56.880
[Amit Varma]: But as you point out, he then spends a lot of time in the palace where he looks at, you

02:47:56.880 --> 02:48:00.760
[Amit Varma]: know, the art of the European artists and gets influenced by that.

02:48:00.760 --> 02:48:04.200
[Amit Varma]: And then he's traveling through all these places, he's evolving.

02:48:04.200 --> 02:48:07.520
[Amit Varma]: One of the things that happened in Baroda was that he got so much patronage there that

02:48:07.520 --> 02:48:12.060
[Amit Varma]: he was freely allowed to travel and show his paintings and that becomes popular.

02:48:12.060 --> 02:48:17.640
[Amit Varma]: He can buy his lithograph press and no doubt that changes the direction of his work.

02:48:17.640 --> 02:48:23.160
[Amit Varma]: How much is your appreciation impacted both by getting a deeper understanding of the circumstances

02:48:23.160 --> 02:48:28.140
[Amit Varma]: and the context in which he's creating his work, and also by the good luck and the privilege,

02:48:28.140 --> 02:48:32.440
[Amit Varma]: as you describe it, and the fact that it must have been so much harder for competition.

02:48:32.440 --> 02:48:36.720
[Amit Varma]: And also for what his work came to mean, like at a particular point in time, we discussed

02:48:36.720 --> 02:48:41.240
[Amit Varma]: civilizational identity earlier, and you've also pointed out about mythological paintings

02:48:41.240 --> 02:48:46.720
[Amit Varma]: became so popular and perhaps played a part like Amar Chitra Katha in later days, or,

02:48:46.720 --> 02:48:51.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, the serial Mahabharata and Ramayana in the 80s, perhaps played a part in forming

02:48:51.680 --> 02:48:53.640
[Guest]: a part of that civilizational identity.

02:48:53.640 --> 02:48:58.360
[Guest]: Yeah, because this is where Baroda's state comes in, because till then Ravi Orma's doing

02:48:58.360 --> 02:49:01.840
[Guest]: mainly a lot of sentimental works, in the sense, woman with a flower, woman doing her

02:49:01.840 --> 02:49:05.560
[Guest]: hair, you know, these pretty paintings, which lots of people like, and he's doing portraits.

02:49:05.560 --> 02:49:06.560
[Guest]: This is his thing.

02:49:06.560 --> 02:49:11.920
[Guest]: With Baroda, what he taps into really is depicting scenes from the epics.

02:49:11.920 --> 02:49:13.000
[Guest]: He started doing some of it.

02:49:13.000 --> 02:49:16.880
[Guest]: He's done a Shakuntala, for example, he's done a Sita Bhumi Pravesh, for example, before

02:49:16.880 --> 02:49:17.880
[Guest]: he comes to Baroda.

02:49:17.880 --> 02:49:22.880
[Guest]: But in Baroda, really, the kind of interest the Maharaja has in having these epic scenes

02:49:22.880 --> 02:49:28.240
[Guest]: depicted in that realistic academic Western style, that gives him an idea.

02:49:28.240 --> 02:49:31.360
[Guest]: And he displays these paintings before they are sent to the palace.

02:49:31.360 --> 02:49:33.540
[Guest]: And the kind of people who come there, they're in awe.

02:49:33.540 --> 02:49:36.360
[Guest]: Because the thing is, you've gone to temples and you've seen sculptures, you've gone and

02:49:36.360 --> 02:49:40.720
[Guest]: seen figurines of gods that you can perhaps do puja to in your houses.

02:49:40.720 --> 02:49:45.040
[Guest]: But you've never seen goddesses in high neck blouses and contemporary sarees.

02:49:45.040 --> 02:49:48.000
[Guest]: Remember that at that time, this is a very contemporary dress that is being worn.

02:49:48.000 --> 02:49:51.320
[Guest]: We now look at a Ravi Arnav painting saying, oh, so quaint and so old fashioned at that

02:49:51.320 --> 02:49:52.320
[Guest]: time.

02:49:52.320 --> 02:49:55.240
[Guest]: This is basically the fashionable way of draping the saree in Bengal.

02:49:55.240 --> 02:49:58.320
[Guest]: Your gods have come out in human form in front of you.

02:49:58.320 --> 02:50:02.600
[Guest]: And this is, he wasn't the first to do it, but his works, because of the access he had,

02:50:02.600 --> 02:50:04.840
[Guest]: managed to garner a lot of attention.

02:50:04.840 --> 02:50:07.880
[Guest]: And that sets him off on an idea which is larger than art itself.

02:50:07.880 --> 02:50:09.200
[Guest]: It's sort of a nationalistic thing.

02:50:09.200 --> 02:50:10.880
[Guest]: And this is where Sayajeev Rao also supports him.

02:50:10.880 --> 02:50:16.280
[Guest]: And most importantly, Madhav Rao, who is the Diwan, he seeds in Ravi Arnav the idea that

02:50:16.280 --> 02:50:19.540
[Guest]: your paintings are fine, but only elites are collecting them.

02:50:19.540 --> 02:50:23.720
[Guest]: If you make prints of the paintings, they can go across to all households in India and

02:50:23.720 --> 02:50:27.200
[Guest]: become a real major thing and create a kind of national imagery for India.

02:50:27.200 --> 02:50:30.440
[Guest]: Ravi Arnav has that idea clearly in his head because of Madhav Rao's comment.

02:50:30.440 --> 02:50:34.200
[Guest]: Sayajeev Rao's commission of those 14 Puranic paintings and the success this received whenever

02:50:34.200 --> 02:50:39.140
[Guest]: they displayed, he realizes that maybe I should invest in a lithograph press.

02:50:39.140 --> 02:50:42.680
[Guest]: So then these paintings are churned out in these cheap prints that are there.

02:50:42.680 --> 02:50:45.480
[Guest]: And that's why he's by some called a calendar artist.

02:50:45.480 --> 02:50:50.120
[Guest]: But the thing is, suddenly your gods are able to come to your house and they look appealing,

02:50:50.120 --> 02:50:53.080
[Guest]: they look accessible, and you've got them on your walls.

02:50:53.080 --> 02:50:57.320
[Guest]: So ever since then, when people shut their eyes and they visualize a Saraswati or a Lakshmi,

02:50:57.320 --> 02:51:00.920
[Guest]: people are visualizing a Ravi Varma depiction of Saraswati and Lakshmi in a saree, standing

02:51:00.920 --> 02:51:05.000
[Guest]: in a certain way, with that proper long sleeved high neck blouse.

02:51:05.000 --> 02:51:07.200
[Guest]: It's not your traditional sculpture where the women are topless.

02:51:07.200 --> 02:51:10.000
[Guest]: It's not your traditional sculpture where the women are voluptuous.

02:51:10.000 --> 02:51:14.960
[Guest]: It is a very Victorianized, but then socially, in the late 19th century, very socially acceptable

02:51:14.960 --> 02:51:16.480
[Guest]: way of depicting women.

02:51:16.480 --> 02:51:19.240
[Guest]: But they're also goddesses and they also look larger than life.

02:51:19.240 --> 02:51:22.320
[Guest]: He's not completely humanized them that they look common.

02:51:22.320 --> 02:51:27.460
[Guest]: At the same time, he's made them human enough for people to take a very keen interest.

02:51:27.460 --> 02:51:31.520
[Guest]: So he does end up doing something and he's very aware that this has a kind of national

02:51:31.520 --> 02:51:32.520
[Guest]: resonance.

02:51:32.520 --> 02:51:36.940
[Guest]: The idea is, at the time when the nationalism is being built, when the nation itself is

02:51:36.940 --> 02:51:41.040
[Guest]: being built, people are aware of difference, Gujarati, Bengali, Maharaja of Baroda, one

02:51:41.040 --> 02:51:45.080
[Guest]: of his incentives in sort of allowing this kind of grand depiction, which can appeal

02:51:45.080 --> 02:51:49.320
[Guest]: in any corner of India, is because he's very aware of dealing with differences within Indians,

02:51:49.320 --> 02:51:50.600
[Guest]: you know, among Indians.

02:51:50.600 --> 02:51:53.680
[Guest]: So when you create this kind of a Lakshmi, it doesn't matter whether you are in Kerala

02:51:53.680 --> 02:51:56.480
[Guest]: or in Kashmir, it will appeal to people.

02:51:56.480 --> 02:52:00.480
[Guest]: He's given it a visual form that will appeal to people and give them one more means by

02:52:00.480 --> 02:52:06.040
[Guest]: which to realize that you are part of one common story and one common religious slash

02:52:06.040 --> 02:52:08.040
[Guest]: civilizational tradition.

02:52:08.040 --> 02:52:11.920
[Guest]: How much of this he did consciously from the start is debatable, but it's clear that the

02:52:11.920 --> 02:52:16.560
[Guest]: idea was told to him by Madhavrao with a very clear statement that this will have a nationalist

02:52:16.560 --> 02:52:18.480
[Guest]: kind of impact.

02:52:18.480 --> 02:52:22.280
[Guest]: And he runs with the idea, gets the patronage of Maharaja of Baroda and, you know, ends

02:52:22.280 --> 02:52:28.320
[Guest]: up doing something that, in some ways, the reputation he enjoys among commoner communities

02:52:28.320 --> 02:52:32.840
[Guest]: or more ordinary people is because of the prints, not because of his grand paintings.

02:52:32.840 --> 02:52:37.280
[Guest]: The paintings were in palaces and big halls, the prints are what really made him a, I wouldn't

02:52:37.280 --> 02:52:41.800
[Guest]: call a household name, but a much more sort of well-known figure across India, which in

02:52:41.800 --> 02:52:45.400
[Guest]: those days was not an easy thing to build that kind of reputation.

02:52:45.400 --> 02:52:47.080
[Guest]: That's why he left Ramaswamy Naidu behind.

02:52:47.080 --> 02:52:51.200
[Guest]: Ramaswamy Naidu never became a household name, whereas he did by taking that very business

02:52:51.200 --> 02:52:55.240
[Guest]: decision of churning out prints that would appeal to everyone, whether it's a tilak in

02:52:55.240 --> 02:53:00.040
[Guest]: Maharashtra or Maharaja of Baroda in Gujarat or the Mysore Maharaja in the south, everybody

02:53:00.040 --> 02:53:01.280
[Amit Varma]: loves them.

02:53:01.280 --> 02:53:03.440
[Amit Varma]: And is that a double-edged sword in some way?

02:53:03.440 --> 02:53:07.440
[Amit Varma]: Like on the one hand, of course, there's something that goes across regions and across people

02:53:07.440 --> 02:53:09.620
[Amit Varma]: and across languages and speaks to people.

02:53:09.620 --> 02:53:13.760
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, is making a picture of something for the very first time in a

02:53:13.760 --> 02:53:18.720
[Amit Varma]: sense an act of vandalism, simply because if you're painting a goddess and so many different

02:53:18.720 --> 02:53:23.160
[Amit Varma]: conceptions of the goddess could have existed before, but then you make that picture and

02:53:23.160 --> 02:53:24.360
[Amit Varma]: then that is the picture.

02:53:24.360 --> 02:53:28.440
[Amit Varma]: And then when people think of the goddess, they think of that picture by Raja Ravi Varma.

02:53:28.440 --> 02:53:33.160
[Amit Varma]: And have we lost something in doing that by homogenizing a particular idea of something?

02:53:33.160 --> 02:53:36.400
[Guest]: Yeah, but you know, and that's why I said in context, if you look at it, it was a time

02:53:36.400 --> 02:53:37.400
[Guest]: of homogenizing.

02:53:37.400 --> 02:53:42.280
[Guest]: Everybody wanted a common nationalism, a common identity, a common language.

02:53:42.280 --> 02:53:46.320
[Guest]: Hindi is essentially constructed in the late 19th century to serve as some kind of common

02:53:46.320 --> 02:53:47.880
[Guest]: unifying language.

02:53:47.880 --> 02:53:51.760
[Guest]: In that time, it was part of that homogenizing trend, you know, and it's clearly left an

02:53:51.760 --> 02:53:52.760
[Guest]: impact.

02:53:52.760 --> 02:53:55.720
[Guest]: As you said, even that serial Ramayana, the kind of thing, costumes they wear, they look

02:53:55.720 --> 02:54:00.320
[Guest]: like they walked out of a Ravi Varma painting because it's clearly left that kind of a cultural

02:54:00.320 --> 02:54:01.320
[Guest]: impact.

02:54:01.320 --> 02:54:02.320
[Guest]: Have we lost something?

02:54:02.320 --> 02:54:03.320
[Guest]: Yes, we have.

02:54:03.320 --> 02:54:08.000
[Guest]: The diversity, the different ways of depicting God, some in ways that would not be considered

02:54:08.000 --> 02:54:12.920
[Guest]: sanitized and proper anymore, you know, some that were very localized, very regional.

02:54:12.920 --> 02:54:17.200
[Guest]: A lot of subaltern traditions of art have been lost because he also elevated a Brahminical

02:54:17.200 --> 02:54:21.200
[Guest]: reading of things, not just, you know, because he came from a highly Sanskritized family.

02:54:21.200 --> 02:54:23.720
[Guest]: His mother, everybody was scholars in Sanskrit.

02:54:23.720 --> 02:54:28.080
[Guest]: So their reading was also extremely elite, not just in class terms, but also in caste

02:54:28.080 --> 02:54:29.080
[Guest]: terms.

02:54:29.080 --> 02:54:34.000
[Guest]: And that became the new gold standard, leaving out a lot of other forms of, you know, representing

02:54:34.000 --> 02:54:35.640
[Guest]: these ideas even.

02:54:35.640 --> 02:54:39.440
[Guest]: In his paintings, it's always the maid or the Asura women who are dark skinned, you

02:54:39.440 --> 02:54:43.260
[Guest]: know, everybody else is fair, which is ironic because a lot of the Puranic figures he painted

02:54:43.260 --> 02:54:44.600
[Guest]: in the Puranas, they're dark.

02:54:44.600 --> 02:54:48.000
[Guest]: Draupadi is dark, but he paints her fair, you know, Krishna is dark, but he won't make

02:54:48.000 --> 02:54:49.000
[Guest]: him that dark.

02:54:49.000 --> 02:54:52.800
[Guest]: You know, Shri Rama also, he will not make him very dark, whereas the maid will be properly

02:54:52.800 --> 02:54:53.800
[Guest]: dark.

02:54:53.800 --> 02:54:57.280
[Guest]: Ravi Varma's mother-in-law was dark and he painted her as she was.

02:54:57.280 --> 02:55:00.240
[Guest]: But perhaps there was a reason people often don't like their mothers-in-law.

02:55:00.240 --> 02:55:01.240
[Amit Varma]: So yeah.

02:55:01.240 --> 02:55:05.160
[Amit Varma]: And a formidable woman, you've described this famous murder case, I think of 1862, where

02:55:05.160 --> 02:55:11.800
[Amit Varma]: this mother-in-law was allegedly having a scene with some outsider to the family and

02:55:11.800 --> 02:55:15.920
[Amit Varma]: the father-in-law got that person murdered and it was a famous case and whatever.

02:55:15.920 --> 02:55:20.240
[Amit Varma]: You also speak about Raja Ravi Varma's iconic painting, There Comes Papa in this, which

02:55:20.240 --> 02:55:24.400
[Amit Varma]: was really a painting which showed his wife Kochupanki and daughter Mahaprabha and Mahaprabha

02:55:24.400 --> 02:55:25.400
[Amit Varma]: and her son.

02:55:25.400 --> 02:55:27.180
[Amit Varma]: Oh, Mahaprabha and her son, sorry.

02:55:27.180 --> 02:55:29.400
[Amit Varma]: And it's called There Comes Papa.

02:55:29.400 --> 02:55:35.240
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing about this, which you point out is that so far, at that point,

02:55:35.240 --> 02:55:37.600
[Amit Varma]: Kerala society was really matrilineal.

02:55:37.600 --> 02:55:38.780
[Amit Varma]: The women mattered.

02:55:38.780 --> 02:55:43.000
[Guest]: You waited for the mother, you waited for the woman, the uncle at most.

02:55:43.000 --> 02:55:46.020
[Amit Varma]: The papa was like a very peripheral figure.

02:55:46.020 --> 02:55:48.240
[Amit Varma]: But here that is flipped around.

02:55:48.240 --> 02:55:51.000
[Amit Varma]: The woman and the child are waiting for papa.

02:55:51.000 --> 02:55:52.000
[Guest]: Because he's doing this.

02:55:52.000 --> 02:55:56.040
[Guest]: This painting is being displayed for a victorianised audience for whom the papa matters.

02:55:56.040 --> 02:56:00.160
[Guest]: So you know, if you asked a Malayali of that generation who your father is, they wouldn't,

02:56:00.160 --> 02:56:01.160
[Guest]: they would answer.

02:56:01.160 --> 02:56:03.000
[Guest]: But the real question is, who's your uncle?

02:56:03.000 --> 02:56:06.040
[Guest]: You know that your maternal uncle, your mother's brother, who's your mother?

02:56:06.040 --> 02:56:07.040
[Guest]: What is her family?

02:56:07.040 --> 02:56:08.040
[Guest]: That is what matters.

02:56:08.040 --> 02:56:13.080
[Guest]: To illustrate, I remember asking my grandfather, his father's name I knew, because my grandfather

02:56:13.080 --> 02:56:14.080
[Guest]: told him.

02:56:14.080 --> 02:56:15.560
[Guest]: And I asked him, what is your father's father's name?

02:56:15.560 --> 02:56:16.880
[Guest]: Grandfather had no clue.

02:56:16.880 --> 02:56:18.800
[Guest]: He has no idea who his father's father is.

02:56:18.800 --> 02:56:22.760
[Guest]: He knows who his mother's father is, but not his father's father, because that man was

02:56:22.760 --> 02:56:23.760
[Guest]: never in the picture.

02:56:23.760 --> 02:56:27.440
[Guest]: There was no question because he was, your father himself is from a different family.

02:56:27.440 --> 02:56:31.000
[Guest]: Father's father, nobody even bothers to care about, you know, it's not a question that

02:56:31.000 --> 02:56:32.000
[Guest]: arises naturally.

02:56:32.000 --> 02:56:35.000
[Guest]: When I asked him, he actually sat down and wondered, why on earth have I never asked

02:56:35.000 --> 02:56:36.080
[Guest]: this question?

02:56:36.080 --> 02:56:40.320
[Guest]: Because even in the 30s, when he was growing up, it was still a matrilineal sort of culture

02:56:40.320 --> 02:56:42.680
[Guest]: where people still focused on the mother's side.

02:56:42.680 --> 02:56:47.040
[Guest]: Ravi Varma's painting though, although he painted his wife, his daughter and son, and

02:56:47.040 --> 02:56:50.920
[Guest]: the lady's pointing out, someone's approaching, she's pointing out to the baby that look,

02:56:50.920 --> 02:56:51.920
[Guest]: someone's coming.

02:56:51.920 --> 02:56:56.360
[Guest]: To a Malayali, you would say, uncle is coming, mother is coming, grandmother's coming.

02:56:56.360 --> 02:56:57.360
[Guest]: Father is a bit unusual.

02:56:57.360 --> 02:57:01.200
[Guest]: Just, and we know this is for a victorianized audience, because this painting was sent to

02:57:01.200 --> 02:57:02.720
[Guest]: America to be displayed.

02:57:02.720 --> 02:57:06.080
[Guest]: And at that time, if you look in the painting, there's also a dog in that painting.

02:57:06.080 --> 02:57:09.600
[Guest]: Dogs were not kept as pets in high caste Hindu houses, they were considered unclean.

02:57:09.600 --> 02:57:14.120
[Guest]: The dog was added simply because in Western countries, the dog represented that kind of

02:57:14.120 --> 02:57:15.240
[Guest]: domesticity.

02:57:15.240 --> 02:57:20.080
[Guest]: And Ravi Varma wanted to signal that, oh, look, this is an Indian native woman in Malabar,

02:57:20.080 --> 02:57:25.440
[Guest]: but even she is the same as you, even she has a pet dog, and she's waiting for her husband.

02:57:25.440 --> 02:57:30.560
[Guest]: He's again trying to construct something that the Westerner can relate to easily, without

02:57:30.560 --> 02:57:34.960
[Guest]: taking away too much from his daughter's, in quotes, native appearance.

02:57:34.960 --> 02:57:38.880
[Guest]: So he's also trying to say, different, but like you, you know, that's the message he's

02:57:38.880 --> 02:57:40.360
[Guest]: trying to send across in that painting.

02:57:40.360 --> 02:57:43.840
[Amit Varma]: But it's kind of fascinating, because when I read about it, my assumption was that it's

02:57:43.840 --> 02:57:45.760
[Amit Varma]: a sign of Kerala society changing.

02:57:45.760 --> 02:57:50.560
[Amit Varma]: But what you're saying is, he's actually also signaling for his new patrons.

02:57:50.560 --> 02:57:54.280
[Guest]: That change is something he's riding, he's realized that this change is coming.

02:57:54.280 --> 02:57:59.400
[Guest]: And he's sort of riding that wave by saying, by sort of depicting that on canvas, you know,

02:57:59.400 --> 02:58:03.280
[Guest]: he wants to show that, yes, change is coming, and this reform is coming in, husbands are

02:58:03.280 --> 02:58:04.960
[Guest]: becoming very important.

02:58:04.960 --> 02:58:07.840
[Guest]: And he's, you know, joining that conversation as well.

02:58:07.840 --> 02:58:12.600
[Amit Varma]: To the book, one of the themes is that there is what you call a triangular contest between

02:58:12.600 --> 02:58:17.440
[Amit Varma]: the prince, between the Diwan, and between the sort of resident or the representative

02:58:17.440 --> 02:58:19.100
[Amit Varma]: of the British Empire.

02:58:19.100 --> 02:58:21.360
[Amit Varma]: So how did that play out in Travancore?

02:58:21.360 --> 02:58:24.920
[Amit Varma]: Because obviously, they kind of got lucky with the Diwans that they had, and you know,

02:58:24.920 --> 02:58:27.600
[Amit Varma]: in the sense of Madhava Rao and Sesha Shastri.

02:58:27.600 --> 02:58:30.900
[Amit Varma]: So you know, how is that kind of playing out?

02:58:30.900 --> 02:58:36.840
[Amit Varma]: And how do things then proceed like this clearly a movement through the decades where things

02:58:36.840 --> 02:58:39.000
[Amit Varma]: eventually start to unravel?

02:58:39.000 --> 02:58:40.100
[Amit Varma]: So take me through that.

02:58:40.100 --> 02:58:42.720
[Guest]: So the thing is, a lot of these people are very conflicted.

02:58:42.720 --> 02:58:45.440
[Guest]: The Raja wants to progress, but only so far.

02:58:45.440 --> 02:58:49.840
[Guest]: He doesn't want to progress so much that his royal power and authority is questioned.

02:58:49.840 --> 02:58:54.620
[Guest]: The Diwan is educated in the English style, and therefore, he also wants to progress.

02:58:54.620 --> 02:58:58.120
[Guest]: But he also wants the Raja to become more and more constitutional, because in his mind,

02:58:58.120 --> 02:59:03.000
[Guest]: it's important that monarchies become constitutional in the western, in the British format, which

02:59:03.000 --> 02:59:04.000
[Guest]: basically means what?

02:59:04.000 --> 02:59:05.120
[Guest]: The Diwan has more power.

02:59:05.120 --> 02:59:08.680
[Guest]: So there's also, on the one hand, the Raja and the Diwan are on the same page in terms

02:59:08.680 --> 02:59:11.080
[Guest]: of answering British propaganda.

02:59:11.080 --> 02:59:13.520
[Guest]: But internally, there's a conflict between the Raja and Diwan.

02:59:13.520 --> 02:59:17.960
[Guest]: Diwan says as the minister, as an educated, trained minister, I should be supreme and

02:59:17.960 --> 02:59:18.960
[Guest]: I should be in control.

02:59:18.960 --> 02:59:20.560
[Guest]: The Raja should not poke his nose too much.

02:59:20.560 --> 02:59:21.560
[Guest]: He should be constitutional.

02:59:21.560 --> 02:59:24.640
[Guest]: Raja's like, no, no, no, I've got enough taken away by the British.

02:59:24.640 --> 02:59:27.120
[Guest]: I'm not going to let my minister also reduce my power.

02:59:27.120 --> 02:59:29.200
[Guest]: So there was a conflict going on between them.

02:59:29.200 --> 02:59:32.880
[Guest]: The Sesha Shastri is actually quite fascinating because he moves to Pudukottai.

02:59:32.880 --> 02:59:36.720
[Guest]: And you see these twin pressures that are in that state.

02:59:36.720 --> 02:59:38.560
[Guest]: On the one hand, the British as well as Madhavra.

02:59:38.560 --> 02:59:41.720
[Guest]: Madhavra writes to Sesha Shastri saying Pudukottai is in a terrible state.

02:59:41.720 --> 02:59:44.680
[Guest]: If it continues like this, the British will come and take over the state.

02:59:44.680 --> 02:59:48.280
[Guest]: As Indians, we are all naturally well-wishers of the states.

02:59:48.280 --> 02:59:49.280
[Guest]: We have to protect the states.

02:59:49.280 --> 02:59:50.560
[Guest]: So you're like a doctor.

02:59:50.560 --> 02:59:54.000
[Guest]: Think of yourself as a doctor going there to rescue a patient or think of Pudukottai

02:59:54.000 --> 02:59:57.180
[Guest]: as an insect struggling on water and you have to go and sort of save it.

02:59:57.180 --> 03:00:01.620
[Guest]: So Sesha Shastri is going into the state with this huge savior complex.

03:00:01.620 --> 03:00:03.920
[Guest]: So his incentives are multiple there.

03:00:03.920 --> 03:00:08.960
[Guest]: He wants to make the state reformed and progressive so it can answer British standards and sort

03:00:08.960 --> 03:00:11.920
[Guest]: of exceed British standards to an extent he succeeds.

03:00:11.920 --> 03:00:16.360
[Guest]: But in the process, he's also an upper caste Brahmin man in a kingdom governed by robber

03:00:16.360 --> 03:00:19.880
[Guest]: caste kings which are technically much lower than him in the caste hierarchy.

03:00:19.880 --> 03:00:22.920
[Guest]: He cannot help but try and Brahminize these people as well.

03:00:22.920 --> 03:00:27.360
[Guest]: So in Trivandrum, the Raja calls himself Padmanabha Dasa because his deity is Padmanabha Swami.

03:00:27.360 --> 03:00:31.640
[Guest]: Sesha comes and says, okay, now you have to start in Pudukottai, the state deity is Brihadamba,

03:00:31.640 --> 03:00:33.440
[Guest]: you have to call yourself Brihadamba Dasa.

03:00:33.440 --> 03:00:37.520
[Guest]: It was a title some Rajas used, but it was by no means a key title to the throne.

03:00:37.520 --> 03:00:41.900
[Guest]: Whereas now Sesha Shastri uses that and makes the Raja this very pious Brahminized sort

03:00:41.900 --> 03:00:44.680
[Guest]: of version of king.

03:00:44.680 --> 03:00:48.520
[Guest]: Then similarly, Sesha Shastri dismantles the entire internal structure which depends on

03:00:48.520 --> 03:00:53.000
[Guest]: Kallar Lords, you know, internal relatives of the royal family and bureaucratizes the

03:00:53.000 --> 03:00:54.000
[Guest]: state.

03:00:54.000 --> 03:00:57.480
[Guest]: So bureaucratizing a state and centralizing a state is always painful because you're taking

03:00:57.480 --> 03:01:02.840
[Guest]: away power from traditional institutions and sort of putting it in a secretariat with men

03:01:02.840 --> 03:01:06.880
[Guest]: who are just qualified men, not men who necessarily have roots in the ground.

03:01:06.880 --> 03:01:10.600
[Guest]: And this is a problem a lot of princely states ultimately faced and it caused a lot of internal

03:01:10.600 --> 03:01:16.040
[Guest]: politics as these days bureaucratized and progressed in courts, they would import bureaucrats

03:01:16.040 --> 03:01:19.160
[Guest]: from Madras or from other parts of British India.

03:01:19.160 --> 03:01:22.720
[Guest]: And inevitably, most of these bureaucrats would be either Tamil Brahmins or Maharashtrian

03:01:22.720 --> 03:01:23.720
[Guest]: Brahmins.

03:01:23.720 --> 03:01:28.160
[Guest]: So when in Travancore, when in Pudukottai, when in Mysore, people say we're fighting

03:01:28.160 --> 03:01:29.160
[Guest]: the foreigner.

03:01:29.160 --> 03:01:32.080
[Guest]: The foreigner refers to these Brahmins and these men who've come from other parts of

03:01:32.080 --> 03:01:34.800
[Guest]: India and take over the bureaucracy of these states.

03:01:34.800 --> 03:01:38.140
[Guest]: In Mysore for example, it started in the 18th century and through the 19th century it sort

03:01:38.140 --> 03:01:42.280
[Guest]: of picked up and eventually there was this whole Travancore for Travancoreans, Mysore

03:01:42.280 --> 03:01:46.760
[Guest]: for Mysoreans, we will not have foreigners, that kind of an argument.

03:01:46.760 --> 03:01:51.080
[Guest]: So the Diwan has his own power to preserve, his own vision of what the king should be

03:01:51.080 --> 03:01:52.520
[Guest]: and he's trying to push that.

03:01:52.520 --> 03:01:55.920
[Guest]: The king has a sense of his power and how loyal the Diwan should be and is trying to

03:01:55.920 --> 03:01:56.920
[Guest]: push that.

03:01:56.920 --> 03:02:00.320
[Guest]: The British are sitting and watching, saying which one can we manipulate at any given time.

03:02:00.320 --> 03:02:04.280
[Guest]: And the Maharaja is also trying to see which one can I manipulate at any given time.

03:02:04.280 --> 03:02:08.000
[Guest]: So he, the Maharaja for example, Madhavrao at one point has a lot of power, Maharaja

03:02:08.000 --> 03:02:09.880
[Guest]: has no option but to listen to him.

03:02:09.880 --> 03:02:12.880
[Guest]: So Maharaja doesn't say anything to him, he goes to the British resident and complains

03:02:12.880 --> 03:02:15.800
[Guest]: and gets the British resident to pull Madhavrao into line.

03:02:15.800 --> 03:02:18.640
[Guest]: Later Madhavrao and Maharaja have a falling out but they decide let's keep the British

03:02:18.640 --> 03:02:22.440
[Guest]: out, you and I will come to terms ourselves so the British don't get involved, we will

03:02:22.440 --> 03:02:25.320
[Guest]: just close this quarrel between us ourselves.

03:02:25.320 --> 03:02:29.440
[Guest]: Nobody has any fixed idea, this is a time of flux, everybody has multiple interests

03:02:29.440 --> 03:02:35.520
[Guest]: in play, which is why again as I said this princely politics was by no means simplistic.

03:02:35.520 --> 03:02:40.320
[Guest]: In Rajputana, again people will say it's quirky and eccentric, the Raja goes and he doesn't

03:02:40.320 --> 03:02:44.240
[Guest]: like going to these imperial functions that the Viceroys invite him to.

03:02:44.240 --> 03:02:48.760
[Guest]: Because often the Udaipur Maharana is placed behind Baroda for example, Rajputs will never

03:02:48.760 --> 03:02:51.800
[Guest]: stand behind a Maratha for example, at least in those days, they used to look down on the

03:02:51.800 --> 03:02:57.120
[Guest]: Marathas, so to have your elephant behind a Maratha Maharaja was hugely insulting.

03:02:57.120 --> 03:03:01.760
[Guest]: And in Rajputana, your title was Hindu Suraj, you were the son of the Hindus, so how can

03:03:01.760 --> 03:03:04.800
[Guest]: you go and stand behind other rulers, you have to be first in the queue.

03:03:04.800 --> 03:03:08.440
[Guest]: So these Rajas in dealing with the British, they would come up with all kinds of diplomatic

03:03:08.440 --> 03:03:09.440
[Guest]: illnesses.

03:03:09.440 --> 03:03:12.280
[Guest]: Raja would come to Delhi but conveniently fall ill on the day of the Darbar and not

03:03:12.280 --> 03:03:15.400
[Guest]: show up in the procession, or he would come to Delhi and then some urgent thing would

03:03:15.400 --> 03:03:17.640
[Guest]: take him back to Udaipur and he would turn around.

03:03:17.640 --> 03:03:21.120
[Guest]: So he could tell the Viceroy, hey look I came to Delhi but I am sorry something urgent came

03:03:21.120 --> 03:03:22.120
[Guest]: and I had to go back.

03:03:22.120 --> 03:03:25.360
[Guest]: Or he would say, I came to Delhi, so I came for your procession but I am so sorry I fell

03:03:25.360 --> 03:03:26.360
[Guest]: ill.

03:03:26.360 --> 03:03:30.960
[Guest]: Baroda did this once where he refused to come for one of Karsan's Darbars by saying an old

03:03:30.960 --> 03:03:34.560
[Guest]: widow died in the palace, therefore I am Ashuddha and I have to do all kinds of rituals, therefore

03:03:34.560 --> 03:03:35.560
[Guest]: I can't come.

03:03:35.560 --> 03:03:36.560
[Guest]: Excuses.

03:03:36.560 --> 03:03:41.880
[Guest]: But the thing is, an Udaipur Maharana also has to do this because if he lets the British

03:03:41.880 --> 03:03:47.500
[Guest]: treat him, let's say not as number one, his nobles will start chewing away at his authority.

03:03:47.500 --> 03:03:49.480
[Guest]: So he's got that to deal with.

03:03:49.480 --> 03:03:52.960
[Guest]: He similarly, Maharana Fateh Singh of Udaipur doesn't even have a Diwan.

03:03:52.960 --> 03:03:57.240
[Guest]: There was a Diwan called Rai Pannalal Mehta and he was in English speaking, very good

03:03:57.240 --> 03:04:00.080
[Guest]: on good terms with the British and all of that.

03:04:00.080 --> 03:04:03.160
[Guest]: And Raja started thinking that hold on, I think this Pannalal is becoming too pally

03:04:03.160 --> 03:04:05.320
[Guest]: with the British at my cost.

03:04:05.320 --> 03:04:08.320
[Guest]: If he and the residents start getting too comfortable with each other, what about my

03:04:08.320 --> 03:04:09.500
[Guest]: power?

03:04:09.500 --> 03:04:14.160
[Guest]: So he finds interesting strategies to get the British to sort of negotiate with him.

03:04:14.160 --> 03:04:17.600
[Guest]: The British are very keen on a railway project into Udaipur.

03:04:17.600 --> 03:04:19.160
[Guest]: Raja sits on it for years.

03:04:19.160 --> 03:04:20.560
[Guest]: British say no, no, you must, must, must.

03:04:20.560 --> 03:04:23.680
[Guest]: Finally he says I will if you let me get rid of Rai Pannalal Mehta.

03:04:23.680 --> 03:04:25.600
[Guest]: They say fine, you get rid of your minister.

03:04:25.600 --> 03:04:27.200
[Guest]: He gets rid of the minister.

03:04:27.200 --> 03:04:30.440
[Guest]: Now to appoint any minister, next minister, he needs British approval.

03:04:30.440 --> 03:04:32.000
[Guest]: Raja simply does not appoint a minister.

03:04:32.000 --> 03:04:36.720
[Guest]: For the next many, many, many decades he simply doesn't appoint a minister, just has secretaries,

03:04:36.720 --> 03:04:40.320
[Guest]: gets the secretaries to fight with each other so he is fully in charge, prevents the resident

03:04:40.320 --> 03:04:42.120
[Guest]: from having too much of a say.

03:04:42.120 --> 03:04:46.440
[Guest]: And this is another, one of the Baroda Maharajas also did this when he was told that any ministerial

03:04:46.440 --> 03:04:51.600
[Guest]: appointment requires British sanction, no minister, I will root myself, a way of subverting

03:04:51.600 --> 03:04:52.600
[Guest]: that.

03:04:52.600 --> 03:04:57.200
[Guest]: So there's different layers at which the same figure is acting in different ways.

03:04:57.200 --> 03:05:02.200
[Guest]: It may seem contradictory, it may seem eccentric, it may seem strange, but it again has an internal

03:05:02.200 --> 03:05:06.240
[Guest]: logic involving all these players simultaneously doing different things.

03:05:06.240 --> 03:05:10.280
[Guest]: Madhavrao may feel loyalty to his British masters.

03:05:10.280 --> 03:05:13.840
[Guest]: He may feel like he has a cause in shaping the future of the states.

03:05:13.840 --> 03:05:16.120
[Guest]: He may feel like the ruler has to become constitutional.

03:05:16.120 --> 03:05:19.880
[Guest]: The ruler also has certain common elements with him where he will ally with Madhavrao,

03:05:19.880 --> 03:05:23.360
[Guest]: but at certain places he will diverge with Madhavrao and ally with the British state

03:05:23.360 --> 03:05:24.360
[Guest]: instead.

03:05:24.360 --> 03:05:26.360
[Guest]: So again, very complex, very complicated.

03:05:26.360 --> 03:05:30.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and fascinating and you said that these guys, you know, they would make excuses to

03:05:30.680 --> 03:05:33.520
[Amit Varma]: the British where they go to Delhi and they'd say I've fallen ill.

03:05:33.520 --> 03:05:37.360
[Amit Varma]: And I think that's a credible excuse because one of the things I was struck by was, you

03:05:37.360 --> 03:05:40.560
[Amit Varma]: know, every time you mention one of these guys for the first time, you're giving the

03:05:40.560 --> 03:05:44.000
[Amit Varma]: year of birth and the year of death and they all died young, like, you know, Visakhan Tirunel

03:05:44.000 --> 03:05:47.480
[Amit Varma]: at one point, I think, laments that no one in my family lives till 50.

03:05:47.480 --> 03:05:48.480
[Amit Varma]: Beyond 50.

03:05:48.480 --> 03:05:49.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:05:49.480 --> 03:05:52.120
[Amit Varma]: And Aswathi Tirunel, in fact, died of obesity, I think.

03:05:52.120 --> 03:05:57.520
[Guest]: He had diabetes then and it became very serious because his weight was out of control.

03:05:57.520 --> 03:05:58.840
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, he died of that.

03:05:58.840 --> 03:05:59.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:05:59.840 --> 03:06:04.340
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, in that age where medicine was nowhere near where it is, it's so kind

03:06:04.340 --> 03:06:05.840
[Amit Varma]: of precarious.

03:06:05.840 --> 03:06:10.720
[Amit Varma]: From Pudukottai you also speak about the precarious state of Ramachandra Tondamayi, who was a

03:06:10.720 --> 03:06:17.800
[Amit Varma]: king till 1886 and how after 1854, where the British kind of made the Diwan much more powerful,

03:06:17.800 --> 03:06:23.840
[Amit Varma]: he was so dependent on the Diwan and the resident for funds that at one point in 1870, he applied

03:06:23.840 --> 03:06:29.320
[Amit Varma]: for funds to buy a pet cheetah, which, you know, you throw in all these little things

03:06:29.320 --> 03:06:34.320
[Amit Varma]: randomly in this thing as if it's something completely normal to buy a pet cheetah.

03:06:34.320 --> 03:06:36.920
[Amit Varma]: The royal who fornicated with elephants.

03:06:36.920 --> 03:06:38.200
[Amit Varma]: How does one fornicate with an elephant?

03:06:38.200 --> 03:06:39.200
[Guest]: I have no idea.

03:06:39.200 --> 03:06:42.800
[Guest]: The thing is, the source I've cited, I went into it to see where he got the information

03:06:42.800 --> 03:06:43.800
[Guest]: from.

03:06:43.800 --> 03:06:47.840
[Guest]: He doesn't reveal it because he says it would amount to defamation to name the prince who

03:06:47.840 --> 03:06:52.080
[Guest]: was suspected of having romantic feelings for elephants.

03:06:52.080 --> 03:06:56.680
[Guest]: So I've said that in the footnote, which is that, you know, Edward, I think it's an Edward

03:06:56.680 --> 03:07:00.640
[Guest]: Haynes essay, where I've said Haynes has not revealed who this is because he says it's

03:07:00.640 --> 03:07:01.640
[Guest]: defamatory.

03:07:01.640 --> 03:07:02.640
[Guest]: But it's interesting.

03:07:02.640 --> 03:07:06.180
[Guest]: I mean, obviously Haynes is a respected scholar, so it's very likely he got it from a series.

03:07:06.180 --> 03:07:09.840
[Guest]: So somewhere in the archives, there must be a letter where a resident suspects that, hold

03:07:09.840 --> 03:07:12.080
[Guest]: on, there's something wrong with this Raja.

03:07:12.080 --> 03:07:15.760
[Guest]: The poor, that Kolhapur Maharaja I mentioned, the poor chap who was beaten to death by his

03:07:15.760 --> 03:07:16.760
[Guest]: British warden.

03:07:16.760 --> 03:07:20.520
[Guest]: At one time, he ran away on a bullock cart pretending to be a car driver because he was

03:07:20.520 --> 03:07:25.880
[Guest]: so tortured and traumatized by these British tutors that had been appointed to take care

03:07:25.880 --> 03:07:26.880
[Guest]: of him.

03:07:26.880 --> 03:07:27.880
[Guest]: He ran away.

03:07:27.880 --> 03:07:30.000
[Guest]: You know, his mental health was in tatters.

03:07:30.000 --> 03:07:32.000
[Guest]: And you know, it's sad.

03:07:32.000 --> 03:07:37.240
[Guest]: Not all of them, like Sayajirao survived the tutoring of the British and became a strong

03:07:37.240 --> 03:07:38.240
[Guest]: man.

03:07:38.240 --> 03:07:41.840
[Guest]: This guy was a contemporary of Sayajirao, same age, but he completely crumbled and ended

03:07:41.840 --> 03:07:45.760
[Guest]: up dying as a young boy because he couldn't withstand the pressure.

03:07:45.760 --> 03:07:48.760
[Guest]: So the British could be very, very cruel to people.

03:07:48.760 --> 03:07:51.960
[Guest]: In Pudukottai, the Rani, for example, this is where Shesha Yashastri and the British

03:07:51.960 --> 03:07:53.200
[Guest]: sort of united.

03:07:53.200 --> 03:07:57.560
[Guest]: The British frowned on Rani's because the Rani's harems were out of control of access

03:07:57.560 --> 03:07:59.040
[Guest]: for the British resident.

03:07:59.040 --> 03:08:01.960
[Guest]: Even in Darbar, they could take control of, they could amend ritual.

03:08:01.960 --> 03:08:03.000
[Guest]: But the harem is sealed.

03:08:03.000 --> 03:08:04.000
[Guest]: It's closed.

03:08:04.000 --> 03:08:05.480
[Guest]: You cannot enter as a white man.

03:08:05.480 --> 03:08:08.800
[Guest]: So they always tried to get rid of the power of the women in the harem.

03:08:08.800 --> 03:08:12.280
[Guest]: So they saw that as illicit power, illegal power, slander.

03:08:12.280 --> 03:08:14.920
[Guest]: These women are saying they're constantly intriguing and plotting.

03:08:14.920 --> 03:08:17.840
[Guest]: But in reality, the women saw the harem as a political space.

03:08:17.840 --> 03:08:21.880
[Guest]: The harem had a legitimate right to advise the king and try and amend policy.

03:08:21.880 --> 03:08:24.880
[Guest]: Shesha Yashastri doesn't like it either because he's a Devan who's an autocrat.

03:08:24.880 --> 03:08:26.420
[Guest]: He likes power in his hands.

03:08:26.420 --> 03:08:29.960
[Guest]: He thinks, as I said, he has a savior complex about reforming and improving and saving the

03:08:29.960 --> 03:08:30.960
[Guest]: state.

03:08:30.960 --> 03:08:33.640
[Guest]: But the Rani and Shesha Yashastri also sort of have issues.

03:08:33.640 --> 03:08:37.800
[Guest]: At one point, she has a sacrifice of cobras because she's trying to get rid of him through

03:08:37.800 --> 03:08:38.800
[Guest]: black magic.

03:08:38.800 --> 03:08:40.600
[Guest]: And he's like, ha ha, no, none of this is going to work.

03:08:40.600 --> 03:08:43.900
[Guest]: This is going to end up making you look worse in the eyes of the British.

03:08:43.900 --> 03:08:49.240
[Guest]: He cuts off access from the harem to the royal bedchamber, to the boy Maharaja's chambers.

03:08:49.240 --> 03:08:53.240
[Guest]: The Devadasis who serve the women, they're actually, Shesha Yashastri doesn't like them

03:08:53.240 --> 03:08:55.280
[Guest]: because the Victorians don't like Devadasis.

03:08:55.280 --> 03:08:58.640
[Guest]: But in reality, the Devadasis are a source of intelligence for the Rani's.

03:08:58.640 --> 03:09:01.920
[Guest]: They tell, they are not parda women, Devadasis can move everywhere.

03:09:01.920 --> 03:09:04.200
[Guest]: They're dancing girls in the court, in the temple.

03:09:04.200 --> 03:09:07.520
[Guest]: They're hearing what the people are saying and they're overhearing conversations in court.

03:09:07.520 --> 03:09:09.000
[Guest]: They report this to the Rani.

03:09:09.000 --> 03:09:13.400
[Guest]: So the Rani's are not surrounded by, you know, the wrong type of women as Shesha Yashastri

03:09:13.400 --> 03:09:14.400
[Guest]: thinks.

03:09:14.400 --> 03:09:17.320
[Guest]: They've actually got a network of informants, which he's cutting off.

03:09:17.320 --> 03:09:20.880
[Guest]: So all of these things, even an intervention of the harem and preventing Devadasis from

03:09:20.880 --> 03:09:22.780
[Guest]: entering is a political act.

03:09:22.780 --> 03:09:25.200
[Guest]: It is about saying, you are a woman, your job is not political.

03:09:25.200 --> 03:09:27.840
[Guest]: You sit in the harem and serve the king in the bedchamber.

03:09:27.840 --> 03:09:31.920
[Guest]: You will not get involved in politics and I will cut off all sources of political information

03:09:31.920 --> 03:09:32.920
[Guest]: from you.

03:09:32.920 --> 03:09:36.380
[Guest]: That's why I said, as you peel back the layers, you start realising that all these things

03:09:36.380 --> 03:09:37.440
[Guest]: have meaning.

03:09:37.440 --> 03:09:41.040
[Guest]: What the British sort of played down saying, oh, you know, foolish Rani surrounded by Devadasis.

03:09:41.040 --> 03:09:44.440
[Guest]: No, she's surrounded by a network of informants who are telling her what's happening in the

03:09:44.440 --> 03:09:45.480
[Guest]: kingdom.

03:09:45.480 --> 03:09:50.200
[Amit Varma]: And as you describe, what Shashtri also does is that he installs his own nephew as a tutor.

03:09:50.200 --> 03:09:51.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, as a junior tutor.

03:09:51.600 --> 03:09:52.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:09:52.600 --> 03:09:56.400
[Amit Varma]: And his own nephew is supposed to be like a smaller mirror image of his, which I found

03:09:56.400 --> 03:09:57.400
[Amit Varma]: quite funny.

03:09:57.400 --> 03:10:01.800
[Amit Varma]: You know, the future Raja at that time, Martanda Bhairav, he is also such a fascinating character

03:10:01.800 --> 03:10:04.840
[Amit Varma]: that he can't, you know, he can't find an Indian woman he likes.

03:10:04.840 --> 03:10:08.160
[Amit Varma]: So he marries this Australian, he meets in a hotel, Mollie Fink, who's called Mollie

03:10:08.160 --> 03:10:09.160
[Amit Varma]: Fink.

03:10:09.160 --> 03:10:10.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:10:10.160 --> 03:10:11.960
[Amit Varma]: When the king hears of this, he says, what kind of name is Mollie Fink?

03:10:11.960 --> 03:10:16.720
[Guest]: Firstly, a Raja marrying an Australian woman was quite scandalous at that time.

03:10:16.720 --> 03:10:19.720
[Guest]: And this guy, he actually gives a speech where he says, you know, because of the way I've

03:10:19.720 --> 03:10:22.680
[Guest]: been brought up and I'm so cosmopolitan, etc.

03:10:22.680 --> 03:10:26.040
[Guest]: He's basically taking a jab at the British because they've raised him to be this very

03:10:26.040 --> 03:10:27.560
[Guest]: cosmopolitan figure.

03:10:27.560 --> 03:10:30.960
[Guest]: He's basically saying, you've made me so cosmopolitan that I must have a white wife.

03:10:30.960 --> 03:10:33.120
[Guest]: I cannot have any local wife.

03:10:33.120 --> 03:10:35.560
[Guest]: You know, these were things the British were horrified at.

03:10:35.560 --> 03:10:39.880
[Guest]: Indian Maharajas having white Ranis, because it opened up all kinds of issues, you know,

03:10:39.880 --> 03:10:43.200
[Guest]: half-breed prince, you know, would he be able to succeed to the throne?

03:10:43.200 --> 03:10:45.400
[Guest]: Would he be a Hindu or would he be a Christian?

03:10:45.400 --> 03:10:47.120
[Guest]: Questions the British had no interest in dealing with.

03:10:47.120 --> 03:10:51.120
[Guest]: Plus, of course, pure racism, you know, a white man marrying a brown woman is fine.

03:10:51.120 --> 03:10:56.000
[Guest]: A brown man, even if he's a king, marrying a white woman was a huge threat in that time.

03:10:56.000 --> 03:11:02.040
[Amit Varma]: And you describe Shastri's dilemma also very well, that dilemma of conservatism versus

03:11:02.040 --> 03:11:06.720
[Amit Varma]: patriotism, which would have been, I think, a dilemma that so many people would have had

03:11:06.720 --> 03:11:08.920
[Amit Varma]: to face within themselves, right?

03:11:08.920 --> 03:11:14.680
[Amit Varma]: Not just Shastri, but even I think all our early liberal leaders from Ranade to Gokhale

03:11:14.680 --> 03:11:19.200
[Amit Varma]: to whatever would have kind of been trapped within that, that you want to kind of maintain

03:11:19.200 --> 03:11:21.520
[Amit Varma]: the order of things, the way in which things have worked.

03:11:21.520 --> 03:11:22.520
[Amit Varma]: You don't want chaos.

03:11:22.520 --> 03:11:25.800
[Amit Varma]: You don't want anarchy to be loosed upon the world.

03:11:25.800 --> 03:11:31.240
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, you know, you get the sense of this larger cause that is kind of

03:11:31.240 --> 03:11:32.240
[Amit Varma]: coming.

03:11:32.240 --> 03:11:36.320
[Amit Varma]: You've already spoken at Baroda about length, your fourth chapter is about that, which is

03:11:36.320 --> 03:11:41.360
[Amit Varma]: really quite superb and should be a long, long web series, you know.

03:11:41.360 --> 03:11:46.360
[Amit Varma]: So I would just not want to go through your entire book in detail, because one, we can't.

03:11:46.360 --> 03:11:47.360
[Amit Varma]: It's a book with so much detail.

03:11:47.360 --> 03:11:52.360
[Amit Varma]: And two, I'd just like readers to pick up the book for themselves.

03:11:52.360 --> 03:11:59.080
[Amit Varma]: So some broad parting questions, in terms of your historical inquiry, what sort of interests

03:11:59.080 --> 03:12:00.080
[Amit Varma]: you?

03:12:00.080 --> 03:12:01.080
[Amit Varma]: Like one, obviously, is Kerala.

03:12:01.080 --> 03:12:02.760
[Amit Varma]: You start with that urge that this is where I come from.

03:12:02.760 --> 03:12:05.300
[Amit Varma]: These characters that I've heard about are so interesting.

03:12:05.300 --> 03:12:06.620
[Amit Varma]: Let me find out more.

03:12:06.620 --> 03:12:09.960
[Amit Varma]: And then because you're in Pune, because you're in Maharashtra, that whole Deccan period,

03:12:09.960 --> 03:12:13.800
[Amit Varma]: which no one talks about, which is neither the Mughals nor Shivaji.

03:12:13.800 --> 03:12:17.720
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and all of this, in a sense, is a continuation of that.

03:12:17.720 --> 03:12:19.000
[Amit Varma]: But what drives you for the future?

03:12:19.000 --> 03:12:23.880
[Amit Varma]: Like are there currents of history which interest you more than others?

03:12:23.880 --> 03:12:27.720
[Amit Varma]: Are there personalities which interest you more than others, figures which interest you

03:12:27.720 --> 03:12:28.720
[Amit Varma]: more than others?

03:12:28.720 --> 03:12:30.440
[Amit Varma]: What can we expect from you in times to come?

03:12:30.440 --> 03:12:34.120
[Guest]: The common theme is just all these subjects are marginalized in one way or the other.

03:12:34.120 --> 03:12:38.080
[Guest]: You know, we often think of marginalization through a prism of class, which is that marginalized

03:12:38.080 --> 03:12:39.840
[Guest]: must be lower class people.

03:12:39.840 --> 03:12:43.400
[Guest]: But in reality, the princely states are a marginalized historical subject.

03:12:43.400 --> 03:12:48.000
[Guest]: You know, the Maharani of Trivandrum in the first book was a marginalized historical figure.

03:12:48.000 --> 03:12:52.680
[Guest]: The Deccan is marginalized under these towering figures like Shivaji, Aurangzeb, the Mughals

03:12:52.680 --> 03:12:53.680
[Guest]: and so on.

03:12:53.680 --> 03:12:54.960
[Guest]: That's also been marginalized.

03:12:54.960 --> 03:12:59.920
[Guest]: So for me, it's always these stories that somehow are fascinating, but not enough people

03:12:59.920 --> 03:13:01.920
[Guest]: have made an effort to tell those stories.

03:13:01.920 --> 03:13:04.320
[Guest]: Not enough people have tried to bring that into the limelight.

03:13:04.320 --> 03:13:09.520
[Guest]: That really is what motivates me and sort of drives me to research on things that, you

03:13:09.520 --> 03:13:13.600
[Guest]: know, are slightly different, and which I feel deserve greater attention.

03:13:13.600 --> 03:13:16.520
[Guest]: As I said, you know, the princely states are so fascinating.

03:13:16.520 --> 03:13:20.480
[Guest]: To really reduce them to this cliche of elephant and dancing girls is quite tragic, because

03:13:20.480 --> 03:13:24.360
[Guest]: not only does it do an injustice in the fact that, as I said, 40% of the country was under

03:13:24.360 --> 03:13:25.480
[Guest]: princely rulers.

03:13:25.480 --> 03:13:30.720
[Guest]: So essentially erasing or eclipsing 40% of the territory and its internal histories from

03:13:30.720 --> 03:13:35.920
[Guest]: what we call modern Indian history, even in understanding how Indian political structures

03:13:35.920 --> 03:13:40.960
[Guest]: adapted to modernity and colonialism, how Indian political figures dealt with colonialism,

03:13:40.960 --> 03:13:45.080
[Guest]: it wasn't just Gandhiji and his satyagraha, it wasn't just Dadabhai Naoroji and his economic

03:13:45.080 --> 03:13:46.080
[Guest]: drain theory.

03:13:46.080 --> 03:13:50.400
[Guest]: There was also multiple other characters in that same time, each of them trying to find

03:13:50.400 --> 03:13:52.360
[Guest]: a different answer to the same question.

03:13:52.360 --> 03:13:56.360
[Guest]: Ultimately, one answer may have triumphed and become the big answer, but there were

03:13:56.360 --> 03:13:59.480
[Guest]: other people trying to find solutions to the same problem.

03:13:59.480 --> 03:14:04.120
[Guest]: And I think 70 years after independence, we should start looking at these stories, just

03:14:04.120 --> 03:14:07.800
[Guest]: because they're so fascinating and interesting, and they tell you about the political conundrums

03:14:07.800 --> 03:14:12.740
[Guest]: people face, the political questions people have to grapple with, the contradictory impulses

03:14:12.740 --> 03:14:13.740
[Guest]: they feel.

03:14:13.740 --> 03:14:18.680
[Guest]: You mentioned Sheshasastri, conservative because he's a Brahmin man, an upper caste Brahmin,

03:14:18.680 --> 03:14:22.840
[Guest]: English educated man, but also a moderniser in terms of he wants roads and bridges, etc,

03:14:22.840 --> 03:14:24.640
[Guest]: but not too much social reform.

03:14:24.640 --> 03:14:28.920
[Guest]: These tell you about the kind of internal battles that human beings have, how human

03:14:28.920 --> 03:14:31.360
[Guest]: beings are also flawed, even the greatest of them are flawed.

03:14:31.360 --> 03:14:35.040
[Guest]: There are issues, they have their prejudices, they are also creatures of their time.

03:14:35.040 --> 03:14:39.720
[Guest]: And frankly, in today's sometimes ultra-woke times, I think it also helps suggest that

03:14:39.720 --> 03:14:43.720
[Guest]: we should treat people with more sympathy because people are complex, people are not

03:14:43.720 --> 03:14:48.640
[Guest]: perfect ideal versions of what they ought to be, people have a mix of emotions and we

03:14:48.640 --> 03:14:51.080
[Guest]: should have the maturity to deal with it that way.

03:14:51.080 --> 03:14:55.680
[Guest]: Same with history, it's not about saying were the Maharajas good or were the Maharajas bad,

03:14:55.680 --> 03:14:57.320
[Guest]: that's not what is interesting to me.

03:14:57.320 --> 03:15:00.120
[Guest]: The interesting thing is, what were the Maharajas?

03:15:00.120 --> 03:15:02.360
[Guest]: Even if they had elephants, what does the elephant represent?

03:15:02.360 --> 03:15:05.640
[Guest]: Even if there are 20 dancing girls, why are the dancing girls there?

03:15:05.640 --> 03:15:08.320
[Guest]: What is this court ritual supposed to represent?

03:15:08.320 --> 03:15:11.960
[Guest]: Those questions are something we should investigate, instead of simply saying, oh elephants, dancing

03:15:11.960 --> 03:15:15.280
[Guest]: girls, not interesting, they didn't contribute anything, bye bye.

03:15:15.280 --> 03:15:19.360
[Guest]: Everything if you ask a question of it will throw up some fascinating answers and in many

03:15:19.360 --> 03:15:24.440
[Guest]: ways complicate our understanding of things like nationalism, the evolution of India as

03:15:24.440 --> 03:15:28.240
[Guest]: an idea and many of the big questions of history.

03:15:28.240 --> 03:15:33.660
[Guest]: This may not be the answer to it, but it will shed some more light in explaining what those

03:15:33.660 --> 03:15:34.660
[Amit Varma]: answers are.

03:15:34.660 --> 03:15:39.200
[Amit Varma]: I think rather than use the term complicate our understanding, I'd say deepen our understanding.

03:15:39.200 --> 03:15:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And of course, as a reader, I share that fascination for A, marginalized characters, B, characters

03:15:44.000 --> 03:15:48.640
[Amit Varma]: which defy a simple narrative, where you're kind of exploring the multitudes that I talk

03:15:48.640 --> 03:15:51.060
[Amit Varma]: about in my show, unpeeling those layers.

03:15:51.060 --> 03:15:55.160
[Amit Varma]: And like I look at contemporary times, and we of course have more people alive today

03:15:55.160 --> 03:16:00.720
[Amit Varma]: than ever before, just in sample size of things that are happening, there is so much more,

03:16:00.720 --> 03:16:05.800
[Amit Varma]: say in any 10 year period, than say a 100 year period from the past, there are so many

03:16:05.800 --> 03:16:10.720
[Amit Varma]: histories kind of taking place in real time, there are stories of the marginalized to be

03:16:10.720 --> 03:16:14.520
[Amit Varma]: told here as well layers to uncover and all of that.

03:16:14.520 --> 03:16:18.960
[Amit Varma]: So when you sort of think of current times, and when you think of history, one, is it

03:16:18.960 --> 03:16:24.400
[Amit Varma]: only what you consider historical that is already sort of there is something fixed and

03:16:24.400 --> 03:16:28.320
[Amit Varma]: you can go back and you can uncover layers of it that interests you, or are you also

03:16:28.320 --> 03:16:30.680
[Amit Varma]: interested in contemporary stories?

03:16:30.680 --> 03:16:35.440
[Amit Varma]: And whatever the answer to that is, what would you say is the dividing line for you?

03:16:35.440 --> 03:16:40.360
[Amit Varma]: Like after what point in time, are you really not interested in kind of getting into that?

03:16:40.360 --> 03:16:45.120
[Amit Varma]: Or is it because there is such a surfeit of material available around you today that you're

03:16:45.120 --> 03:16:48.560
[Amit Varma]: like enough people to do that, you know, let me write about the Deccan in 1800.

03:16:48.560 --> 03:16:52.600
[Guest]: The present, on its own terms, doesn't interest me that much, frankly, for that you have good

03:16:52.600 --> 03:16:55.520
[Guest]: journalists who are going out and putting those stories out there.

03:16:55.520 --> 03:16:59.800
[Guest]: What interests me is perhaps making sense of why the present is in its current shape

03:16:59.800 --> 03:17:00.800
[Guest]: by looking at the past.

03:17:00.800 --> 03:17:05.560
[Guest]: So in that sense, if I had a cut off, I would say 1947, you know, independence, for me,

03:17:05.560 --> 03:17:09.560
[Guest]: I'm interested in the period before that really the modern period 18th century till the mid

03:17:09.560 --> 03:17:12.760
[Guest]: 20th century, perhaps a little bit longer into the 20th century.

03:17:12.760 --> 03:17:16.440
[Guest]: But that is my face because I see a lot of our current political institutions, a lot

03:17:16.440 --> 03:17:20.880
[Guest]: of the ideas, a lot of the historical experiences that has made us the people we are with our

03:17:20.880 --> 03:17:22.800
[Guest]: strengths, but also our insecurities.

03:17:22.800 --> 03:17:27.960
[Guest]: A lot of the reason the map of India is the way it is, a lot of this depends on events

03:17:27.960 --> 03:17:32.080
[Guest]: that happened in these centuries, of course, the other centuries have had an impact.

03:17:32.080 --> 03:17:34.800
[Guest]: But practically speaking, this is what appeals to me.

03:17:34.800 --> 03:17:36.800
[Guest]: And I want to keep working on that.

03:17:36.800 --> 03:17:42.600
[Guest]: The present in its own right, my skill set is not adequate for sort of unravelling that,

03:17:42.600 --> 03:17:46.600
[Guest]: that I think you have journalists and people who can go into the story and dig them out.

03:17:46.600 --> 03:17:51.320
[Guest]: I would rather dig out things from a different time and try and make sense of the present,

03:17:51.320 --> 03:17:56.800
[Guest]: you know, by explaining why those times have resulted in this system that we have now.

03:17:56.800 --> 03:18:00.360
[Amit Varma]: So on that note, while we are shaped by what happened, we are also shaped by what we think

03:18:00.360 --> 03:18:04.960
[Amit Varma]: happened, right, which is all of these kind of narratives that are all around us and are

03:18:04.960 --> 03:18:05.960
[Amit Varma]: fighting us.

03:18:05.960 --> 03:18:09.920
[Amit Varma]: And I think we brought this up at the start of the episode that we are, you know, there

03:18:09.920 --> 03:18:11.560
[Amit Varma]: is narrative warfare all around us.

03:18:11.560 --> 03:18:13.040
[Amit Varma]: How much does history really matter?

03:18:13.040 --> 03:18:18.280
[Amit Varma]: How much does it matter what actually happened or how many people Akbar may have slaughtered

03:18:18.280 --> 03:18:20.880
[Amit Varma]: or how many temples Aurangzeb may have built?

03:18:20.880 --> 03:18:23.920
[Amit Varma]: To me, at one level, it should not matter at all.

03:18:23.920 --> 03:18:27.640
[Amit Varma]: And yet it is these narratives that seem to matter and not history itself.

03:18:27.640 --> 03:18:31.960
[Guest]: Do you sometimes think that this is an insurmountable battle to fight?

03:18:31.960 --> 03:18:33.720
[Guest]: All of history is frankly about narratives, right?

03:18:33.720 --> 03:18:34.720
[Guest]: It is about narratives.

03:18:34.720 --> 03:18:38.840
[Guest]: When I talk about the princely states, they were marginalised because of a British narrative.

03:18:38.840 --> 03:18:43.360
[Guest]: You know, everything ultimately is about how we make sense of the past.

03:18:43.360 --> 03:18:47.560
[Guest]: And this is not just our generation, all generations try to link themselves to the past.

03:18:47.560 --> 03:18:51.560
[Guest]: When a king, you know, crowns himself and then claims he is a long lost descendant of

03:18:51.560 --> 03:18:55.960
[Guest]: Arjuna or Krishna or whatever, he is connecting himself to something that is recognised as

03:18:55.960 --> 03:18:58.040
[Guest]: supreme and wonderful and great.

03:18:58.040 --> 03:19:02.320
[Guest]: All of history is about narratives and this sort of constant conversation and battle between

03:19:02.320 --> 03:19:07.400
[Guest]: narratives to say which one or the other defines not just the present but what shape the future

03:19:07.400 --> 03:19:08.400
[Guest]: will take.

03:19:08.400 --> 03:19:13.280
[Guest]: You know, the current government has a huge interest and investment in shaping a historical

03:19:13.280 --> 03:19:17.000
[Guest]: narrative because that will enable them to guide and shape the future.

03:19:17.000 --> 03:19:19.560
[Guest]: So the three are in some ways linked that way.

03:19:19.560 --> 03:19:22.960
[Guest]: But you know, I'll just end on one quote by Srinath Raghavan which I think he said in

03:19:22.960 --> 03:19:27.800
[Guest]: a print interview but it's a very wise line and I think it teaches historians also humility

03:19:27.800 --> 03:19:32.480
[Guest]: and a certain amount of modesty which is that history does not teach any lessons, historians

03:19:32.480 --> 03:19:33.480
[Guest]: do.

03:19:33.480 --> 03:19:37.240
[Guest]: And I think that's a wonderful line and you know, it teaches us that at the end of the

03:19:37.240 --> 03:19:39.960
[Guest]: day we are also in the business of narratives.

03:19:39.960 --> 03:19:43.000
[Guest]: I never make the claim that I've uncovered the truth, you know.

03:19:43.000 --> 03:19:47.600
[Guest]: I have uncovered certain evidence, certain things, I have connected the dots and said

03:19:47.600 --> 03:19:50.440
[Guest]: that this is why this happened and these are the things that happened.

03:19:50.440 --> 03:19:52.600
[Guest]: But it is my narrative ultimately.

03:19:52.600 --> 03:19:56.960
[Guest]: I am by no means claiming that this is some kind of truth that will never change in time.

03:19:56.960 --> 03:20:03.000
[Guest]: In future, somebody else may counter my version of events with another reading of history.

03:20:03.000 --> 03:20:04.000
[Unknown]: And that's perfectly fine.

03:20:04.000 --> 03:20:08.560
[Guest]: History, you know, recently somebody invited me for a debate, I couldn't participate saying

03:20:08.560 --> 03:20:11.680
[Guest]: should history be rewritten and it struck me in my head that history is always being

03:20:11.680 --> 03:20:12.680
[Guest]: rewritten.

03:20:12.680 --> 03:20:17.000
[Guest]: You know, politicians writing it is one thing, that is political football that they are sort

03:20:17.000 --> 03:20:18.120
[Guest]: of kicking around.

03:20:18.120 --> 03:20:24.160
[Guest]: But history is about the past being constantly rewritten, retold, revisited, reanalyzed.

03:20:24.160 --> 03:20:25.800
[Guest]: That is exactly what history is about.

03:20:25.800 --> 03:20:29.960
[Guest]: So to say should Indian history be rewritten is kind of redundant because it's always being

03:20:29.960 --> 03:20:30.960
[Amit Varma]: rewritten.

03:20:30.960 --> 03:20:34.560
[Amit Varma]: I saw an ad on Twitter for that and I thought the question was kind of vague.

03:20:34.560 --> 03:20:39.480
[Amit Varma]: But either ways, you know, I mean, whether history is rewritten or not, history should

03:20:39.480 --> 03:20:44.360
[Amit Varma]: at least be read and you make it easy to do that with your wonderful narratives and incredible

03:20:44.360 --> 03:20:45.360
[Amit Varma]: storytelling.

03:20:45.360 --> 03:20:48.680
[Amit Varma]: So thank you so much for your time and insights today and for coming all the way to Andheri

03:20:48.680 --> 03:20:49.680
[Amit Varma]: from Pune.

03:20:49.680 --> 03:20:52.680
[Amit Varma]: Although you didn't come just for this, but thank you anyway.

03:20:52.680 --> 03:20:54.360
[Amit Varma]: And thank you for writing these great books.

03:20:54.360 --> 03:20:55.360
[Guest]: More power to you.

03:20:55.360 --> 03:20:58.400
[Guest]: Thank you for having me for the fourth time on your podcast.

03:20:58.400 --> 03:21:02.600
[Guest]: Hopefully this is longer than my first longest episode.

